 (35,'The intricate columns and façade of the New York State Education Building.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (36,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As the capital of New York, there are numerous museums dedicated to the history of the great state. The Albany Institute of History & Art is dedicated to works by local Albany artists and artists from the famed Hudson River School. For those interested in the history of the state, the New York State Museum over in Empire State Plaza hosts exhibits and displays collections of historical and cultural artifacts. The New York State Capitol Building on State Street is home to New York\''s government and is open daily for free guided tours. The historic homes of Ten Broeck, Cherry Hill and Schuyler mansions offer a glimpse into Albany\''s past through the great families who built the city. For the military buffs, the World War II destroyer ship, USS Slater, is available for tours as it sits docked along the Hudson.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Family Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As a NASA Space Place, the Henry Hudson Planetarium at the Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center enjoys plenty of school gatherings as well as family outings. In other nearby regions, there is the Adirondack Museum with hands-on exhibits dedicated to the preservation and understanding of the Adirondack region\''s habitats. No trip to the area is complete without a stop in Cooperstown at the National Baseball Hall of Fame & Museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Palace Performing Arts Center on North Pearl Street is home to the city\''s main theater events with tours of big Broadway shows, comedy performances and classic-movie screenings. The Palace is also home to the Albany Symphony Orchestra which calls two other venues of the area home: the Troy Savings Bank Music Hall in Troy and the Canfield Casino in Saratoga Springs. The Capital Repertory Theatre also on North Pearl Street has independent and off-Broadway shows their intimate venue. The Egg over at Empire State Plaza (thus named for its egg shape) hosts a variety of music, dance and family performances at this unique theater. On Hudson Avenue is the eba Dance Theater, a dance school with a professional touring company that is a popular community dance and theater space.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Comedy</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If comedy is more your thing, The Comedy Works on State Street hosts comedy shows and comedians from around the country in a small club close to the New York Capital. At the Crossgates Mall, the comedians at the  Albany Funny Bone will have you clutching your sides with laughter.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are several modern movie theaters in Albany, the majority of them located outside the Downtown area. The Regal Colonie Center Stadium 13 and Regal Crossgates Stadium 18 have stadium seating, trendy concessions and are located in two of the region\''s best-loved malls. If you like watching re-runs of Hollywood\''s classics and other family favorites, The Palace has screenings of films like <em>The Wizard of Oz</em>, <em>Citizen Kane</em> and <em>Casablanca</em>.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Times Union Center in the heart of Downtown is the largest venue for big sporting events, like MAAC Basketball Championship games, ECAC Hockey Championships, Siena College\''s Saints basketball team, and the AHL\''s Albany River Rats. The Washington Avenue Armory is home to many cultural and sporting events, and it is home to the Albany Patroons, a Continental Basketball Association (CBA) American Division team. Albany is also home to the New York Giants\'' summer training camp, so chances are you can see some of the season\''s biggest names for low prices while they are in town.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are plenty of open green spaces in Albany. The multi-million dollar project of revitalizing the Hudson River Way and Riverfront Park has created one of the loveliest walkways around, especially with the comfortable amphitheater that overlooks the water. To the west of Empire State Plaza along Delaware Avenue is Lincoln Park, an enjoyable place in the summer with its large outdoor pool or in the winter with its cross-country skiing and snowshoe trails. In Washington Park, there are many places to walk around, bike or have a picnic. During the summer months, enjoy a show at the Park Playhouse.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Over on Lark Street and Downtown towards the River are a majority of the city\''s popular nighttime hangouts. Café Hollywood has retro jukebox where you can pick your favorite tunes and the Lark Tavern is a great place to catch live music, hang out with friends or try a microbrew. If you like your cuisine farm fresh and your drafts regional, then the New World Bistro Bar is an excellent place to spend an evening. Great modern Mexican food combined with a fantastic array of tequilas are to be had at the art-covered Ama Cocina. For the LGBT crowd, Albany has a few good options like the Oh Bar on Lark Street and a perennial favorite, the Rocks.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (37,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Capitol Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This area is home to the ultra-modern public space of the Governor Nelson A. Rockefeller Empire State Plaza (usually shortened to simply Empire State Plaza), the New York State Capitol Building, and the Alfred E. Smith Building. The central part of the city known as Midtown is booming with over 12,000 government employees who fill this 96-acre (39-hectare) area on weekdays, and with visitors galore at nighttime during performances at The Egg.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The area around Broadway by the Hudson is the site of the first Dutch settlement in Albany. Unfortunately, none of the 17th-century buildings remain. However, there are other historical buildings in the area, including the 1915 Delaware and Hudson, or D&H Buildings, which were originally constructed to hide the factories and incoming ships into the port of Albany. Today, the D&H Building is headquarters of the State University of New York (SUNY) College system. The Hudson River Way and Riverfront Park have been part of an enormous revitalization project by introducing tree-lined walking and cycling paths as well as an 800-seat amphitheater that overlooks the Hudson. One reason most people come to this part of the city is to attend sporting events, concerts and conventions at the Times Union Center.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lark Street: Center Square & Hudson/Park</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Situated right behind Empire State Plaza are the two neighborhoods of Center Square and Hudson/Park. Intersecting the two is the popular Lark Street Business Improvement District. This unique seven-block strip from Washington Avenue to Delaware Avenue has everything you need, day or night. During the day, there are small bookstores, interesting knickknack shops, restaurants, eclectic bars and minimal chain outlets (just Ben & Jerry\''s and Dunkin\'' Donuts). Lark Street is also home to LarkFEST in September and Capital Pride in the month of June. These two districts are full of beautifully maintained, mid-19th-century townhouses.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Mansion</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This small, scenic area borders Capitol Hill and is named for the New York State Executive Mansion that is located here at Eagle Street. You will not find many places to eat, shops or anything of that nature in this area, but it\''s a popular residential area with lovely homes that are easily accessible from Empire State Plaza.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pastures</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Another residential area that goes down to the Hudson is the historic district of Pastures with its Federal-style houses, which has been on the National Register of Historical Places since 1972. During the 17th Century, the area was just that - pastures. Although the neighborhood fell into disrepair for many years with derelict houses and unkempt public grounds, Pastures is currently experiencing urban revitalization thanks to the nearby Albany Housing Authority and the introduction of tennis courts, a children\''s playground and efforts to tidy up the buildings and sidewalks.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Arbor Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This neighborhood is located in the hilly northern part of Albany and is where you can easily find gorgeous 19th-century homes that have been restored to their former glory. The Palace Theatre, a former RKO movie house on the corner of North Pearl and Clinton Avenues, which opened in 1931 and closed in 1969. Thanks to new owners interested in its preservation, The Palace underwent an enormous restoration project and has reopened as the home of the Albany Symphony Orchestra. The Palace also hosts numerous music events and screenings of classic films.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ten Broeck Triangle</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">So named for the small triangle of streets that surround the Ten Broeck Mansion, the Ten Broeck Triangle Historic District is a residential section filled with pre-Civil War townhouses. The Mansion on the hillside was built in 1798 and is home to the Albany County Historical Association.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cherry Hill & Krank Park</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">At the far end of Albany, there are two other historic residences, Cherry Hill (1787) and the Schuyler Mansion (1762). The Georgian-style Cherry Hill was occupied until 1963 when its owner Catherine Rankin passed away. The home was also where an infamous love triangle murder took place in 1827, which resulted in a closely-followed and well-publicized trial. Home to Revolutionary War hero Philip Schuyler and his wife Catherine Van Rensselaer, the Schuyler Mansion is a great example of Georgian brick design and one of the best mansions to visit in the area. Tours of both historic houses are available.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
