 (65,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Rembrandt, Van Gogh, Vermeer and Frans Hals, the Old and Great Masters of Holland, are just a few of the highlights of the city\''s artistic legacy. Amsterdam has some of the finest art museums in Europe, ranging from conventional to eccentric. No matter your interests, there\''s bound to be something to grab your attention at one of the city\''s museums. The majority of museums are placed within a short range of one another, allowing travelers to easily walk from one to the next.Many of Rembrandt, Vermeer and Frans Hals\'' finest works are part of the national heritage and housed in the Rijksmuseum. Take your time in this beautiful museum, as it sports a massive collection of permanent exhibitions and temporary shows that demand more than just an hour. Rembrandt\''s paintings are also found in abundance in Rembrandthuis. The life and works of Van Gogh can be found in the sprawling Van Gogh Museum. For modern art, tour the exhibitions in the Stedelijk Museum. It may also be worth your while to explore the many private galleries around Amsterdam, especially those that have been a longstanding fixture in the city\''s arts scene. These include the centrally located Annet Gelink Galler, the Galerie Fons Welters, the Upstream Gallery, and the Reflex Modern Art Gallery located across from the Rijksmuseum.  If you\''re interested in science and interactive entertainment, don\''t miss Science Center NEMO, designed specifically for children with numerous hands-on exhibits and technological wonders. The Scheepvaartmuseum is perfect for travelers interested in the country\''s significant maritime and nautical history. Nature lovers should visit the Hortus Botanicus Amsterdam, which contains over six thousand different kinds of plants.In a city with a past as lengthy as Amsterdam, historical museums are found in abundance. One of the best is Amsterdamse Historisch Museum, where you will learn about the city\''s developments from the 13th Century to the present day. The world-famous Anne Frank House is one of the city\''s most noteworthy attractions, recently expanded to accommodate the attraction\''s increasing popularity among visitors.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam\''s cinema repertoire has grown a great deal in the past few years, and the city offers a diverse selection of both Hollywood blockbusters and European releases. Movie options are divided into two main categories: popular cinemas (with high-profile international films) and <em>filmhuizen</em> (art houses), where art films, documentaries and retrospectives are shown. The Movies, with its extravagant interior, is a great place to visit for regional selections and lesser-known art films, as is the Cinecenter, another indie film spot in the city. The FilmHallen, tucked away in Haarlemmerdijk, shows a bevy of restored classical films, alongside several unreleased and rare movies. The EYE Film Institute boasts of a similar agenda, with a mix of both Dutch and foreign films thrown in. A few other cinema houses include the historic Rialto and De Balie.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam hosts many theatrical events, with more productions in English than in Dutch. The De Parade is a prelude to the theater season, beginning at the end of summer and showcasing several days of performing arts, food and drink. One of the most important theater venues is the Koninklijk Theater Carré. The building was once home to a circus, but now houses a beautiful theater by the Amstel Canal with a wide variety of contemporary national and international productions. Amsterdam\''s dance culture is just as lively as its theater community. Amsterdam\''s main theater for viewing dance performances is Het Nationale Ballet. Aside from these established companies, there are several independent and amateur organizations that put on shows intermittently throughout the city\''s performing arts spaces.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam has a lively music scene, with scores of festivals, events, and numerous concerts in the city\''s various venues. Offering brilliant acoustics for soloists and orchestras, the Royal Concertgebouw Hall has a regular program of classical performances. Beurs van Berlage also hosts a large amount of classical concerts on a regular basis. If you\''re interested opera, head to the Het Muziektheater (Stopera) on Waterlooplein, where the Netherlands Opera company puts on several shows each season.Local groups and jam sessions can often be heard throughout the city during the night. For jazz legends in intimate confines, Casablanca and Bimhuis Jazz & Improvisation are surefire options.International stars usually play in larger venues like Paradiso and Melkweg. Besides this there are a lot of concerts held throughout the year at Westergasfabriek, a former gas factory that is now a cultural space. The Amsterdam Pop Prijs, a music competition for emerging bands and artists, is held at Melkweg.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightclubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Air Amsterdam and Paradiso on Saturday evenings are hip dance nights where locals come to shake their stuff. Techno, house and hip-hop music are some of the more popular specialties for DJs in the area. Melkweg has dance evenings that skew more toward hard house and drum & bass. The crowd is diverse but mainly young, and the atmosphere is relaxed. Other clubs like Club Prime and Escape are open until the wee hours of the morning. Jimmy Woo, a themed nightclub is spread over two stories, and has a dazzling dance floor, not to mention a strict door policy. John Doe, another favorite in the city is famous for its fabulous after-parties and works the party circuit in Rembrandtplein.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Gardens & Parks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam has several lush gardens and parks that play host to the city\''s population in warmer months. Vondelpark is arguably the most famous park among tourists and <em>Amsterdammers</em>. The nearby Dutch Film Museum has a beautiful terrace where you can spend a whole afternoon sitting, relaxing and watching locals go about their day. The Amstel Park is located a bit away from the city center, but is a lovely retreat containing rose gardens and a glasshouse. The Amsterdamse Bos is a busier breed of parks where you can enjoy some sporty activities like cycling or running. Several of Amsterdam\''s private gardens can be accessed with prior arrangement, whether through the city\''s tourism office or a private tour operator.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam is well known for its passion for soccer, though other sports such as hockey, skating and cycling are just a few of the area\''s popular recreational activities. The city has many cycling lanes, and though traffic still presents a threat, drivers are much more accustomed to bikes on the road. The parks are excellent for outdoor sports during warmer months, but sports centers offering gyms, saunas, swimming and bowling are wonderful wintertime options.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (66,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dam Square</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The real core of Amsterdam is Dam Square, with its beautiful Royal Palace. Most visitors arrive by train, which takes passengers from Centraal Station along the Damrak right past this busy tourist area. All kinds of souvenir shops, street performers and restaurants, not to mention hungry pigeons, populate the area. The square is used for events and concerts. Amsterdam\''s two main shopping streets, Kalverstraat and Nieuwendijk, are located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Leidseplein & Rembrandtplein</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Leidseplein and Rembrandtplein are very crowded day and night. When the sun is shining, the terraces quickly become filled with tourists. Street performers entertain the public with acrobatic acts and music. At night, the crowd changes as Amsterdammers venture out to celebrate and visit the theaters, cinemas and clubs. Many of the bars and clubs in the area, such as Escape, are open until the early morning.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jordaan</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Built in 1612 during the expansion of the city, the Jordaan neighborhood is well known all over the country for its unique street life, while Jordanezen (the native inhabitants) are renowned for their corny songs, sarcastic humor and working-class mentality. However, most of the Jordanezen left some years ago for improved housing in neighboring cities like Almere and Purmerend. Nowadays, it is a district with many students, artists and young urban professionals, though the area does still retain a unique street culture. The Jordaan accommodates several art galleries, bars and cozy restaurants, and is akin to a small village in a big city. The area is located between Brouwersgracht, Prinsengracht, Raamstraat and Marnixstraat.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Red-Light District (De Wallen)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amsterdam\''s Red-Light District begins left of the Damrak where medieval Amsterdam used to be. The district inhabits the streets and canals between Niezel and Sint Jansstraat to the north and south, and Nieuwmarkt and Warmoestraat to the the east and west. De Wallen is best known for its window prostitution, sex shops and live shows, concentrated around the Oude Kerk, in alleys and around the canals. The atmosphere is somewhat chaotic most of the time, but also bewildering. You\''ll find numerous places to eat, drink and have a good time.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Canals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">On February 1, 1999, the Dutch government made Amsterdam\''s canal district a national monument. In 2010, UNESCO named it a World Heritage Site. The concentric rings of canals (ranging from the Singel Canal up to the Prinsengracht Canal) are a historically important part of the region, and are one of the city\''s most attractive sights. The network of canals starts at River Amstel and ends at Brouwersgracht. One third of the houses along the canals (grachtenhuizen) were built before 1850. During the 17th Century, the city extended its boundaries, and the canals were dug around the oldest part of Amsterdam to accommodate wealthy tradesmen and <em>burghers</em>. The Singel Canal was dug out first, followed by the Herengracht, Keizersgracht and, last of all, Prinsengracht.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">De Pijp</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">De Pijp was Amsterdam\''s first modern housing development, and was built at the end of the 19th Century to accommodate the city\''s growing number of laborers. Nowadays, De Pijp is known as the perfect example of a multicultural neighborhood. People from all over the world live here: young and old, students and artists. The main streets in De Pijp are Albert Cuypstraat, famous for its market, and Ferdinand Bolstraat. Around these roads you\''ll find many diverse restaurants. A typical Amsterdam <em>bruin huis</em> (pub) is located at just about every corner.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museum Quarter</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Museum Quarter is the area around the Museumplein, just a ten minute-walk from Leidseplein. The Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum and Stedelijk Museum are all located here. The Concert Building can be found in this neighborhood, as well. The Museum Quarter is also known for its exclusive shops. Many international clothing brands have boutiques on P.C. Hooftstraat and Van Baerlestraat. Of course, the Museumplein is a great place to sit in the sun, enjoy your lunch or just relax. This cultural area is very crowded during the day, but usually deserted at night.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Banks of the River Ij</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The most modern city developments are located on the southern banks of the River Ij, on both the west and east sides of Centraal Station. This desolate area used to be occupied by dilapidated warehouses, but was completely redeveloped, allowing Amsterdammers to take advantage of the beautiful views of the river. Oostelijke Handelskade, a man-made island, is filled with theaters and a thriving nightlife. Passenger Terminal Amsterdam, a cruise terminal, is also located here. The buildings have aroused much interest because of their innovative architecture.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
