 (111,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Antwerp has come to be a fashion capital in the same league as Milan and Paris thanks to the young Flemish designers who have wholeheartedly embraced the avant-garde style. Besides the designer boutiques around Nationalestraat, the Meir is one of the most prestigious shopping streets in Europe offering a wide range of department stores and boutiques. The Groenplaats and Huidevetterstraat are also worthy alternatives.If you want to buy diamonds it makes sense to visit the certified shops in the vicinity of Antwerp\''s renowned Diamond Center near the Central Station. You can also visit the Diamond Museum for an exciting day out.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Antwerp has acquired a reputation for innovative and exciting ballet, with the Royal Ballet School at the helm of its internationally renown repertoire. The principal ballet company is the Royal Flanders Ballet (Koninklijk Ballet van Vlaanderen).The Royal Flanders Philharmonic (Koninklijk Filharmonisch Orkest) is also well-known and can be heard at the Singel concert hall where mostly modern and contemporary concerts are performed.Antwerp\''s theater repertoire rivals those of New York City and London, with over 100 active theater groups calling this city their home. Most performances are in the native languages, however, and tourists not familiar with either French, Dutch or German may find it hard to locate a show they understand. The Stadsschouwburg is Antwerp\''s premier destination for the performing arts, alongside others like the Arenberg and a multitude of smaller theaters where independent companies fill the stage a few nights per week, all year long. Puppet shows are quite common as well.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For art lovers, Antwerp offers an array of galleries and museums to fit everyone\''s taste. The most popular art museum is the Royal Museum of Fine Arts in \''t Zuid, while contemporary artists are exhibited at the M HKA or the Museum of Contemporary Art. Lesser known, but equally enchanting, are specialty museums like the Fotomuseum, the ModeMuseum and the Museum De Reede with its collection of graphic art by the likes of Edward Munch and Goya.There\''s plenty for history buffs to explore as well. While the Plantin-Moretus Museum and Rubenshuis showcase art history, the Museum aan de Stroom delves into local culture. The Middelheim Open Air Sculpture Museum and the Vleeshuis with its collection of musical instruments are also quite intriguing.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A night out in Antwerp is an inviting prospect with a whole host of options to explore. Beer is a local passion, one that is celebrated with much ardor at the Bierhuiske. Here, over 300 varieties of beer are served to adoring fans of the brew in a setting that is remarkably homely for such a large pub. The Den Engel and De Vagant are other worthy contenders.The city\''s dance clubs are no less exciting, with stalwarts like the Café d\''anvers to look forward to. This legendary dance club has been in business for close to two decades and regularly features as one of the nation\''s top nightlife venues. Lovers of live music should head to De Muze, Antwerp\''s authentic jazz cafe.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinemas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The UGC Antwerpen multiplex near the Central Station and the Metropolis are the city\''s top choices for mainstream cinema. The Metropolis, in particular, impresses with its massive screens; located just outside the city center it was until recently among the largest multiplexes in the world. Cinema buffs can also catch the latest arthouse movies at Cinema Cartoon\''s.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (112,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Old City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Many of the city\''s splendid architectural highlights can be found in the Old City, which was established in the 16th century. It encompasses the area around the Cathedral of Our Lady and the Grote Markt. The Vlaeykensgang is an example of the picturesque medieval streets that riddle the neighborhood, while the numerous paintings of Peter Paul Rubens on display at the city\''s museums bear testament to Antwerp\''s Golden Age. The destruction caused by WWI and WWII impacted the vitality of the Old City, but recent renovation projects have restored it to its former grandeur.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartier Latin</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Some great window-shopping is guaranteed in Quartier Latin. Antwerp has earned a place among the world\''s fashion capitals thanks to the efforts of numerous young Flemish designers who have received international acclaim. Some of them include Nadine Wynants, the extravagant Walter van Beirendonck and the popular Ann De Meulemeester. You can find the new fashion district of Antwerp around Nationalestraat and the more mainstream boutiques in the back streets of Huidervetterstraat.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Port of Antwerp</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Antwerp is the second largest seaport in Europe, following Rotterdam. The harbor was originally situated in the district which is now called <em>\''t Eilandje</em> or \"The Island.\" This district has definitely preserved some of the authentic harbor vibe. Expansion pushed it north to the left bank area, where you can now find large docks and Europe\''s largest energy facilities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sailors Quarter</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The main Red Light District of Antwerp is situated in what is called Schipperskwartier or Rosse Buurt, located between Sint Paulusstraat and Brouwersvliet, not so far from the Grote Markt square. The mood is not as playful as it is in Amsterdam, but you can still find some trouble to get into.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The South</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The main attraction in the <em>Zuid</em>, or South of Antwerp, is the Royal Museum of Fine Arts which is housed in a monumental, neo-classical building. This area really started to buzz a few years ago after numerous successful redevelopment projects. Now you\''ll find many fine brasseries and bistros that serve great food at reasonable prices. The annual amusement fair, Sinksenfoor, is held here in June.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Meir and de Keyserlei</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">These are Antwerp\''s main shopping streets and among the prettiest in Europe. Most of the Meir is reserved for pedestrians only and the stylish buildings with international department stores are quite a sight. You\''ll find a wide range of trendy boutiques along the main thoroughfare and down side-streets.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Station</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As you walk down de Keyserlei at the end of your shopping spree, you\''ll catch a glimpse of the magnificent Central Station. The surrounding area is a strange mixture of nouveau riche and underground cool. The shops on de Keyserlei and the fabulous postmodern Astrid Park Plaza Hotel stand not far from raucous, loud bars in Statiestraat. If you walk from Koningin Astrid Square towards De Coninck Square you\''ll wander into Antwerp\''s small Chinatown and the more discreet Red Light District.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jewish Antwerp and the Diamond Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Antwerp is also the \"Diamond Capital of the World\" and near the Central Station, you will find the Diamond District. The streets between the station and the city park, called Stadspark, also make up the city\''s Jewish Quarter. Estimates put the number of Jewish citizens in Antwerp from 15,000 to 20,000, their population more than halved by the upheaval of the Second World War. Nevertheless, the city is still home to the largest concentration of Orthodox Jews in northern Europe. The Great Synagogue, Hollandse Synagogue and Oosten Synagogue are three of the most prominent Jewish landmarks in this quarter.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
