 (150,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Casinos</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The thrill of the game is what brings people to Atlantic City, and a whole world of entertainment exists in its casinos. The Borgata Casino features slots, Blackjack, Video Poker, Baccarat, and Texas Hold\''em Poker games on its 161,000-square-foot (14,957-square-meter) gaming floor. With its fine dining and casual restaurants, event center, nightclubs and spa, this casino offers all-round entertainment to its patrons. The Golden Nugget Atlantic City is another of Atlantic City\''s casino giants. These are just a few of the many places you can go to get your heart pounding and your fingers tingling.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Atlantic City is a city of the night and its clubs are some of the best you\''ll find. Pool After Dark and Providence Atlantic City are some of the most popular, both upscale joints, the first features pool-side cabanas, VIP Bottle service, some of the best DJs in town, and a fun-loving ambiance. A more casual atmosphere can be found at Planet Rose which proclaims itself \"The Greatest Karaoke Bar on Earth\" and is open seven nights a week.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Atlantic City is not all quick thrills; history and art can also be enjoyed between rolls of the dice. Atlantic City Art Center at Garden Pier offers a wide variety of mediums, showcases local and international artists, and plays host to a number of events. If you\''ve been having a bad day at the slots, don\''t worry, admission is free! The Wheaton Arts & Cultural Center is devoted to the city\''s rich glassmaking history, while Noyes Museum of Art offers a diverse array of art. Appreciate African-American culture and history at the African American Heritage Museum of Southern NJ or the Civil Rights Garden. The Ripley\''s Believe It or Not on the Boardwalk is great for those with a curious streak and is sure to shock and surprise you.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historical Attractions</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A great part of the Jersey Shore\''s heritage is its maritime tradition, which is featured at the nearby Tuckerton Seaport. This historic village, with its 17 recreated buildings makes a great break from the big city. Closer still is another maritime landmark, the Absecon Lighthouse. Just a quick walk from the Atlantic City Boardwalk, it is one of the largest lighthouses in the U.S. and offers a great view of the shore.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts and Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Many music and comedy acts can be found in the Casinos themselves, for instance, the Borgata Hotel Casino & Spa contains the Borgata Music Box, a venue that features live music and comedy. Other venues that host stand up shows include the Resorts Casino Hotel and Tropicana Casino & Resort. For classical evenings, the Richard Stockton College Performing Arts Center, home to the Bay-Atlantic Symphony promises a mesmerizing evening. Broadway musicals such as <em>The Producers</em> are featured at Harrah\''s and Borgata. You can enjoy the latest movie releases at the IMAX Theatre at Tropicana. There isn\''t a bad seat in the house at the intimate 240-seat Dante Hall Theater in Ducktown and shows by the Atlantic City Ballet are a must for dance enthusiasts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoor Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Located at the Boardwalk, the Atlantic City Steel Pier has been entertaining families since the 1800s! The theme park has rides, plus a museum and an arcade for a fun day out.You\''re never too far from a beach in Atlantic City and the long stretch of shoreline makes a compelling argument for spending hours soaking up the rays. A little further along, the Ocean City Beach is considered one of the best places for some R&R while further south, Cape May Beach offer a more exclusive experience.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (151,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Boardwalk</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Atlantic City\''s Boardwalk is famous. Constructed in 1870, the Boardwalk was the first of its kind in America and boosted the seaside experience for visitors. With its mesmerizing ocean views and fun attractions, the Boardwalk is an Atlantic City icon. This stretch along the Atlantic Ocean is known for its resort hotels, sandy beaches, and local boutiques. For more information on city\''s accommodations, shopping, restaurants and entertainment, there is a tourist information center at the Boardwalk Hall, more notably the historic landmark where famous events such as the Miss America pageant have taken place. For a fun day out, The Quarter at Tropicana offers a host of activities to keep you busy from day spas to nightclubs and bars once the sun sets while the Steel Pier promises a host of thrilling rides for some wholesome family fun. If you\''ve got a sweet tooth then don\''t miss a chance to try the classic saltwater taffy at Fralinger\''s Salt Water Taffy, they\''ve perfected that recipe over 100 years!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown and Midtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Discover a variety of flavors with tons of diverse restaurants, like the Cuba Libre Restaurant & Rum Bar and Los Amigos for some Caribbean and Latin specialties in Atlantic City\''s Downtown. If you happen to be shopping at Tanger Outlets The Walk and need a break, Cavo Crepe Café has a full menu of sweet and savory treats. One of the most popular restaurants in town is Dock\''s Oyster House, a great place for seafood. When you have had enough to eat, catch a show or exhibition at Atlantic City Convention Center. Then dance the night away at one of the city\''s hottest clubs Providence Atlantic City.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Arts District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Anchored by the Noyes Arts Garage of Stockton University, better known as The Garage, the Arts District is at the center of the city\''s burgeoning creative scene. The Garage with its 15 studios, shops and galleries is where you can have one-on-one talks with artists, support emerging artists, and build your collection of works.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Absecon</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Check out some fascinating destinations like Absecon Lighthouse, one of the largest in the U.S. You can also stay at The Dr. Jonathan Pitney House, a B&B and home of the city\''s founder. For a more conventional route, get comedy or concert tickets at the Borgata Music Box. Do not worry too much about reserving seats in advance because the venue holds up to 1,000 people.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Marina</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Set sail with Atlantic City Cruises where dolphin watching is a favorite pastime. If you want a more close-up encounter, visit the Atlantic City Aquarium. When hunger strikes, Back Bay Ale House not only serves micro-brewed beer, but also seafood, steaks and burgers with a great view of the water. Try your luck at The Borgata Casino where you can choose from over 200 table games including high-stakes poker or hit the slot machines and hope for a jackpot.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outside the City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With so much excitement in the city, Ventnor Beach is a great place to get away from the bustle. The whole family will enjoy Ocean City Parasailing with no experience necessary. Six Flags Great Adventure amusement park will keep the teens preoccupied all day, but for the younger ones who do not always make the minimum height requirement for those thrilling rollercoasters, Storybook Land is a safer bet.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (152,'View of the harbor and city skyline on a sunny day.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (153,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">As New Zealand writer Kevin Ireland once observed, Auckland has a weight problem: \"It is one of the biggest cities in the world. Its swollen bulk hangs out over the constricting belt of its isthmus and bulges further than the eye can see. Its head cannot locate its toes.\"  Over a quarter of the nation\''s inhabitants live in the Auckland region. Since the Maori alighted from their <em>waka</em> (canoes) to occupy the densely forested land, a steady stream of migrants have followed; Europeans, Asians and Polynesians have all made the journey to create the largest Polynesian enclave in the world. More than 50 volcanoes have erupted in Auckland, permanently scarring its landscape. The last, 600 years ago, gave birth to Rangitoto Island. Today, the buzz, aggression and vitality of the city echoes this turbulent past.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
