 (169,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Whether you are a music fan searching for that up-and-coming band, or a musician looking for the perfect tune, you can carve out your niche here. The music scene has something for everybody: blues, jazz, fusion, house/techno, pop/rock, noisepop, twee-pop, reggae, trip-hop, hip-hop, hard rock, country, Latino, classical, folk, experimental, garage and psychedelic. With 100 or more venues to choose from it may seem like a daunting task, but the Austin Chronicle offers helpful online updates.  Visit Stubb\''s, Mohawk, or Emo\''s to catch top local acts and independent touring musicians. Stop by Hole in the Wall for live music seven nights a week, or the Flamingo Cantina to sample a variety of bands. Live music in Austin is not limited to the club scene though; frequently musicians are found performing in record stores, coffee shops and art galleries. Other exciting venues in the city include The Continental Club in South Congress, the White Horse, a favorite honky-tonk on Comal Street, and the Carousel Lounge, a psychedelic haunt featuring live music and a laidback vibe.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Austin Museum of Art at Laguna Gloria is a beautiful place to enjoy diverse artwork created by 20th-century artists from around the world. The Mediterranean-style villa that is home to the museum was built in 1916 and is surrounded by lush gardens and quiet paths. The Art School at Laguna Gloria is also on the grounds, offering classes for children and adults in sculpture, graphic arts, painting, jewelry-making and more.  For a multicultural Latin American experience visit the Mexic-Arte Museum, featuring three galleries that exhibit works from Mexic-Arte\''s permanent collection, along with touring and self-curated shows. The museum also presents theatrical, musical and performing arts events on weekends.  Sculptor Elisabet Ney moved to Austin in the late 1800s and built Formosa, her home and studio. This Greek/Gothic building, now the Elisabet Ney Museum, is dedicated to the life and works of the artist. Ney sculpted the figures of Sam Houston and Stephen F. Austin that stand on the Texas State Capitol grounds today.  If it\''s a beautiful day in Austin, you must visit the Umlauf Sculpture Garden & Museum. Charles Umlauf\''s work is showcased here in the outdoor Xeriscape garden, where visitors linger by the pond. This casual setting is home to 62 bronze and cast pieces.To immerse yourself in a bit of history, head to the Bullock Texas State History Museum that ensures a fun time for both adults and kids, while the Harry Ransom Center in the University of Texas boasts of an impressive archival collection of manuscripts and literary artifacts from both United States and Europe. The first edition of the King James Bible is one of their most prized artifacts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Austin offers big Broadway shows in legendary theaters like the Paramount Theatre or the University of Texas\'' Bass Concert Hall. For an interesting change of pace try the experimental, Off Broadway-type shows presented by one of the 70 theater companies thriving in Austin.  For original cutting-edge performances visit the Vortex Theatre in East Austin. Once an abandoned warehouse, this building has been converted into an intimate, comfortable, 80-seat venue that showcases contemporary theater, nationally known performance artists, multimedia performances, musical theater and ritual theater. Other arts centers like the Hyde Park Theatre and the Long Center for Performing Arts also boast of an exciting event calendar. The FronteraFest, one of the city\''s most happening winter-time fringe theater festivals is held at the Hyde Park Theatre.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Austin is known for hosting big-ticket concerts within its urbane sprawl which comes as no surprise considering its musical roots. Home to a burgeoning student population, Austin\''s concerts are staged at venues like the Frank Erwin Center, Michael and Susan Dell Hall, and the Austin360 Amphitheater.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you are looking for a place where you can order great food and have it served to you while you take in a film, try the Alamo Drafthouse Cinema, where visitors can catch old B-movies, historic silent films and more. The iPic Austin located in The Domain, and the Cinemark Tinseltown 20 & XD are two of Austin\''s most modern theaters. The Violet Crown Cinema, on the other hand, is a local gem that screens indie flicks, world movies and thought-provoking documentaries in the Second Street District.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of only three professional ballet companies in Texas, Ballet Austin showcases dancers from around the world. The company presents five seasonal ballets, including the popular Nutcracker every December. Ballet East is a community of dancers from many ethnic backgrounds, with a strong emphasis on Austin\''s Latino dancers.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Comedy</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Political satire is especially strong at Esther\''s Follies, a campy comedy venue located on East Sixth Street that has become part of the fabric of Austin. Just next door is the Velveeta Room, where local and visiting comic talents take the stage and try the outrageous. If you\''re looking for big-name comics, look no further than the Capitol City Comedy Club; nationally known comics like Ellen DeGeneres, Jeff Foxworthy and Bobcat Goldthwait have all taken this stage in support of their art.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (170,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Austin</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The commercial hub of the city of Austin, Downtown is also known as its Central Business District, and sits on the north end of the Colorado River that slices through the city.  Hemmed by landmarks like the University of Austin and Lady Bird Lake, Downtown Austin boasts of an impressive arsenal of buildings that contribute to its expanding skyline. Downtown District is also one of Austin\''s most comprehensive neighborhoods, comprising several smaller districts within its monumental sprawl. Some of the districts include Second Street District, West End/Market District, Judges Hill and the Red River Cultural District.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sixth Street/Red River Cultural District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">To experience \"The Live Music Capital\" of the world, Sixth Street is a good place to start. Often closed to vehicle traffic on the weekends, this street is lined with dance clubs, live music venues, eateries and street musicians, plus several tattoo and piercing shops. Visitors can have their tarot cards read by a gypsy on a street corner, or buy handmade jewelry from artists and hippies. Music fills the air in this area every night of the week, and visitors can hear everything from country to hip-hop, blues to noise-pop. The Pecan Street Festival, dedicated to the fine arts, is held here. An array of shops, restaurants and cafes dot the street, and attractions like the Museum of the Weird, and the Alamo Drafthouse Cinema are located here as well.  If you venture north on Red River Street, you\''ll find some of Austin\''s best live music venues, including Stubb\''s, Mohawk and Beerland. This upbeat neighborhood, also considered as one of the most important hubs of entertainment in the city, is teeming with clubs and bars of all kinds and stripe that dot its main and side streets. The Doyle House, which hosts the Austin Symphony Orchestra, is also located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Capitol Building</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Built in 1856 and 1857, the Capitol Complex Visitor Center is the oldest remaining state office building in Texas. In 1997, it underwent an enormous restoration and extension. The Capitol Building is a Renaissance Revival-style building made of Texas pink granite and native limestone, overlooking Congress Avenue. Guided tours are free and provide interesting information and anecdotes for visitors. Make sure to stand in the center of the Rotunda, look up, take notice of the Texas star and enjoy the beautiful architecture.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Congress Avenue/Travis Heights</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Regarded as a significant thoroughfare in the 19th Century that stretched from the Colorado River to the State Capitol, the Congress Avenue neighborhood was brimming with several government structures, saloons and now-historic stores when then-mayor Edwin Waller planned the city. Today, it still retains its prominence, with several handsome Victorian buildings adorning its wide streets, such as the landmark Paramount Theater, the Old Bakery and Emporium, and the Sampson Building. The Travis Heights neighborhood, another historic area, extends forward south of the river, and forms part of the South Congress District. Walk along South Congress and cross Lake Austin, and you\''ll soon see a new side of the city. Starting with Güero\''s Taco Bar, you will notice that South Austin has a different kind of energy - relaxed and funky. Here, you will find antique shops, retro resale shops, vintage clothing and folk art. Stop by Terra Toys to check out their collection of tin soldiers and chemistry sets, then head over to Texas French Bread for soup and a sandwich. The St. Edward\''s University and a couple of public parks are located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Second Street District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Second Street District went from being a bleak, fast-declining neighborhood filled with lumberyards and abandoned structures, to a district that was revived with a warren of retail buildings, offices and mixed-use buildings. Located north of Lady Bird Lake, this revitalized district is also famous for its culinary and retail options, and comprises tons of cafes, wine bars, swish restaurants, high-end boutiques and designer stores. A couple of hotels like the W Austin Hotel and Residences overlook Butler Park, whereas the Moody Theater, a live music venue, is also the city\''s fourth-tallest building.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Barton Hills</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Zilker Park is a 400-acre park home to natural, spring-fed Barton Springs Pool, a miniature train that circles the park for children to ride, a giant playscape, picnic grounds, rugby and soccer fields, a disc golf course and canoe and kayak rentals. At Christmas time, one of the city\''s moonlight towers serves as the trunk for the Zilker Park Christmas Tree. Thousands of colored lights are strung to form the shape, and each year locals and visitors twirl around underneath the enormous structure.  Enjoy a number of musical, dance and theater events at the Zilker Hillside Theatre, where the Austin Shakespeare Festival is held each year. Or, visit the Zilker Botanical Gardens, where visitors spend the better part of a day enjoying the cactus, succulents, roses, butterflies and special gardens - all for free.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Clarksville</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Originally an African-American community half a mile outside of the city limits, Clarksville remains a melting pot of art and culture. Houses have increased greatly in price due to the location of the neighborhood and all it has to offer. Jeffrey\''s resides here, a restaurant for fine dining. You may also enjoy a visit to Nau\''s Enfield Drug, where you can order an old fashioned malt.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Drag</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The strip of business along Guadalupe Street, bordering the University of Texas, is lovingly called \"The Drag.\" Many of Austin\''s coolest shops are here. Stop by the outdoor 23rd Street Artists\'' Market, where you will find jewelry, clothing and gifts made by Austin artisans. If you\''re looking for live music any night of the week, head down to the Hole in the Wall. This small dive hosts live music seven nights a week, with free Sunday night shows. The back room is full of pool tables and pinball games, and the crowd features many regular customers.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Hyde Park</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Take a leisurely walk or drive through this Central Austin neighborhood and view its historic homes. You will likely see many residents working in their yards, walking pets or riding bikes. Duval Road runs through the neighborhood and is home to the popular Hyde Park Grill. This unique area, the city\''s first planned suburb, has its own small grocery store, and boasts a theatre in its name - Hyde Park Theatre. Stop by Dolce Vita Gelate and Espresso Bar for sweet Italian ice cream or check out Quack\''s 43rd Street Bakery for a cappuccino and a homemade muffin.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">East Austin</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This dynamic neighborhood underwent an surprising renaissance that is still under process, transforming from an area filled with turn-of-the-century bungalows, to one teeming with chic condominiums and a melange of modern eateries. Today, East Austin comprises of smaller neighborhoods like Chestnut, Rosewood, Holly, Foster Heights, and the quirky East Cesar Chavez. The district features a cornucopia of street art that contributes to its vibrancy, and a hipster vibe that blends fantastically with Austin\''s emerging trends. There are a few traditional Southern-style landmarks as well, as you will find in places like Franklin Barbecue. Then again, a row of cocktail bars, atmospheric live music venues and art venues vie for attention in this upcoming, trendy neighborhood that is definitely worth a visit. While you\''re here, plan a jaunt along the area\''s famous Tejano Walking Trails, a stretch comprising of historically significant Latino houses, structures and religious landmarks.  &nbsp;</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
