 (287,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">What the city\''s got to offer in terms of culture has been improving over the last years, with the inauguration of the Guggenheim having been the impetus for a marked revitalization of the cultural life of Bilbao. The magnificent architecture of the building and its constantly changing exhibitions give the tourist the perfect excuse to come to the banks of the Nervión. Nearby one can find the Museo de Bellas Artes, one of the most important art galleries in Spain, which has been able to avail itself of the success of the Guggenheim. The choice of museums is completed by the Museo Vasco (the Basque Museum) and the Museo de Reproducciones Artísticas, Museo de Arte Sacro and the Museo Taurino. The Bilbao Arts District, an art-powered initiative has backed the expansion of the arts scene in Bilbao. The Sala Rekalde Contemporary Art Gallery is part of this initiative, and promotes several emerging Spanish artists.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts and Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Bilbao hosts a wealth of local cultural venues that promote theater and arts, from the Palacio Euskalduna that features opera acts and classical concerts, to Teatro Campos Elíseo that stages everything from contemporary concerts to avant-garde plays. The La FuNdicIOn Bilbao also has an exciting program throughout the year. In the world of theater, the Teatro Arriaga is worth a mention, an architecturally impressive building situated in the Casco Viejo. The Bilbao Exhibition Centre, a sprawling congress venue on the city\''s outskirts hosts large-scale music concerts as well, as does Sala Santana 27.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Live Music Venues, Nightclubs and Bars</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Bilbao has a large audience for dinner theaters as well as live music venues. Venues like Luz Gas, Kafe Antzokia and Azkena feed the city\''s appetite for both local and international touring bands who perform here regularly. Others like the Cotton Club double up as a Hollywood-themed nightclub and live-gig venue, and are keenly visited by indie loving youth in the city. La Ribera, an otherwise culinary-centric establishment serving <em>pinxtos</em> and delicious Basque cuisine transforms into the night to host an exciting repertoire of intimate music events and small concerts. Ambigú has a similar agenda, and hosts DJ nights to celebrate weekends. For intense partying scenes, visit Shake Bilbao, or join the raucous crowds at the LGBT-friendly La Lola. Past midnight, Bilbao\''s streets get taken over by a younger crowd who do their own hopping from bar to bar, normally along the streets like Barrenkale, Barrenkale Barrena, Somera and others. Some of the more popular bars in this part of town worth checking out include K2.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals and Events</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">It is no surprise that Bilbao\''s colorful cultural landscape includes an impressive line-up of festivals and events that attract droves of crowds from across the nation and the globe. The Carnaval de Bilbao is a true-blue Basque celebration that commences the Saturday before Ash Wednesday, and continues for several days, finally culminating on Easter Sunday. A lengthy line-up of parades, music programs, competitions and more constitute this extravaganza.The Semana Santa is another cultural and religious festival celebrated in Bilbao. There are also a number of music and film festivals that take the streets of Bilbao by storm, including the Jazz Euskadi Festival, the Bilbao BBK Live which celebrates rock and pop music, the blues-festival Festival Internacional de Blues de Getxo, and the Bilbao International Film Festival.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (288,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Deusto</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">To get to District 1, called Deusto, you have to cross either the Puente de Euskalduna or the older Puente de Deusto bridge, which up till a few years ago still used to be raised to let big boats pass under. Walk along the Ribera de Deusto to get a glimpse of how one part of the estuary flows through city life. While here, a must-see is the Universidad de Deusto. Established in the 19th Century and run by Jesuits, this university has been the alma mater of such luminaries as the banker Mario Conde, the politician Arzalluz or the former president (\"Lehendakari\") of the Basque government, Garaikoetxea. All in all, the neighborhood has a rather student-like feeling and is filled with bars, cafés, restaurants, etc. If you\''ve been out partying all evening, this is a great place to pass the very last hours of the night.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Uribarri & Begoña</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Still on the same side of the estuary, use either the Calatrava footbridge or the Puente del Ayuntamiento to get to District 2, called Uribarri. Take a stroll in Campo Volantín or get a closer peek at the Ayuntamiento de Bilbao (City Hall). From here you take the Funicular de Artxanda to the top of Archanda Hill, from where you can enjoy the fantastic views and the fresh air, or have a bite to eat in one of the many restaurants.  From here it\''s straight over to District 4, Begoña, where you will find the Santa María de Begoña, the \"Amatxo\" (mother) of Bilbao. Walk to the church along the Calzadas de Mallona, which begins in the Casco Viejo, you can also take the Ascensor de Begoña or the metro.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Casco Viejo</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is District 5, the Casco Viejo. It\''s clear how one can easily spend time in this lively neighborhood—eating and drinking in one of the numerous establishments, listening to the street musicians, and doing a bit of shopping. But before diving into the sensual delights of the Casco Viejo there\''s a few other things you could see, such as the Centro Cívico de La Bolsa o Palacio Yohn. Or look at  La Sociedad Bilbaína on Nafarroa Kalea, one of the old-established and most elegant cultural and recreational societies in Spain. For more high culture, cross the Puente del Arenal to visit the Teatro Arriaga and the San Nicolás de Bari church. Once there you can slowly make your way to Siete Calles by way of the Ribera, taking in the Puente de La Merced on the way to the Iglesia de San Antón (but don\''t forget to stop in the Mercado de La Ribera and admire the amazing selection of vegetables, fish and meat!). Once you are in the heart of Casco Viejo, just like a pilgrim tracing the route of the Camino de Santiago, make your final stop here at the Catedral de Santiago.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Abando</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Time to hop over to the other side of the estuary, to Abando, District 6. Beginning at the monument on the Plaza del Sagrado Corazón, stroll down the Gran Vía de Don Diego López de Haro. Measuring one-and-a-half kilometers (0.93 miles), this avenue is lined with houses with charming façades—keep an eye out especially for the Edificio Sota and the Edificio de la Diputación. A stroll down the Gran Vía will take you along the relaxing Parque de Doña Casilda Iturrizar with its Museo de Bellas Artes de Bilbao (Museum of Fine Arts). Halfway down the Gran Vía, there is the quaint Plaza Moyúa. At the far end of Gran Vía, you come to Plaza Circular where the monument in honor of the founder of the town sits. Other places worth checking out in this area are the Iglesia de San Vicente, a church in 12th-century Basque Gothic style, the Jardín de Albia and the Mercado del Ensanche. As well, you\''re not far from two streets that are very popular for bar hopping, Ledesma and Licenciado Poza. From here you can see the city\''s \"other\" cathedral, that is to say, the Estadio de Fútbol de San Mamés, which may not be quite as spiritual as the Catedral de Santiago, but you can be sure there are many citizens of this town that consider the city\''s soccer team, Athletic de Bilbao, to be sacred. For real soccer fun head all the way to Mazarredo street and visit the little palace that houses the headquarters of the Athlétic. The area around Mazarredo is another very popular night haunt. And for lovers of a bloodier sport, one is not far from the Plaza de Toros de Vista Alegre (whose name ironically means \"Happy View Bullfighting Ring\") and its bullfighting museum, the Museo Taurino. There\''s a lot of other places to visit in this district, such as the Museo Guggenheim Bilbao, the Estación de Abando (a.k.a. Estación del Norte) with it\''s magnificent stained-glass windows, the Santa Casa de Misericordia, and the Azkuna Zentroa.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Rekalde</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The last district, District 7, called Rekalde, is reached by crossing the highway to Larrasquitu. This is a popular excursion for people wanting to scale the Pagasarri hill. At the top there is a little refuge from where one gets some splendid views of the south side of the \"botxo\" (the pit). If you don\''t already know why Bilbao is known affectionately by this name, you will once you see it from here!</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (289,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Centered around the historic downtown, Billings has grown into Montana\''s largest city in the span of a few decades. While downtown remains the cultural and commercial hub of the city, beyond its historic streets, lie sprawling residential neighborhoods and communities.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
