 (324,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bollywood/Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mumbai is not only the country\''s financial center, but also the proud host of Bollywood, one of the biggest film producing industries in the world. Films and everything to do with films is BIG here. Cinema halls like Regal and Liberty still carry on with the tradition of single screen theaters while multiplexes like PVR, INOX and IMAX are forever booked for the latest in Hindi and English films.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art and Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mumbai also has a thriving art scene. On par with the cultural capital New Delhi, it is always buzzing with exhibitions, book readings, talks, seminars and cultural festivals. Kala Ghoda is a very popular annual art festival that brings together renowned artists from all over the country. Jehangir Art Gallery is the most respected name in the Mumbai art world, while National Gallery of Modern Art (NGMA), Artist\''s Center, Chemould Gallery and Cymroza are established patrons of contemporary Indian art. These places also encourage interactions with the artists through workshops and lectures. Art Galleries thrive in every nook and corner. The National Center for Performing Arts, Nehru Center, Prithvi Theater and others play host to critically-acclaimed plays and concerts throughout the year. Theater is huge in this city and there are numerous organizations encouraging English, Hindi, Marathi and other regional theater.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Visitors who\''ve had their share of the busy art scene may explore a number of shopping complexes. Full of malls, arcades, designer shops, flea markets and local vendors, shopping centers sell everything from hairpins to heavy duty appliances. Phoenix Mills mall heads the favorites list. It is a sprawling complex comprising malls, restaurants, and nightclubs. The ultra-luxe Palladium Mall with its designer shops and swanky restaurants is the address for the city\''s fashionistas. Khadi Gramudyog Bhavan is a trusted name for handicrafts and textiles, and Colaba Causeway not only offers inexpensive cotton wear but stashes hundreds of stalls selling artificial jewelry, souvenirs and interesting nick-nacks.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Among the city\''s museums, the Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Vastu Sangrahalaya (formerly known as Prince of Wales Museum) has a fantastic collection of Indian art and sculpture through the ages and offers insight into the country\''s artistic traditions. The Bhau Daji Lad Museum in Byculla, located by the Byculla Zoo, is great for those wanting to know more about the city\''s fascinating transition from fishing villages to booming metropolis. Smaller museums like the Monetary Museum and the Railway Museum are specialized museums that have small but interesting exhibitions.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Amusement Parks and Family-Friendly Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There\''s plenty to explore with kids in Mumbai. The city is home to some of the country\''s largest amusement parks just beyond its fringes like Adlabs Imagica, Essel World, and Water Kingdom. For more educational pursuits, the Nehru Science Center, Nehru Planetarium and Taraporewala Aquarium are excellent choices that offer a range of interactive exhibits and fun activities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mumbai has a buzzing nightlife scene, and every mall has its share of restaurants and pubs drawing in crowds. Pubs like the Social have multiple outlets around the city and cater to a varied crowd of young professionals. Neighborhoods like Lower Parel, home to the revitalized mill district with its industrial chic vibe, Bandra, Andheri, and Juhu host trendy celeb-friendly nightclubs as well as casual bars for an after-work drink like Trilogy. Art collectives and alternative venues host poetry evenings, local musicians, and independent plays for those who eschew the mainstream. Essentially, there\''s something to suit every taste in Mumbai.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (325,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">South Mumbai</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mumbai is divided into two major districts- North and South Mumbai. If South Mumbai, also known as Town, is considered an elite address by every Mumbaiite, then Nariman Point is the Manhattan of the city, overflowing with high-powered corporate offices. It also has Dalal Street, the volatile stock market area. South Mumbai comprises areas such as Marine Drive (with beautiful art deco buildings), Byculla, Churchgate, Parel, Elphinstone Road, Mahalaxmi, Worli, and Kemp\''s Corner/Cumballa Hill. It has places of historical importance, wide roads, hundreds of high-rises, the luxury hotels, trendy bars and restaurants, and an eclectic mix of residents. But this was until North Mumbai caught on.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Colaba/Fort</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Part of South Mumbai, much of the city\''s historic character is visible along the colonial-era buildings and wide boulevards of Fort, remnants of British rule. Home to the heritage Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus railway station (popularly called V.T. Station) and the Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Vastu Sangrahalaya (formerly the Prince of Wales Museum) this area is packed with popular attractions. Colaba is famous for its Causeway, a bargain-hunter\''s haven great for street shopping. Just a few minutes away is the Gateway of India from where boats to Elephanta Caves depart and the heritage Taj Mahal Hotel is located.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Girgaum</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Away from the colonial areas, lie what was once the Native Town; another enclave of South Mumbai. A fascinating hodgepodge of small bylanes and alleys, this area is home to the Mumbadevi Temple and other interesting, if lesser known landmarks like Khotachiwadi, an oasis of calm in the chaos of the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lalbaug and Dadar</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the city\''s busiest neighborhoods, Dadar is home to some of the biggest markets and mumbaikars make the trek to get the best bargains around. Lalbaug is where the famous Ganesh Festival is at its peak and the Lalbaugcha Raja draws millions of visitors every year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Western Suburbs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mumbai is a sprawling metropolis connected by the railway line, the artery of the city. The Western suburbs extend past Bandra, Juhu, Andheri and beyond. Due to soaring real estate prices in the \''town\'' or South Mumbai, the younger, working populations have migrated north to these suburbs, which as a result have a lively, upbeat character. Among these, Bandra, a trendy neighborhood full of coffee shops, eateries, independent boutiques and celebrity homes along with a beautiful heritage church, Mount Mary, and one of the busiest shopping streets, Linking Road, is a favorite choice for the younger crowd. Juhu\''s upscale villas and beachfront homes, dotted with the abodes of famous Bollywood actors, and home to the Prithvi Theater, is another landmark. Even further, Borivali with its Sanjay Gandhi National Park and ancient caves is worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central/Eastern Suburbs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Beyond Dadar, neighborhoods like Matunga, Chembur and Ghatkopar each have their own independent character, while satellite suburbs like Thane and Panvel are cities in their own right. Matunga is famed for its South Indian lunch homes and often people make the trip just to enjoy a delicious fluffy set dosa at one of the many <em>udipi</em> restaurants.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Navi Mumbai</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Modern Navi Mumbai, or New Bombay, as it was earlier known, is home to a conglomeration of new offices, residential complexes and mega malls. Of these, Vashi is the most developed and well-known and is a major commercial center. It\''s quite natural for mumbaikars to commute long distances and the network of public transport which includes three local train lines, a monorail and a metro connect these diverse neighborhoods with each other. Much of the commercial and office spaces are concentrated in hubs like Nariman Point, Lower Parel, Goregaon and Navi Mumbai, and several people commute to South Mumbai from outlying areas for work.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (326,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">One of the oldest cities in America, Boston evokes a distinctly European feel. The charming town is lined with ivied brick buildings and sprawling parks, lending it a warm and welcoming atmosphere. Once considered a conservative destination, Boston has developed quite the progressive attitude over the years, becoming one of the most exciting places in New England. You\''ll find culinary treasures, shopping havens, and lots of youthful energy alongside national landmarks and historic sights that define this dynamic capital.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
