 (380,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Royal Museum of Art and History is the finest museum in the country, with over 650,000 pieces of art and illuminating exhibitions that help visitors learn more about the history of Belgium. Since Belgium used to be known as a top producer of lace, the Museum of Costume and Lace is also a popular stop, while the Jubelparkmuseum displays of Asian, Greek and Roman art with everything but painting represented. For those interested in photography, Contretype is a must-see. Its extensive and unique collection of photographs has made it a world-renowned destination for photography enthusiasts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Auditorium Jacques Brel is just one of the many venues across the city that frequently hosts concerts and other live events. St. Peter\''s Church is filled with 15th-century artwork and a common place for classical music performances, while the St. Franciscuskerk te Groningen hosts smaller orchestral groups.Brussels boasts six opera houses, the grandest being the De Munt/La Monnaie. This opera house was fully renovated in 1986 and is now one of the most modern opera houses in Europe. The Grand Foyer upstairs, where you can enjoy a drink at intermission, has not really changed. The parquet flooring and rococo décor have been retained, and the original ceiling in the main dome has been restored.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Brussels European Film Festival is an annual event where filmgoers can check out the latest in film from around Belgium. The Christmas Creche and Illuminations are annual holiday celebrations that are quite popular among families. Every December to January, a manger display and brilliant lights are strung to help mark the occasion. Another citywide celebration is the European Christmas Market which runs along the Place St. Catherine.<p dir=\"ltr\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"><p dir=\"ltr\">On weekends there are many markets that take place throughout the city - it is hard to know which to visit first! The bird market, held every Sunday, is probably the best-known while at Place du Grand Sablon you\''ll find the hippest of flea markets. Here, there\''s an abundance of beautiful goods for sale, such as paintings and antiques.Of course, there are also a great number of wonderful shops in Brussels where you can purchase antiques, jewelry, Belgian lace, chocolates, books, crystal, and more. There are also a number of late night shops, mostly situated in the vicinity of Grote Markt / Grand Place. They sell everything from groceries to books and tobacco.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (381,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Brussels\''s city center is essentially pentagonal, with all roads leading to Grote Markt / Grand Place, the city\''s core. Sights such as the Cathédrale des Saints Michel et Gudule, Mont-des-Arts, and the city\''s main shopping complexes are located here. In the area between De Broukère and Place Rogier you\''ll find close to a dozen points of interest including Brussels\'' stock exchange (the Bourse), the fish market, Brussels\'' Red Light District and Parc de Bruxelles. The Palais Royal (Royal Palace) is another popular attraction, the home of Belgium\''s kings furnished with 18th-century artwork. Nearby, the Palais de Justice was built for King Leopold II and showcases neo-Gothic architecture.You\''ll also find Grote Markt / Grand Place here. It\''s considered the largest and most extensive market square in all of Europe. Spending a day exploring the unique shops and stalls here is definitely a must.The Manneken Pis is another popular site; a symbol of Brussels, this small, occasionally dressed statue mimics the image of a peeing boy. Head down Rue de Loi to reach Jubel Park/Parc du Cinquantenaire, a 36.4-hectare (90-acre) park just outside of the bounds of the city center.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ixelles/Elsene</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Ixelles is a serene and tranquil alcove in busy Brussels, where lie the beautiful Bois de la Cambre forest, parks, ponds, and the Abbaye de la Cambre, which was founded in 1196 by the Sisters of the Cistercian Order. The building was rebuilt during the 17th and 18th Centuries after suffering extensive damage during the Huguenot Wars of Religion. There is only one remaining section of the original church itself, which dates back to the 14th Century. The Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium is the largest museum in the country and exhibits artwork acquired from the collection of King William I, as well as pieces dating all the way back to the 14th Century. The Place du Grand Sablon is a large square with many interesting shops. There is also a statue of Minerva and several churches and other excellent examples of Belgian architecture.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartier Louise</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Avenue Louise is Brussels\'' Rodeo Drive or Champs Elysées, the city\''s most prestigious shopping street and a real favorite with tourists and residents alike. If you continue walking along Avenue Louise you\''ll come to Bois de la Cambre, near Sonian Forest, one of Brussels\'' best parks.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
