 (426,'The colonial-style architecture of Victoria Memorial Hall.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (427,'The spectacular Victoria Memorial Hall illuminated at night.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (428,'The Dakshineshwar Kali Temple with its nine spires.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (429,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music & Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The city of Kolkata has had a long and passionate relationship with music; while melodious tunes are one aspect of it, music has also been used in the past as a form of rebellion, often questioning politics and society. Folk music like <em>baul </em><span style=\"font-style: normal\">and </span><em>Kabigaan, </em><span style=\"font-style: normal\">classical music and the popular </span><em>Rabindra Sangeet </em><span style=\"font-style: normal\">form the traditional structure of Bengali music. Apart from Bengali cinema tunes, a number of rock bands like Mohiner Ghoraguli, Chandra Bindoo, Bhumi and Fossils are popular; these bands sing in Bengali, and successfully blend Bengali folk music into the rock format.</span> <p style=\"margin-bottom: 0in; font-style: normal\">The Dover Lane Music Festival, held every January, explores Indian classical music and features big names as well as new talent. The festival\''s venue, Najrul Mancha is also known to host a number of rock concerts throughout the year. Cultural clubs like Tollygunge Club and CCFC, shopping hubs like South City Mall, establishments like Dalhousie Institute and Weavers Studio Centre for the Arts, and pubs like Someplace Else, Roxy, Trincas and Soho organize a number of rock, jazz and classical music events throughout the year.While Bengal does not have a classical form of dance, folk dances, especially <em>Chhau</em>, have been around for a long time. Also, a number of traditional forms from other parts of India, like Bharatnatyam, Kathak, Odissi and Manipuri, are enjoyed by the people of Kolkata. Dance festivals and events, classical and otherwise, take place throughout the year. Multi-faceted venues like Nandan, Rabindra Sadan, Kala Mandir and Madhusudan Mancha host both, music and dance events throughout the year and are considered the most important in the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Pioneered by acclaimed director Satyajit Ray, the Bengali film industry or Tollywood (a moniker inspired from the popular \''Bollywood\'' in Mumbai) is extremely popular in Kolkata. The love for cinema, however, extends to Bollywood, Hollywood and foreign cinema as well. The Kolkata International Film Festival, the largest of its kind in India, is held every November. The Tri-Continental Film Festival, and Kalpanirjhar International Short Fiction Film Festival are some of the other important film events. Goethe-Institut and Satyajit Ray Film & Television Institute are actively involved in bringing international cinema to the city. For the regular movie-watching experience, a number of old, single-screen cinemas like Priya Cinema still exist; however, modern establishments like INOX can be found all over the city.With abundant talent in acting, direction and script-writing, Kolkata is one of the most active theater-loving cities in the country. In fact, the biggest Indian theater event, Nandikar\''s National Theater Festival, is held here every December at the Academy of Fine Arts. The Kolkata theater calendar is filled with other festivals like National Children\''s Theatre Festival and a host of events and independent plays, leading some to dub the city as the \''theater capital of India\''. Important theater venues include Rabindra Sadan and Madhusudan Mancha.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art & Literature</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With the <em>patachitra </em>being the most important type, folk art from Kolkata is typical of Eastern India. During the British Raj, a specific style known as the Bengal School of Art was created. The movement was spearheaded by British art teacher Ernest Binfield Havel and supported by Rabindranath Tagore\''s nephew Abanindranath Tagore. While it was associated with Indian nationalism, the basic theory was to create a form of art based on Indian spirituality. The movement faded by the early 20th Century; however, Kolkata has produced many eminent Indian contemporary artists ever since. Art exhibitions are regularly featured in local papers, and the most prominent venues include Academy of Fine Arts, Birla Academy of Art and Culture, Weaver\''s Studio Centre of the Arts and Taj Bengal. Kolkata\''s contribution to the world of literature has been tremendous; authors and poets like Rabindranath Tagore, Vikram Seth and the contemporary novelist Amitav Ghosh hail from the city. The love for books is apparent at the Kolkata Book Fair (earlier Calcutta Book Fair and locally, Kolkata Boimela), which happens to be the world\''s largest non-trade book fair and Asia\''s biggest book fair. Regular exhibitions, book readings and launches take place at important venues like Rabindranath Tagore Centre, Asiatic Society, British Council Library, Goethe Institute</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">and bookstores like Oxford, Crossword and Starmark.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Kolkata has a lively nightlife and covers the gamut from laid-back live music venues to swanky cocktail lounges. Park Street is an important nightlife hub: Tantra, Someplace Else, and Roxy are all known to be hot spots among the younger crowd. Venom, HHI Underground and Soho are popular nightclubs as well. International events, DJ nights and live music are a part of the Kolkata nightlife.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Cricket and Football are the two major sports enjoyed by the people of Kolkata. Sourav Ganguly, former Indian Cricket Team captain, was a resident of Behala in the southern fringes of Kolkata. Eden Gardens Stadium in Esplanade has played host to a number of important tournaments in the past. Among the many football clubs in the city, Mohun Bagan and East Bengal are some of the most popular. Football tournaments are played at the Salt Lake Stadium.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Religious Events</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">No other city in India celebrates religious festivals with as much pomp as Kolkata. Commemorating the Hindu goddess <span style=\"text-decoration: none\"><em>Durga</em></span>\''s triumph over <em>Mahishasura</em>, <em>Durga Puja</em> is held every fall and is considered the beginning of the festive season in Kolkata. The main festival of the city sees <em>pandals </em>(temporary temple-like constructions) set up all over the city, and the streets are crowded with people for the six-day long festival. Another festival, considered to be the equivalent of the Indian festival Diwali, is <em>Kali Puja</em> later in the year. Ratha Yatra organized by ISKCON is a street procession where the <em>Jagannath</em> chariot is carried to venues like Maidan.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Family-Friendly</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Nicco Park, Nicco Super Bowl, Nalban Boating Complex, Science City and Millennium Park are best visited at leisure and are a great day out with the kids. There\''s no shortage of family-friendly fun in this vibrant city. From historical sights to museums and theme parks, there\''s lots to explore for visitors of all ages!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Kolkata is a shopping destination for all budgets. From street markets like New Market, Gariahat and Kumortuli for bargain shopping and heritage complexes like Dakshinapan and Swabhumi for handicrafts and textiles to upscale malls and shopping centers like South City Mall and the ultra-luxe Quest Mall for international brands, there is something for everyone in this bustling city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A magnificent marble structure, the Victoria Memorial Hall, built to commemorate Queen Victoria is today a landmark and museum with several galleries housing historic memorabilia, artifacts, sculptures and art. The repository of  a myriad treasures, the Indian Museum is a behemoth filled with everything from rare fossils, Mughal fine art and even an Egyptian mummy! For science buffs, the Science City and Birla Industrial & Technological Museum are fun, educative experiences no matter your age. An insight into the illustrious Rabindranath Tagore awaits at Tagore House Museum. Other specialty museums like the Nehru Children\''s Museum cater to younger visitors.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (430,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Kolkata</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Kolkata was the first developed area of the city; marshy wetlands were cleared and the area was converted into the political and commercial hub of the British East India Company in the late 18th and early-19th Centuries. While on one hand it houses the State Government\''s offices, on the other, beautiful colonial monuments and busy markets thrive. Central Kolkata can be said to fall between the Vidyasagar Setu</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">(Second Hooghly Bridge) and Howrah Bridge (Rabindra Setu), with neighborhoods like B.B.D. Bagh, Maidan and Hastings along the Hooghly, and extending eastwards up to Taltala, Park Street and Park Circus. In between, other neighborhoods include the Esplanade (Chowringhee and New Market), Chandni Chowk, Barabazar (and Posta Market) and Bowbazar. The larger neighborhood of Dharmatala includes parts of Bowbazar, Entally and Moulali but its exact boundaries stretch further. The relatively smaller areas of Outram Ghat and Janbazar also lie within. The area is bound by Strand Road along the Hooghly, AJC Bose Road on the south and east, and Mahatma Gandhi Road on the north. Since the roads here tend to be extremely congested, metros are the fastest mode of transport when in Central Kolkata; it is also well connected by trams and buses. BBD Bagh: Once known as Dalhousie Square, B.B.D. Bagh</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">is a historic area around Lal Dighi and is marked by important political buildings like Writers\'' Building</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">and Raj Bhavan. In the same vicinity, Town Hall, Calcutta High Court, Kolkata GPO</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">and St. John\''s Church</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">with Job Charnock\''s Mausoleum are constructions from the British Raj era and display neo-Renaissance architecture. Along the Hooghly (on Strand Road), you will find a number of government offices like Kolkata Port Trust Headquarters, Central Excise and Customs House. With numerous banks, commercial offices, foreign embassies, the Eastern Railway Headquarters and the Calcutta Stock Exchange, this is the commercial and political hub of the city. Esplanade: Kolkata\''s most beloved neighborhood, Esplanade is colloquially pronounced \''splan-edd\''. However, defying the traditional definition, Esplanade does not run along the Hooghly, but somewhat parallel to it and includes the area earlier known as Chowringhee and the adjoining New Market</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">area. Shaheed Minar and its surrounding street food stalls are just behind the Esplanade Bus Terminus on Dufferin Road, Indian Museum is on the Jawaharlal Nehru Road (formerly Chowringhee Road) and the Tipu Sultan Mosque is on Lenin Sarani. This is one of the most crowded areas of the city and with a number of souvenir shops along New Market, it is a strong tourist magnet. Historic eateries like Ralli\''s and Aminia are also here. On the Hooghly end, near Babughat and Outram Ghat, is the famous Eden Gardens Stadium.Maidan: Marked by large green patches, Maidan is considered to be \''the lungs of Kolkata\''. The area is mainly made up of three large compounds, namely Fort William, Kolkata Race Course and Victoria Memorial. Major attractions like St. Paul\''s Cathedral and Birla Planetarium also fall in this neighborhood. Along the Hooghly (on Strand Road), on the southern end of Fort William is the Prinsep Ghat monument with the Vidyasagar Setu in the background. Smaller areas like Hastings and Kidderpore are to the south. With wide roads and ample greenery, this area is a pleasure to navigate.  Park Street: Lined with restaurants, both old and new, Park Street was once an icon of glamor and grandeur. During the British Raj era, cabaret performances and musical soirées were the order of the day and the area resounded with celebration and laughter on most nights. Today while many of the old restaurants like Mocambo, Moulin Rouge and Trincas still exist, newer additions like Flurys have also been made to the restaurant row. An important landmark near the Park Street Metro Station, is The Asiatic Society. Today, the street is still a popular destination among locals and tourists alike. Park Circus: Park Circus, marked by the Park Circus Maidan is the point where many central streets meet. The famous 7-point Crossing is here. The area has a predominantly Muslim population and is dotted with a number of Masjids and Dargahs. Don Bosco School and Lady Brabourne College are also situated here. The Park Circus Connector to EM Bypass is one of the most important roads of the city.  Taltala: The area gets its name from its Palmyra trees that are locally known as <em>Tal Gachh.</em> The locality is home to a large Muslim community, with the earliest settlements dating back to the early-19th Century. An old locality of Kolkata, Taltala is an important assembly constituency and has a police station within. This area is not especially popular with tourists, as it is mostly a residential area.  Bowbazar & College Street: In the early-19th century, while the central area was known as \''White Town\'' and other smaller areas became \''Native Town\'', the adjoining Baitakkhana, Dharmatala and Janbazar areas fell in the in between zone. At the time Bowbazar came to include a multi-ethnic community of Armenians, Portuguese, Chinese. Today the <em>bazar</em> or market area is famous for its variety of jewelry and music shops marked by narrow lanes and large crowds.A few minutes to the north is the famous College Street area, where visitors can find the Presidency College, Hindu School and the Indian Coffee House. Burrabazar & Posta Market: Burrabazar literally translates to \''Big Market\'' and consists of a large wholesale market. The area had always been reserved as a market; however, its current status is in sharp contrast to the wealthy merchants that dominated the area during the British era. Posta Market, although spread over a smaller area, has more or less the same story and is now considered a part of Burrabazar. This market stocks a wide variety of goods from textiles to tea.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">South Kolkata</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">South Kolkata is a well planned area, with somewhat clearer divisions of neighborhoods within. While a major part consists of residential spaces, a number of attractions, shopping options and restaurants can be found here as well. Bound by AJC Bose Road on the north, neighborhoods like Alipore, Bhowanipore and Ballygunge are a stone\''s throw away from Central Kolkata. Further down south are the major areas of Kalighat, Lake Gardens and Tollygunge. Jodhpur Park and Jadavpur are predominantly residential areas. Jadavpur is famous for the Jadavpur University. Alipore: Just south of Maidan, continuing the pattern of clean roads and greenery is the Alipore area. A few kilometers away from Victoria Memorial and Fort William, Alipore is where the infamous Alipore Jail stands. With major landmarks like National Library, Agri Horticultural Gardens and Zoological Gardens, the area ensures easy navigation. Taj Bengal, a luxury offering, is also found here. The New Alipore area is an extension of this neighborhood, mostly housing government and commercial offices. Bhowanipore: Situated between Alipore and Ballygunge and just north of the Kalighat & Lake Gardens area, Bhowanipore has a balanced mix of residential areas and commercial streets. Netaji Bhavan on Elgin Road is an important landmark. Considering its proximity to Central Kolkata, Bhowanipore has a number of strategically located budget stay options on Sarart Bose Road. Ballygunge: Ballygunge is a posh locality with many modern residential areas. As you enter via the Syed Amir Ali Avenue, Birla Mandir and Calcutta Ice Skating Rink are prominent landmarks. Restaurants like 6 Ballygunge Place, Red Hot Chilli Pepper and Mainland China are popular haunts. The Goethe Institut, Birla Industrial & Technological Museum (BITM) and ISKCON are also in this area.  Gariahat: Although Gariahat is considered to be part of Ballygunge, the busy market place is a far cry from the relatively modern Ballygunge surroundings. Situated at Rash Behari Avenue, the popular Gariahat Market is just off the Gariahat Crossing.  Kalighat & Lake Gardens: Kalighat is a densely populated neighborhood with the main attraction being the Kalighat Kali Temple. Other important landmarks include Lake Kalibari, Ramakrishna Mission Institute of Culture, Golpark and Birla Academy of Art & Culture. Major Durga Puja venues like Deshapriya Park and Triangular Park are also situated here. In the same vicinity, Lake Gardens is the area around the Dhakuria Lake or Rabindra Sarobar and includes important event venues like Najrul Mancha and Rabindra Sarobar Stadium. Lake Gardens has a peaceful atmosphere, surrounded by greenery, and as a result dotted with young couples.  Tollygunge: Named after William Tolly who was involved in the early development of the area, Tollygunge is home to the Bengali film industry or \''tollywood\''. The rapidly developing residential area is also known for its concentration of schools, colleges and institutes. Tollygunge Club, Royal Calcutta Golf Club and South City Mall are major landmarks in this area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North Kolkata</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">North Kolkata has a typical environment: wide main roads with a constant flow of traffic, narrow by lanes and buildings that date back to the 19th Century are some of the main features of this area. Most of the neighborhoods within are historically important, although may not have as many touristic attractions. The area tends to be crowded with people all the time. Using the tram service is one of the best ways to tour some of these neighborhoods; trams take you through the areas at a leisurely pace. Dubbed as the \''cradle of Bengal Renaissance\'', the northern neighborhood of Jorasanko is the site of Jorasanko Thakur Bari - Rabindranath Tagore\''s ancestral home - and includes the important institution of Adi Brahmo Samaj.  Large market areas like Shyambazar, Shobhabazar, Kumortuli and Bagbazar are a display of the bygone grandeur. However, the forlorn buildings somehow create a sense of strange nostalgia.  Another northern neighborhood, Jorabagan, is said to be the place where East India Company employee Job Charnock first landed. It also includes the Hindu cremation ground known as Nimtala Ghat; a memorial stands on the site where Rabindranath Tagore was cremated. Chitpur and Cossipore are neighborhoods that lie further up north and are largely industrial areas with a number of factories and <em>godowns</em>. The Gun and Shell Factory in Cossipore holds the distinction of being the oldest functional factory in the Indian subcontinent.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">East Kolkata</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">East Kolkata is distinctly different from any other part of the city: with the planned township of Salt Lake City and the upcoming Rajarhat area, this part of the city is truly metropolitan. Tangra, Kolkata\''s Chinatown, is also included in East Kolkata. Tangra: Kolkata\''s Chinatown had more than 350 tanneries at one point of time and the residing Chinese made the leather industry in Kolkata a profitable one, providing employment to many. Since the Chinese also bought their cuisine to the area, a new kind of fusion cuisine, made to suit the Indian and specifically, Bengali palette was created and this came to be known as \''Indian Chinese\''. Salt Lake City: Built between 1958 and 1965, Salt Lake City, like the name suggests is a city planned around salt water bodies. The intelligent design seamlessly blends the natural beauty of the area with modern infrastructure. The saucer shaped area is divided into five sectors and is defined by wide roads and ample space. Around the Central Park, attractions like Nalban Boating Complex, Nicco Park and Salt Lake Stadium, shopping complexes like Swabhumi and Mani Square Mall and a number of restaurant complexes and entertainment venues are scattered across the sectors. This is the IT hub of the city and also has a number of residential areas and facilities like schools and colleges.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dum Dum</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Dum Dum houses the Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose International Airport and is about 12 kilometers away from Salt Lake City and 18 kilometers away from the city center.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Howrah</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Although a different city on the western banks of the Hooghy, Howrah is often considered a part of Kolkata. The Grand Trunk Road is an extremely important trade route and connects Kolkata to important national highways. The Howrah Station is one of the most important landmarks, with a busy bus stand and a jetty stop around it. The Acharya Jagadish Chandra Bose Botanical Garden is in the Shalimar area of Howrah.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northern Fringes</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Pilgrimage spots like Dakshineswar Kali Temple and Baranagar (Kancher Mandir and Path Bari) are situated in the northern fringes of Kolkata.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Southern Fringes</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Areas like Barisha, Garia and Joka are at the extreme south of the city. These are mostly residential surroundings that do not include many touristic attractions. However, a number of prestigious <em>Durga Puja </em>venues fall in this part of the city</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
