 (458,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are enough museums and galleries in Canberra to keep you busy for a number of days. To start, tour the National Museum and National Gallery of Australia, then move along to the National Portrait Gallery. After a few days in the city, set your sights on more specific venues like Questacon - The National Science and Technology Center. And before you go, do as every visitor to the city should do and stop by the Australian War Memorial.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Whether you prefer mainstream or alternative cinema, this city has something for you. There are large cinema complexes in each town center, like Hoyts in Belconnen and Woden, meaning you have easy access to the latest on-screen adventures at all times. For international films and cult favorites, try the National Film and Sound Archive\''s Arc Cinema.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Live Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Canberra\''s music scene caters to all possible tastes. Local and interstate bands perform at most clubs and pubs in the city while several other venues specialize in live music. Well-known Australian artists perform on a regular basis at Tilley\''s in Lyneham. Blues and jazz lovers crowd such venues as PJ O\''reilly\''s and the Canberra Southern Cross Club. Irish music has is also popular, and there live performances every Sunday at the Phoenix. Popular international acts visit the city more often these days, particularly at venues such as the Royal Theatre and AIS arena.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The latest dance music is always the flavor in Canberra, and various nightclubs cater to late-night dancing on the weekends. The highest concentration of clubs is found in the city center and around Manuka. New clubs are popping up all the time and many offer specialty nights that cater to most musical tastes. Canberra\''s only casino—Casino Canberra—has entertainment available in every arena and is guaranteed to keep you going well into the night whether you enjoy dancing, dining, live music or simply gambling.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Canberra hosts a full annual calendar of festivals, many of them internationally famous and visited by tourists from across the globe. The best known and loved of these festivals is Floriade, which is held in September and October each year when the shores of Lake Burley Griffin at Commonwealth Park are transformed into a botanical masterpiece. In April, the National Folk Festival is a lovely celebration of music in Exhibition Park. Sports fans are also well taken care of in Canberra given its many rugby teams, including the Canberra Raiders.&nbsp;</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (459,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Canberra</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The city center is split into two areas: the inner north and the inner south. The inner north is filled with students and young professionals, and in turn, it fills a demand for chic boutiques, vegan eateries, and the like. If you\''re into all things trendy, be sure to tour the inner north while in town.In contrast, the inner south is home to many of the city\''s most cherished landmarks, including Parliament House and Lake Burley Griffin. The city\''s political center, the inner south retains its charm through a strong local business culture fostered by the families and professionals that live in the area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Belconnen</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A relatively residential area, Belconnen sits northwest of central Canberra. It also houses a fair number of university students. Much like in the city center, there is an artificial lake at the heart of the district, Lake Ginninderra. Elsewhere, the Westfield Mall in the Belconnen Town Centre serves as one of the largest commercial hubs around.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Tuggeranong</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">You\''ll find lots of family homes in Tuggeranong also, many of which date back generations. You\''ll find cultural activity at the Tuggeranong Arts Centre and shoppers galore at the Tuggeranong Hyperdome. The scenic district also makes for an excellent backdrop if you\''re looking for a lakeside stroll and a dose of fresh air.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Woden Valley</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The biggest draw to Woden Valley is the Woden Town Centre, home to the Westfield shopping mall. The area also hosts a number of sports teams worth checking out if you\''re curious about the local scene. Among those with the biggest fans bases are the Woden Rams rugby team and Australian-rules football team the Woden Blues.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Gungahlin</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Gungahlin is a fairly bustling district with an eclectic mix of residents. It has a modest commercial center, and there are plenty of scenic spots around, among them the Mulligans Flat Woodland Sanctuary and Yerrabi Pond District Park. Given the presence of the light rail, travel in and around Gungahlin is easy and efficient.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
