 (505,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art and Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Owing to the city\''s cosmopolitan character, the Caracas art scene is fascinating and worthwhile. Every day you can find some sort of cultural activity and, particularly at the weekend, Caracas\'' talented artists show off their creativity, to the many <em>Caraqueños</em> and travelers who are out and about. There are always a number of cultural centers with something on. Some of the places where you can get a good idea of what Venezuelan art has to offer are the Museum of Contemporary Art and the National Art Gallery. The Ateneo de Caracas and the Quinta Anauco are some of the places that display a tremendous amount of Venezuelan art as well.  The museums of Caracas are distinguished by their beauty and magnificence, not only in architecture, but also the artifacts exhibited inside.  The Children\''s Museum, a family-friendly museum that encourages learning through active science and technological displays is a popular spot to visit in the city. The Museum of Natural Sciences also follows a similar pattern. The Museo Bolíviariano, a venerated spot dedicated to the importance of the Latin American independence at the heart of which was Simón Bolívar, is one of the best museums in the city. Other smaller museums include the Carlos Cruz Díez Museum, a stunning repository of more than 2500 printing and design-related objects, the 17th Century Casa Natal del Libertador Simón Bolívar that housed the great revolutionary, the Transport Museum and the Arturo Michelena Museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">When it comes to theaters there also is a great variety to choose from. One of the most famous theater groups is Sala Rajatabla, which stages its plays at the Ateneo de Caracas. Other theaters well worth a visit are the National Theater, a favored spot for traditional <em>zarzuelas, </em>or theatrical, opera-like performances that alternate between music and drama, and the Foundación Celarg that hosts an excellent performing arts program. The El Teatro Municipal is one of the city\''s oldest opera houses, although it is no longer the home of the national opera. This honor now belongs to the Teresa Carreño Cultural Complex, that houses two concert halls - José Félix Ribas and the Ríos Reyna - and is also home to the Venezuela Symphony Orchestra. The Teatro Municipal however, does host the Municipal Symphony Orchestra of Caracas.   The two best places to enjoy classical, lyric chants, chamber music, latin, jazz and Venezuelan music are the Complejo Cultural Teresa Carreño, the Centro de Cultura Corp Banca and the Aula Magna located within the Central University of Venezuela. Every month each presents a recital from symphonic orchestras and guests from abroad.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightclubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While nightlife in Caracas may not be what it used to be, Caracas has found methods to entertain its denizens. Find local bars like Juan Sebastián that serenade visiting crowds with jazz performances, or Le Club, one of the city\''s oldest and most premier clubs that operates between Thursday and Saturday. The Buddha Bar Caracas, located in the city\''s prime neighborhood for nightlife, Las Mercedes, is also wildly popular among the city\''s well-heeled lot. If you love a good dose of quirkiness, the Hog Heaven will serve you well. A funky motorcycle bar, this atmospheric spot is great for mingling with locals, listening to live music, or unwinding with a beer on its patio. The 360º Roof Bar is also a good option.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (506,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">El Silencio (Downtown)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This neighborhood offers history at a glance. El Silencio proudly showcases Venezuela\''s rich history, with architectural gems from the 17th and 18th Centuries. This part of Caracas is well worth a visit. Places such as Plaza Bolívar and the Catedral Metropolitana de Caracas, a 1665 structure, form some of its main landmarks. Other notable structures, longstanding vestiges of the city and country\''s treasured heritage include the Casa Natal El Libertador, the house where Simón Bolívar, the Liberator, was born and the 17th century La Casa Amarilla, once a prison, but now used by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The El Capitolio Nacional, seat of the legislative council, the Teatro Nacional, and the El Panteón Nacional, the resting place for prominent Venezuelans are also located here. While enjoying a sightseeing tour in the downtown area, prized architectural landmarks such as the Basílica de Santa Teresa, the El Palacio de Miraflores, which is the presidential palace, and the Museo Arturo Michelena, should not be forgotten.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parque Central Complex</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Home to innovation, architecture, art and culture, and the country\''s two highest towers - if there is any place that shows how modern Caracas is, it is El Parque Central. Located less than a few kilometers to the southeast of La Plaza Bolívar, the park contains a concrete structure with two 53-floor octagonal towers and residential buildings. However, if it is not architecture and structural designs, but rather culture that takes your interest, you will be pleasantly surprised to find a great number of art centers here. In the Complejo Cultural Teresa Carreño, the arts reach their utmost expression, through theater, dance, concerts and ballet performances among others.  You will find a large concentration of museums in this area, all located within walking distance of one another. The The Museum of Contemporary Art in Caracas, a contemporary art museum, and the Museo de los Niños where adults as well as children will find enjoyment surround the Parque Los Cabos. Museo de Ciencias Naturales, the Museum of Fine Arts, and the Galería de Arte Nacional, a landmark art institution which possesses a permanent collection of more than 3,500 works of art are also located in the vicinity. Nearby is the immense Botanical Garden, and the Ateneo de Caracas, where you will find a cinema, theaters, an art gallery, a cafeteria and a bookstore. To the south of the Botanical Gardens, you will find the largest university in Caracas, the Universidad Central de Venezuela.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sabana Grande & Las Mercedes</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Even though this is not quite a tourist mecca, here we will find the famous Sabana Grande Boulevard, more than three-quarters of a mile and surrounded by shops, hotels and restaurants. The neighborhood of Las Mercedes is one of the most busy and popular areas in the city. It is characterized as being the center of fashion and Caracas\'' nightlife. Here you will be able to enjoy yourself, go to a good restaurant or to a classy nightclub, all in the same area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Altamira, Chacao & El Hatillo</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Altamira is one of the most pleasant neighborhoods in the city, which normally includes some smaller districts such as La Castellana, Los Palos Grandes, Bello Campo and La Floresta. It is an important business area and is the location of the Plaza Francia which has a large obelisk, a monumental trademark of Caracas. Chacao is a district teeming with corporate towers and skyscrapers, strewn amid which are various shopping centers such as the Centro Comercial Sambil Chacao. El Hatillo is ideal for those that may want to escape the hustle and bustle from the city. It is a small village filled with old houses, artisanal shops, cafes and restaurants.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
