 (523,'Historic homes overlook the shore on Battery Street.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (524,'The U.S. Custom House overlooks East Bay Street and the harbor. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (525,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music and Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">You\''ll find some of Lowcountry\''s top music venues in this city full of Southern charm. The Charleston Symphony Orchestra is conducted by music director David Stahl and is the largest year-round performing arts organization in South Carolina. The orchestra performs a wide spectrum of music for adults and children through its concert series. You\''ll find more contemporary offerings at the Charleston Music Hall that invites both local artists and international performers to its stage. Jazz has always shaped the city\''s music scene, and there are a number of bars and clubs that still pay homage to the classics. Under the klieg lights, the Charleston Stage Company performs plays and musicals at the historic Dock Street Theatre. The North Charleston Performing Arts Center seats over 2500 patrons and is one of the largest performance spaces in the city, it\''s a great venue for Broadway-style shows and big-name concerts. You\''ll find some of the best contemporary theater at the PURE Theatre while the folks at the 34 West Theater Company offer up classic theater fun in the heart of Downtown Charleston. From small independent companies to international troupes, this city has it all.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Exhibits</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the most historic cities in the United States, Charleston is packed with history. You\''ll want to make a trip to the Charleston Museum, considered one of the first in the country. The historic sea fort, Fort Sumter National Monument is where you can explore the city\''s maritime legacy. The Karpeles Manuscript Museum is one of seven Karpeles museums in the country. Charleston\''s African-American heritage is preserved at the Avery Research Center for African-American History and Culture. Papers, photographs, oral histories and other materials are maintained in the archives. The Jewish Heritage Collection of the College of Charleston\''s Robert Scott Small Library recounts the Jewish experience in South Carolina from colonial times to the present. For the aquatic lover, there is the South Carolina Aquarium.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The downtown Charleston City Market offers a wide selection of art, jewelry, clothing books and collectibles and is one of the best place to really take in the city\''s vibrant spirit in a local atmosphere. Find international designer and upscale labels at the Shops at Charleston Place or explore the offerings at one of the city\''s longest running retailers, M. Dumas and Sons, a men\''s clothier established in 1917. For a truly exclusive shopping experience, the people at Hampden Clothing will get you outfitted in the latest luxury fashions. Antique collectors will find several well-curated stores to search for their next collectible.<h2 style=\"position: absolute; width: 1px; height: 1px; top: -1000em; overflow: hidden; color: #222222; font-family: arial,sans-serif\" class=\"hd\">Search Results</h2></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Charleston is home to several sports teams. The South Carolina Sting Rays, a Buffalo Sabres affiliate, were in the playoffs each of their first eight years of existence beginning in 1993. The Charleston River Dogs baseball club is a Class-A affiliate of the Tampa Bay Rays in the South Atlantic League. You\''ll find the best sports events at the North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center, the MUSC Health Stadium home turf of the Charleston Battery of the United Soccer League, and the Joseph P. Riley, Jr. Park.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Harbor and</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Beaches</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Charleston Harbor has several opportunities for fun boating. The Ocean Sailing Academy provides U.S. Sailing Certification courses from the Charleston Harbor Marina and Bohicket Marina. For experienced sailors, the academy also charters boats as large as 46 feet. If you like to fish, Fin Stalker Charters boasts year-round fishing with Charleston native Captain Chris Chavis. Captain J.R. Waits, of Fish Call Charters, is another experienced guide, who will take the experienced and the novice on light tackle and fly-fishing excursions.For quieter times, Charleston Waterfront Park has 12 acres of shrubbery, trees and benches overlooking the water. The park includes a 400-foot (121.92-meter) long wharf and fishing pier. Nearby Beachwalker Park furnishes sandy beaches and 450 feet (137.16 meters) of designated swimming area. Lifeguards are on duty seasonally. Folly Beach is located near Charleston and has a nice selection of seafood restaurants. Isle of Palms is known for its sandwich shops as well as its waterfront.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (526,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Charleston has a lot for visitors to see and do. Besides the historic churches, buildings, and landmarks, there are plenty of opportunities for shopping. Visitors find that Downtown is a convenient starting point for getting to know Charleston as it is a vibrant combination of old and new, offering diverse attractions suitable for just about anyone.The Historic District is the oldest part of town and a lot of the buildings and houses have been preserved. Tours are available, like the Historic Homes Walk, which will allow you to learn more about the amazing architecture dating back to the mid-18th Century. Charleston is also known for its cuisine. You\''ll be able to find great options throughout the city and especially in this district, such as Hyman\''s Seafood Restaurant.King Street is one of the main areas within the historic district and is home to a number of independent boutiques, designer stores, bars and cafes, and a great selection of some of the best restaurants in the city. Harleston Village is an eclectic neighborhood that\''s full of interesting places to explore. You can stroll around Colonial Lake and in the evening its a great place to watch the sunset. Walk through the neighborhood and admire the stately mansions, later pop into one of the local cafes for a bite and a cup of joe.The elegant French Quarter with its beautiful mansions and streets steeped in history is one of the oldest neighborhoods in the city. The cobblestoned streets are home to institutions like the Dock Street Theatre. Take a self guided tour to appreciate all the neighborhood has to offer. South of Broad is one of the Downtown Districts most exclusive neighborhoods. Its antebellum mansions speak of a bygone era and its storied streets are full of Victorian charm. If you take a carriage tour, it will most likely take you through this enchanting district.Cannonborough/Elliotborough are at the epicenter of downtown revitalization and is home to a youthful and creative crowd. Contemporary restaurants, galleries, and innovative performance spaces make this the perfect place to experience a different side of this historic city!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Uptown and Wagener Terrace</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Uptown Charleston is where much of the city\''s young professional crowd live. You\''ll find craftsman style homes here, many of them dating from the 1920s to the 1960s. Hampton Park, a 60-acre (24.2 hectares) public park is a lovely place to spend an afternoon. Among the neighborhood\''s many cafes and restaurants, the Cooper River Brewing is the place for a pint of craft beer brewed on the premises.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Mount Pleasant</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Founded in 1680 and located to the East of Charleston, Mount Pleasant is known for its fine dining. Whether it\''s breakfast, lunch, or dinner, you will find that this area is packed with all different types of eateries. Mount Pleasant is also the home of one of the biggest naval & maritime museums in the world, Patriots Point Naval & Maritime Museum. Tour boats are available from Mount Pleasant to view Fort Sumter, the site where the Civil War began. This historic city also has Patriots Point Golf Links, a challenging and beautiful golf course.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North Charleston</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">North Charleston is the main business and transportation location for the southern half of South Carolina. Both the International Airport and Amtrak Station are located here. Adding to the bustle of North Charleston is the 14,000-seat North Charleston Coliseum, home of the South Carolina Stingrays hockey team. Also, a 2,341-seat North Charleston Performing Arts showcases touring Broadway shows along with other music concerts and performances.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (527,'Country|United States|Population|137,447 (city); 548,404 (metropolitan area)|Elevation|20 feet / 6 meters',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (528,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Dubbed \"<em>The Queen City</em>,\" after Queen Charlotte, the wife of King George III, Charlotte is an undeniably historic American city. Today, it is one of the top 20 fastest-growing metropolitan areas in the United States, and home to an endless array of interesting attractions, popular restaurants, and raging late-night hotspots.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
