 (687,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bars & Pubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A truly international city, Dubai, as most metropolises its size, has a vibrant nightlife scene. You\''ll find bars, pubs, cafes, clubs, and more to pique your interest. Whether you\''re in the mood for a chic evening out sipping on cocktails or a high-octane dance party hosted by the world\''s best DJs, you\''ll find it here. For the ultimate beach club experience, head to Summersalt at the Madinat Jumeirah. For the classic pub experience, The Irish Village brings the traditional Celtic pub to the heart of Dubai. For exceptional views, while sipping your glass of bubbly, Skyview Bar is your top choice.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">An interesting mix of cultural education and shopping is the Heritage & Diving Village, which simultaneously teaches visitors about the old days in Dubai and operates as a craft fair. If you truly do want to learn about local life, you\''ll want to develop an understanding of Islam, which you can do at the Sharjah Islamic Museum. For history specific to Dubai\''s recent past, check out the H.H. Sheikh Saeed House. It served as the seat of government during part of the 20th Century, during the reign of the current Sheikh\''s grandfather. Being on the shores of a large sea inlet known as The Creek, Dubai\''s history is full of boat culture. You can learn about this part of the city\''s history at Narish Khyma, the boat museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">From atmospheric souks to world-class malls stocked with virtually every major brand and designer, Dubai is a shopper\''s paradise. Dubai is world-renowned for its shopping malls, which take relaxation and atmosphere seriously. The Dubai Shopping Festival, held annually is a major draw for visitors, held every year through January and February. Among the top shopping destinations, the luxurious Mall of the Emirates, the BurJuman, and the Dubai Mall have not only a plethora of shops to choose from but also fun attractions and entertainment for the whole family.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theme Parks and Family Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While we\''re on the topic of entertainment for the family, we can\''t go without mentioning the huge number of theme parks and water parks that Dubai has. Thanks to Dubai\''s searing heat, water parks are one of the best ways to cool off and beat the climbing temperatures. Of the many available options, Aquaventure Waterpark and Wild Wadi Waterpark are the most popular. For those who want to go one-degree cooler, Dubai even has a Ski Dubai, an indoor ski theme parks where you can zip down the slopes. Legoland Dubai is especially fun for the younger travelers, as is IMG World of Adventure.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater and Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">More than just shopping and theme parks can be found in Dubai. Those looking for a cultural evening out will find several options to glam up for an evening. Among the top choices in the city, Dubai Opera and the Madinat Theatre host internationally renowned artists alongside national players. For music lovers, Dubai is a global stage for contemporary music. The city hosts some of the hottest stars who add Dubai to their tours of international cities. Among the favorite venues to catch top talent, MusicHall and Dubai Media City Amphitheater are worth checking out. More intimate venues like the Fridge and The Music Room are also noteworthy for their great selection of artists.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (688,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Dubai</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The heart of the city\''s economic hub, Downtown Dubai boasts some of the city\''s most iconic sights. The Dubai Mall, the world\''s largest mall, the Burj Khalifa and the JW Marriott Marquis all contribute to the city\''s ever-changing skyline. A myriad of family-friendly options, like the Dubai Ice Rink, Dubai Fountains, and Dubai Aquarium and Underwater Zoo, mean there is something here for all ages.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dubai Creek and Old Dubai</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Tourists and business travelers will find something to provoke their imagination in this busy and cosmopolitan city. This natural sea-water inlet cuts through the middle of the city. But just around the corner, you might come upon an ancient house or some other testament to the rich heritage of this city. Dubai is able to boast an Arabian experience in a protected, open-minded city. Even the desert itself holds tourist appeal.Old Dubai is divided into two parts. Diera on the north side of the Creek and Bur Dubai to the south. They are connected by a tunnel and two bridges. But no matter which side you find yourself on, a stroll along its banks will remind you of the city\''s centuries-old trading traditions. And each side has everything you might want, from great hotels and stores to mosques and <em>souks</em> (bustling markets).Diera</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">:</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Diera is a district filled with banks and office buildings, showcasing Dubai\''s strong business sense. It can be found northeast of the Creek, and is filled with many merchants selling local goods, such as artwork, jewelry, fruits and vegetables, spices and traditional clothing. There are also fortune tellers, snake oil salesmen and street performers on every corner. You could spend all day wandering through the Diera, so don\''t be afraid to bargain. You never know what you\''ll end up going home with. Bur Dubai: Southwest of the Creek you\''ll find the other half of Dubai\''s business district, Bur Dubai. In Dubai\''s early years, this district was a large fishing village that generated revenue to feed the entire town. Here you will find many important monuments that testify to Dubai\''s rich history. The former palace of Sheikh Saeed Al Maktoum, built in 1896, is a must-see. It has been completely restored, allowing guests to examine the stunning Arab architecture first-hand. The Dubai Museum in Al Fahidi Fort is also an important historical landmark. Learn about the history of Dubai through exhibitions of period pieces ranging from jewelry to pearl diving tools. The Heritage & Diving Village is another great place to discover Dubai\''s early days. Explore the components of an authentic fishing village and learn how men foraged for pearls and established Dubai\''s successful pearl industry. For a glimpse of Old Dubai, head to the old Bastakiya district. The narrow streets will remind you of days gone by and the old wind towers are the mark of Dubai. Before electricity, the wind towers brought air into the homes to help cool them. This district has been restored to show tourists the true old Dubai. Just outside the central city to the north is the neighboring emirate of Shariah. And to the west and south are the neighborhoods of Satwa, Jumeirah, and Umm Suqeim.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jumeirah</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hugging the coast, Jumeirah is home to the glittering Burj al Arab hotel, the Madinat Jumeirah hotel alongside its adjacent <em>souk</em>, and the pedestrianized Beach mall, Jumeirah is where most of the city\''s landmarks can be found. Wild Wadi Waterpark is located in Jumeirah, and is a great place for families to have fun, relax and cool off. If your interests run to archeology, there are three main excavations that you can explore: one at Ghusais, another at Al Sufooh and a third one at Jumeirah. The first two are 2,000-year old graveyards and the third dates from the 7th to 15th Century and contains artifacts and more. Visitors must obtain a permit from the Dubai Museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dubai Marina</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Dubai Marina Mall sits in the center of the awe-inspiring Dubai Marina district. A short walk takes you to the docks, where the waterfront restaurants feature al-fresco terraces and dazzling views. The surrounding skyscrapers are beautifully reflected in the marina\''s waters and the fascinating Cayan Tower with its twisting facade can be spotted from here. Food enthusiasts should make a trip to Pier 7, this tower hosts a different restaurant on every one of its seven levels.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Palm Jumeirah</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Palm Jumeirah is one of the world\''s largest islands made by man. This unique island is where the Atlantis hotel is situated, known for its ocean-inspired design complete with arches and elegant turrets. The district has a plethora of luxury hotels dotting its shores; some of the world\''s most well-regarded luxury brands can be found here. For visitors who choose to stay in a more affordable part of town, the upscale restaurants, opulent spas, and gorgeous beaches complete with sweeping views of the Gulf make this worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Al Quoz</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A hip industrial suburb known for its emerging art scene, Al Quoz is a great spot to discover new artists and modern Arabic art. The majority of galleries are focused around Alserkal Avenue, including private galleries and museums like Carbon 12. and the Salsali Private Museum. A number of cafes have also popped up in the area to cater to the artists and visitors.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Media City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Media city is as the name suggests, the city\''s media hub where a concentration of the television, news and magazine publishers are located. Here, you\''ll find the Media City Amphitheatre that hosts an eclectic line up of concerts and other events around the year. A number of restaurants and cafes have sprung up here to cater to the professional crowd.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
