 (721,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Lying low in the Tanana Valley, Fairbanks takes up a central space in the Land of the Midnight Sun. Blessed with a pristine frontier much like other parts of Alaska, Fairbanks is the gateway that leads to Denali in the south and the Arctic Circle further north. Its wintry disposition makes it a hotbed for outdoor activities like snowshoeing, skiing and ice-sledding, and it is also the starting point for the Yukon Quest - a fascinating dog-sled race held annually.  Summers are short-lived, yet warm, carpeting its otherwise steely landscape in full bloom. The Georgeson Botanical Garden is a good place to witness this phenomenon. Its magnetism for adventure notwithstanding, Fairbanks\'' mainland features many a diverse attraction. Whether it is a brush with its gold rush history, its innate cultural pull or its artistic pursuits, Fairbanks transcends its geographically endowed limits. Fairbanks is the largest city in the Alaskan Interior, and is bordered by the Chena River to its west.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
