 (727,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Fairbanks wears its glorious history proudly, as is evident from its well-maintained museums. The best place to explore Alaska\''s golden past is at Pioneer Park, where the history of the Gold Rush is brought alive through various museums and exhibits. Make a stop at the Tanana Valley Railroad Museum to see the original locomotive that played a huge part during the frenzied era of the Gold Rush. Nearby, the Pioneer Air Museum explains the city\''s brush with the aviation industry, through varying exhibits such as maps, flight instruments and aircrafts from the bygone era. Closer to Downtown, the Fairbanks Community Museum traces the city\''s history through trying times such as the 1967 floods, its proficiency in the sport of Dog Mushing, and the Klondike Gold Rush. Another museum that pays tribute to Fairbanks\'' natural phenomena, such as the Aurora Borealis, is the Museum of the North, located at the University of Alaska. The Fountainhead Antique Auto Museum is also a popular museum that is home to 70 vintage cars from the post-Gold Rush era.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Several of Fairbanks\'' art galleries house artwork inspired by Alaska\''s dramatic landscape, and are well worth a visit. The lesser known Rose Berry Alaska Art Gallery at the UAF Museum of the North displays the myriad facets of Alaskan heritage and geography through unusual exhibits. From ivory carvings that date back 2000 years, to captivating Alaskan art, the museum transports you back in time. Must see exhibits include the permanent exhibition by John Luther Adams, a beautiful installation that captures Alaska\''s unique climate and topography through different mediums such as music and lighting. The Alaska House Art Gallery is another storied museum. The brainchild of Alaskan artist Claire Fejes, the gallery displays several artworks created by Claire herself, besides those of 200 other local artists.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Located at a stone\''s throw from the Alaska Salmon Bake, the Palace Theatre brings alive the history of the \''Golden Heart City\'' of Fairbanks. One of its productions, the Golden Heart Revue, is a brilliant musical comedy about life in the city. At the Morris Thompson Cultural & Visitors Center, immerse yourself in the unique culture of the native Athabascan Indians with the Tanana Chiefs Conference Cultural Programs. The programs bring about a festive air through traditional dancing and music. The Davis Concerts Hall has a similar atmosphere during the annually held Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival and the Festival of Native Arts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Fairbanks has a handful of live music venues that feature local flavor most weekends. Don\''t expect to see any big, recognizable performers here, as most venues play host to obscure local bands. But if local acoustic folk is something that interests you, haunts like Kodiak Jack\''s and The Blue Loon host live music nights on the weekends. Else, listen to local musicians at the \''time out at Noon\'' concert held every Thursday in Pioneer Park. This hour-long concert lets you listen in on the latest local talent for free. If classical music is more to your liking, then the Davis Concerts Hall at the University of Alaska hosts the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra every season.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoor Recreation</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Fairbanks\'' rugged, snow-carpeted landscape is a favorable spot to engage in outdoor activities. Summer brings in relaxing activities like berry picking at the Murphy and Ester domes, to cycling along the peaceful scenery of the Ester Dome Singletrack Happy Valley Trail. Winter has a slew of activities planned for you, from traditional Dog Mushing tours, to chasing the soul-stirring Northern Lights. For more conventional winter adventures, plan a skiing trip at the Birch Hill Ski & Snowboard Area, or Skiland. Families with kids can take a trip to walk with Santa\''s helpers at the Running Reindeer Ranch.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (728,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Fairbanks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A look at its city center, and it is hard to believe that this lively milieu coexists with the arduous climate of Alaska. The Golden Heart Plaza is the epicenter of most activities and landmarks in Fairbanks. With the river to one side, this picturesque area is teeming with art galleries, restaurants, local watering holes and small shops. As you stroll the city streets, you will see the occasional historic building along the way. Some of the buildings can be traced back to its glorious gold rush days. The Fairbanks City Hall is situated here as well. Downtown Fairbanks is also the gathering place for annual festivities, such as the Winter Carnival or the Midnight Sun Festival.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West Fairbanks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The western corridor of Fairbanks is mostly famous for Pioneer Park. This outdoor museum and entertainment complex is a fairytale village in disguise. Lit up in twinkling lights when the winter sun gives way, Pioneer Park draws attention to the city\''s rich history. Housed within the park is the Pioneer Air Museum, the Tanana Valley Railroad Museum, a mini-golf playground, a center for arts and pavilion for playing. During summers, the park doubles up as a concert venue of sorts, with local musicians entertaining visitors.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Fort Jonathan Wainwright</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Lying toward the eastern end of Fairbanks, this region consists of largely underdeveloped land. It is primarily used as base for Ladd Army Airfield, a military airfield built in 1938. The only other landmark in the area is the Chena Bend Golf Course.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outlying Areas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Several of the city\''s prominent attractions are part of the larger Fairbanks area. The North Pole for instance, lies a short drive outside city limits. Don\''t mistake this for the legitimate pole that lies further north. Then again, a closer look at this suburb may have you rubbing your eyes in confusion, to fully ascertain the difference. This festive suburb has everything you hope to see in Christmas, right from Santa Claus\''s abode and reindeer, to teeny-sized snowflakes settling quietly on the ground. While you\''re here, make a trip to the neighboring Chena Lake Recreation Area. Besides being home to spectacular views of the Alaskan landscape, it is also the place to chase the elusive Northern Lights. The University of Alaska campus lies a little outside city limits, but is well worth the visit. Take in the spectacular architecture and explore mini attractions within, such as the Museum of the North, and the Georgeson Botanical Garden. This sprawling campus is also home to the Geophysical Institute and the Large Animal Research Station.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
