 (810,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Genoan cinema was revolutionized a few years ago when the multiscreen Cineplex was opened. It has nine screens, seats 3,000 and offers advanced technology, comfortable seats, and free parking. The building is in the Magazzini del Cotone in the old port area, and the largest two rooms were designed by Renzo Piano. They show commercial films but some quality works are assured by the Istituto Luce, a partner in the enterprise. national competition for short films, the Genoa Film Festival will take place here in June. In the city centre, the Universale has three large screens and Dolby surround sound. It offers commercial, quality films. For something slightly different, go to Il Corallo, which has two screens and more adventurous programs or the Ariston, which alternates between international and Italian.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Carlo Felice Theatre offers a varied selection of opera as well as jazz and rock concerts. The building was renovated in a post-modern style and has a capacity of 2,000. As for prose theater, the most classic offerings can be found in the Teatro della Corte, famous for its school that has produced many well known actors. It is also in a modern, well designed building.  Two large halls have diversified theater in Genoa in the last few years. Teatro Duse and Genovese halls offer a program of successful musicals and comedians who do television work. As for alternative theater, two places in Genoa offer an interesting choice. The Teatro della Tosse is now a favorite place for two great artists: comedy writer Tonino Conte and set designer Lele Luzzati. It produces its own shows and, during summer, organizes surprising events in old factories and abandoned forts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Carlo Felice Theatre is the place to go to hear opera and classical music concerts as well as high quality jazz. There are also various places in Genoa that offer live music. The recently opened DLF offers an intense, ambitious program that is open to international music trends with a strong emphasis on sounds from the London club scene. It has a capacity for 1,300 people and serves as one of the best places to hear live music in the city. The program is developed by the same people who organize the only popular music festival in the region, the Goa-Boa in July.  The smaller music club circuit centers around the historic district. Quaalude was the first place in Genoa to open the way for underground music. Fitzcarraldo hosts sought after artists, even if the small location is not great for larger crowds, and Mascherona and the Palace offer a chance to hear live music as well, usually punk or rock.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The heart of the city\''s nightlife can be found in the historic center where the underground culture can be discovered in the alleyways surrounding historic palaces and monuments. It is not always easy to find what you are looking for, but this is all part of the game, and the style of the city. Most of the nighttime haunts are concentrated in area between Piazza Sarzana and Via San Lorenzo. During the day it is nice to wander around the backstreets here in search of some of the more hidden places in the city. There are some sophisticated wine bars to be discovered here such as Le Cantine Squarciafico and open-late tapas bars, such as La Lepre. The scene changes on the weekends, when the usually peaceful alleyways are taken over by lively crowds on their way to Cafè Latino in piazza Delle Erbe and Le Corbousier in piazza San Donato. These places are always packed, and the neighboring areas are full of cocktail and wine bars. This is a veritable epicenter of nightlife where you can barhop all night or go on to one of the clubs in the area or even go along to a disco like DLF.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (811,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Boccadasse</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Starting right on the water, Boccadasse is perhaps the most-visited neighborhood in the city. It sits on the sea and houses much of the tourist activity in Genoa. Be charmed by a waterfront stroll down main promenade Corso Italia and pacified by the soothing sounds of the Ligurian Sea. While there are a few landmarks in the area, such as the Chiesa di Sant\''antonio di Boccadasse, cultural opportunities largely revolve around the neighborhood\''s fishing history, so don\''t miss the chance to people watch over impossibly fresh seafood while in the area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Caruggi</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Offering as much character as Boccadasse under its slightly less shiny façade, the Caruggi district is dense with cultural attractions. Start your visit in the historic center, which makes for an excellent walking tour destination. Beginning in Strada Nuova, now known as Via Garibaldi, take in relics of the days when great, Genovese families were at their richest. Continue on and see sights like Via Garibaldi and the palatial structures it houses or venture to the famous Aquarium of Genoa. Eye-catching architecture is a mainstay of the Old City and those interested in touring historic churches, plazas, and museums may just want to head here first. Via Balbi is a particularly nice place to explore as it is rich with palaces and now houses the university buildings of the School of the Humanities. You\''ll also find nightlife opportunities in the bustling Caruggi neighborhood though visitors should be aware of the presence of pickpockets after dark.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sturla</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Moving outside the more touristic areas of Genoa, Sturla boasts a small but lovely beach and all the appeal of an authentic Italian neighborhood. It has stayed true to its fishing village roots and offers visitors a true taste of Genoese life, not to mention some tasty local dining options. Points of interest in Sturla include the Santissima Annunziata and San Celso churches, which preserve medieval architecture and house lovely artworks. And for a livelier activity, check out the <em>trallalero</em> folk music scene that pulses through the neighborhood.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Albaro</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Albaro is a residential area of Genoa where visitors can go for peaceful walkabouts replete with glimpses of hillside villas. Many of the residences found in the area are elegant and historic, built anywhere from the 16th century by aristocrats to the 19th century by the entrepreneurial elite. Catholic churches also dot the area, lending a bit of culture to the neighborhood. To surround yourself with elegance and enjoy the salty sea air in peace, be sure to stop by lovely Albaro.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
