 (848,'The Rotunda of Illustrious Persons is temple to honor Mexico\''s national heroes.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (849,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">An aspect, which stands out in the city, is the great number of plazas and shopping areas—more than 60—along with outdoor spaces and covered galleries for window shopping. Some outstanding commercial centers include Plaza del Sol, Plaza México and Centro Magno. Besides the commercial complexes, Guadalajara also has a thriving craft culture, and the stores in Tlaquepaque and Tonala are the best place to purchase quality handicrafts and pottery straight from the artisans.Those with a love for shoes shouldn\''t miss out on buying a pair of handcrafted leather shoes here; in fact, a visit to Galeria del Calzado is a must on any shopping itinerary for a custom-fitted pair of loafers or bright sandals.While there is no shortage of markets in the city, the Mercado Libertad, one of the country\''s largest indoor markets, is a veritable treasure trove of sights and sounds. The market\''s three levels feature everything from traditional eateries to shops selling souvenirs, handicrafts, and local products.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoor Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The area\''s excellent climate allows for outdoor activities year-round, such as the Zoológico Guadalajara, a massive zoological park that\''s home to a number of animals from around the globe. You\''ll see everything from African elephants to Emperor penguins from Antarctica here! For those who prefer the great outdoors, the Bosque de la Primavera offers chances to spot local wildlife like coyote and lynx in a land of lush forest, cool waterfalls, ancient fossils and a myriad hiking and biking trails.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The nightlife promises an entertaining evening in one of the variety of bars and clubs. Concentrated along Chapultepec Avenue, the heart of the city\''s entertainment zone, Guadalajara has an eclectic ensemble of options. Whiskey connoisseurs should drop by Unplugged Whisky Bar that has a line up of great rock music every night. For a fun night out and a chance to put on your dancing shoes, head to La Fichera, a local favorite that\''s packed to the hilt; get here early to bag a spot at the bar. Slinging some of the cheapest drinks in town, Bananas Cafe with its bright muraled walls is roomy, though thanks to its popularity there\''s always a queue. For a glimpse of Old Mexico, Cantina La Fuente is the place to go. This nostalgic tavern still has an old-fashioned vibe, and ordering anything \''fancy\'' is inadvisable.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Art</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As Jalisco\''s capital, Guadalajara is the cultural hub of the region and boasts a thriving cultural scene that showcases the best of regional and national art. Among the top museums, the Instituto Cultural Cabanas, once a historic hospital complex, is today a cultural center that hosts a number of exhibitions. One of the main reasons to visit is the exquisite murals that cover the building\''s walls, done by José Clemente Orozco, renowned for his mural art. Other places worth visiting are the Palacio de Gobierno and the Museo de las Artes de la Universidad de Guadalajara. For contemporary art, a number of galleries showcase local artists in a variety of mediums from sculpture to painting and design.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (850,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historic Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The most beautiful area in the city undoubtedly is the <em>Centro Histórico</em> (Historic Centre), especially the Plaza Tapatía. A journey through history begins at the Catedral Metropolitana and ends at the Instituto Cultural Cabañas A first stop would be the Teatro Degollado. Probably the most picturesque walk is down the shady tree-lined Avenida Vallarta to wind up at <em>Los Arcos</em> (the Arches) and the fountain, tribute to Minerva. This scenic stroll leads past colonial-era mansions, many of which have been converted to shops, eateries and discotheques.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central and West Guadalajara</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Central and Western Guadalajara are made up of several distinct neighborhoods, each with their own unique flavor. Among these, Providencia, Americana, Santa Teresita, and Chapalita stand out. West Guadalajara is known for its upscale residences, five-star hotels and fine-dining restaurants.Providencia: This neighborhood is one of the most sought-after residential areas. It is where Casa Jalisco, the governor\''s mansion, is located. This area is popular with expats and has several lively bars, restaurants, and chic boutiques.Chapalita: This spacious neighborhood is characterized by its leafy parks. You can enjoy a stroll around Parque Juan Diego or Glorieta Chapalita, where on Sunday\''s local artists exhibit their works. A short distance away, the La Estampida is a landmark worth visiting.Mexicaltzingo: A neighborhood characterized by a typical Mexican feel, Mexicaltzingo is one of the city\''s oldest neighborhoods, and the remnants of a bygone era still chronicle the passage of time.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zapopan</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">,</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Tlaquepaque</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">and</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Tonalá</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For almost five centuries, the growth of its population and urban center has given way to a great metropolis, blurring the boundaries with the ancient villas of Zapopan, Tlaquepaque and Tonalá which share common traditions, tastes, interests and styles.Zapopan is characterized as being the seat of the Basílica de la Virgen de Zapopan. Filled with plazas and gardens, the area is ideal for leisurely strolls. Tlaquepaque is a pottery paradise, brimming with arts and crafts boutiques with everything from ashtrays to sculptures. One of the most attractive shops found here is the Galería Sergio Bustamante where all items purchased are certified for their authenticity. One of the best restaurants in the area is the Abajeño Campestre, for dining in the outdoor garden on exquisite Mexican fare while enjoying mariachi and regional dance.The factories of</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Tonalá</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">—a <em>villa alfarero</em> (potters villa)—allow a firsthand glimpse at how clay is fashioned by artisans. Hundreds of workshops produce traditional pottery here, that are then sold in the town\''s many boutiques and shops catering to tourists.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
