 (865,'The Guadalajara Cathedral\''s clock towers surrounded by a modern plaza.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (866,'A dramatic sunrise over clouds in Guatemala City.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (867,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Family-Friendly</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While it may not look that way at first glance, Guatemala City has plenty for all ages. For fun days out with the kids, the Zoológico La Aurora is a top choice, while indoor pursuits include the Museo de los Niños de Guatemala. Blending education with a day out in nature, the Jardín Botánico is another top pick, as is the fascinating Mapa en Relieve.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">New movies can be seen at screens around the city. Top choices include the Cinépolis chain of multiplexes that dot the city, one of the most popular venues being the Cinépolis Oakland Mall where visitors can enjoy Hollywood magic. Most of the larger commercial centers and shopping complexes house a cinema, often featuring English-language films.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There is no shortage of museums in Guatemala\''s capital city and a visit to the National Museums Center is a must. This complex includes the Archeology and Ethnology Museum, the Museo de Arte Moderno and the Museo de Historia Natural. The Ixchel Museum of Indigenous Dress and the Museo Popol Vuh are in the last six streets of Zone 10. They offer an impressive exhibition of the history and culture of Guatemala. For younger visitors, there is the Museo de los Niños, is an interactive museum for children. Other specialty and smaller museums like the Casa Mima, Museo de Musicos Invisibles, Museo Numismatico de Guatemala and Museo del Ferrocarril enrich the city\''s cultural landscape.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">When it comes to nightlife in Guatemala City, things start to liven up in the traditional bars of the city center at about five o\''clock in the evening. In Zona 1, La Bodeguita del Centro plays live music through the week and is a local favorite. In Zona 4, Trovajazz is a great place to groove to the rhythms of live jazz, latin beats, and folk music. In the Zona Viva (Zone 10) in the south of the city, dozens of venues compete to offer the finest food and best entertainment. This area is now the city\''s most popular attraction, bursting with nightclubs, discos, bars, restaurants, and shops selling jade, silver, pottery and fashion based on tribal embroidery designs.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As a vibrant metropolis, Guatemala city has its fair share of large shopping complexes and malls that exist alongside local shops and trendy boutiques. Among the most popular shopping centers are the upscale Paseo Cayala and Oakland Mall while the Mercado Central, or Central Market, is the best place to buy local products including handicrafts and souvenirs at reasonable prices.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As the capital city, Guatemala City is the country\''s center for art and culture. Here, visitors can experience a variety of offerings from theater to plays and concerts. Among the top choices, the Centro Cultural de España has a wide line up of dance, music, theater and art exhibitions and showcases the best of Spanish culture. Another major institution for the arts is the Centro Cultural Miguel Ãngel Asturias or the Teatro Nacional, located in the heart of the Centro Cívico. This unique structure is built to resemble a seated jaguar, and in itself is an interesting landmark. It hosts national-level performances through the year and has an outdoor amphitheater as well as a black box for more intimate performances.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (868,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zone 1</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is the historic center of the city. In 1775, when Guatemala de la Asunción was founded, the most important governmental and ecclesiastical buildings were constructed here, as well as the houses of the leading families of the era. Private houses were characterized by the <em>mudejar</em> architectural style, with a construction so uniform that the only thing to differentiate between each was the size of the property. Public buildings were constructed in a Neo-Classical style and few of them had more than one floor. Today, the heart of Zone 1, where the Plaza Mayor de la Constitución and most of the important government and church buildings like the Metropolitan Cathedral, Palacio Nacional and Edificio de Correos Central are located, is protected as a historic heritage site. In this area, there are lots of shopping centers and stores, such as shoe stores, boutiques, fabric stores and other businesses where you can buy good merchandise at low prices.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zone 2</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This zone was founded as a town for indigenous people transferred from Antigua, Guatemala, the former capital of the kingdom. With the construction of the North Hippodrome, during the Liberal Government, many wealthy families built residences on the Avenida del Hipódromo. Some of these houses are still standing today, and belong to private families. The famous Mapa en Relieve of the Guatemalan Republic was constructed in 1904. It is the only map of its kind in the world and a tourist attraction in its own right.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zone 4</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In 1890, during President Barillas\'' term in office, the canton of Exposición was formed, with the Guatemalan Pavilion of the Paris World Fair in its center. The Centro Cívico is located in this zone, and houses the Guatemala Tourist Institute, Guatemala City municipal offices and other governmental buildings. These buildings were built between 1954 and 1970. They are decorated with impressive murals. In the cultural center is the national theater, called Centro Cultural Miguel Angel Asturias. Constructed in 1978, this consists of the Main Theater, the Chamber Theater, an open-air stage and the Salon Dorado. The building is shaped like a crouching jaguar. This complex is venue to magnificent theatrical and musical performances.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zones 9 & 10</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In 1892, the public garden Boulevard 30 de Junio was created. Today it is known as the Avenida La Reforma which features gardens, upscale villas, embassies, and luxury hotels along its stretch. Among the landmarks found in Zona 9, the Torre del Reformador, a commemorative steel tower built to honor Justo Rufino Barrios Guatemalan president and the Obelisco, a monument to Guatemalan independence stand out. Avenida La Reforma separates zones 9 and 10, where the best hotels, restaurants, night-clubs and shopping centers like Centro Comercial La Pradera and Oakland Mall are located. Zone 10 is known as the Zona Viva because there is a party here almost every night! Besides the vibrant nightlife, Zona 10 is also home to a number of attractions like the Jardín Botánico and the Museo Ixchel del Traje Indigena.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Zones 13 & 14</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">These zones are separated by the Avenida Las Américas. At one end of the avenue, a small square was built to celebrate the first Eucharistic Congress. As its name suggests, the avenue is dedicated to the countries of the American continent. In each corner of the square, a picture with wrought iron adornments was installed. Each picture has the shield and the name of an American country. Along here you can see beautiful gardens and many small squares and statues lining the avenue.Art and culture lovers can explore Zone 13\''s many museums like the Museo Nacional de Arqueología y Etnología and Museo Nacional de Arte Moderno \"Carlos Mérida\" while kids will enjoy the Museo de los Niños and zoo, Zoológico La Aurora located here. Zone 13 is also where the city\''s international airport, La Aurora International Airport is situated.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
