 (915,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hartford has several unique museums and historical sights that cater to history buffs, the literary-inclined and art enthusiasts. Hartford\''s Wadsworth Atheneum houses one of the finest small collections of European and American art in the country along with special touring exhibits. The Harriet Beecher Stowe and Mark Twain residences in the Asylum Hill area are not just for schoolchildren, but lovers of American literature, dedicated to two of the country\''s most prolific and influential writers. For local history, visit the Museum of Connecticut History, and check out the Connecticut Science Center and the Children\''s Museum with your kids.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Connecticut River Valley is full of unique theaters, their program ranging from local productions to national tours of big Broadway shows thanks to its proximity to New York City. The Bushnell Theater in downtown Hartford is the city\''s premier theater venue with a stellar line-up of Broadway hits as well as concerts by leading musicians. Also in Hartford is the XL Center which is not just a sports arena, but also a venue for major concerts featuring the likes of Coldplay, Tina Turner and Neil Diamond. During the summer months, nothing beats an outdoor concert at the Xfinity Theatre where the annual Dave Matthews concert draws crowds for two days of musical interlude.If you are interested in taking a scenic drive down Route 9 towards Long Island Sound, the Goodspeed Opera House in East Haddam puts on three productions a year of new and lesser-known (yet astounding) American musicals. The Goodspeed is birthplace to two great shows, <em>The Man of La Mancha</em> and <em>Annie</em>, both of which made the successful route up to Broadway and Hollywood.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Whalers\'' NHL franchise might be gone, but there is no dearth of sporting events in Hartford. The XL Center has been home to the AHL team, the Hartford Wolf Pack, since 1997. Also held at the XL Center each year are numerous games of the men\''s and women\''s University of Connecticut (UConn) basketball teams, while others are held at the Gampel Pavilion on the main UConn campus over in Storrs.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are several public spaces for a pleasant stroll in Downtown, like Bushnell Park with its historic carousel, and Pope Park with its ample walking and cycling trails. Another great spot for a stroll is over at Trinity College where the campus is closed to major traffic and you can explore the school\''s famous quads on foot. One of Hartford\''s most popular in-city retreats is Riverside Park, composed of four parks on both sides of the Connecticut River.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (916,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Hartford contains some of the city\''s oldest buildings, such as the Federal-style Old State House (1796) designed by Thomas Bulfinch, architect of some of New England\''s other great state houses. The Center Church & Ancient Burial Ground right in the heart of the downtown area were part of the original congregations of the city, founded in the early 17th Century. Intermingled amongst the quaint 18th-and 19th-century architecture, lie the ultra-modern skyscrapers of today, housing the headquarters of the nation\''s largest insurance companies. Downtown also hosts a variety of cultural venues, such as the Wadsworth Atheneum with its impressive collection of European art, the Hartford Stage, and The Bushnell - a theater that hosts first-run and national tours of Broadway\''s biggest show, providing entertainment for tourists and locals alike. If you prefer to spend some time in the outdoors, Bushnell Park offers a comfortable escape from the manic pace of downtown Hartford and a vintage carousel to please children of all ages. Close to Interstate 91, the scenic Riverfront Park, overlooks the majestic Connecticut River.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parkville</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Parkville is home to the Hartford\''s Portuguese-speaking community with plenty of streets lined with Portuguese and Brazilian shops, restaurants and the Our Lady of Sorrows, a Catholic church still celebrates Mass in Latin.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Frog Hollow</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Named for its marshy land, Frog Hollow was originally home to a large African-American community prior to the Civil War. After the war, in the midst of America\''s Industrial Age, numerous immigrants came to the Hartford to work at one of the many factories that lined the Connecticut River throughout the 19th Century and the early 20th Century. Today, it is home to the city\''s Latino and Caribbean communities, with the main drag of Park Street often referred to as \"New England\''s Spanish Main Street.\" Frog Hollow is also home to one of the country\''s premier liberal arts schools, Trinity College, with noted alumni such as playwright Edward Albee and political pundit Tucker Carlson. Pope Park, one of the city\''s original recreational areas, was created in 1898 by the Olmsted Brothers Landscape Architects, an architectural landscaping firm known for their work on several National Parks, college campuses and in city parks.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Asylum Hill & West End</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The peculiar name of Asylum Hill comes from the School that was founded here in 1807 - the Asylum for the Education and Instruction of Deaf and Dumb Persons, the first of its kind in the United States. In commemoration of this area\''s history, a statue of Alice Cogwell, the school\''s first student was placed at the intersection of Farmington and Asylum Avenues. Over the years, Asylum Hill has been home to Hartford\''s notable society, including writers such as Harriet Beecher Stowe and Mark Twain, their residences now the site of museums that detail their lives and work. Along with its famed residents is the neighborhood\''s unique architecture, epitomized by the Trinity Episcopal Church and Cathedral of St. Joseph.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sheldon-Charter Oak & South Green</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The original site of the city\''s Dutch settlement along the Connecticut River, Sheldon-Charter Oak is immediately recognizable to those arriving via I-95 into Hartford by the Colt Firearms Factory\''s blue onion dome. The 50 German-style houses constructed along the riverway were originally intended for the employees of the factory, a section known as Potsdam Village; however, only ten of these residences still remain. At the intersection of Charter Oak Avenue stands a monument to the Charter Oak, the oak tree that once hid the Connecticut Colony charter during the late-17th Century.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northeast</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The neighborhood known as the Northeast is located in the upper corner of the city and was home to many Jewish and Irish immigrants who worked in nearby factories, such as the Fuller Brush Company and the Bishop Ladder Company. On July 6, 1944, during an afternoon performance of the Ringling Brothers and Barnum & Bailey Circus, the circus tent caught fire (it was coated with paraffin and gasoline, a common waterproofing solution at the time) and approximately 165 people lost their lives in the scramble to escape the blaze. As a result of the fire, circuses were banned throughout Connecticut until the 1970s. Today, a memorial stands to those who died as a result of the fire.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North Meadows</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In nearby North Meadows is one of Connecticut\''s great music venues - the Xfinity Theatre, formerly and most commonly referred to as The Meadows. Plenty of pleasant excursions can be had at the Riverside Park where there is ample open space for frisbee, boating or even cricket.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">South End</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Just as nearby New Haven has Wooster Street, Hartford has its Little Italy in the South End. Like several urban centers of the Northeast, the majority of the population of this neighborhood was Italian-American until the past couple of decades. Nonetheless, its past can easily be seen in the high number of Italian-owned businesses that still line Franklin Avenue (Little Italy). These walkable streets are full of bakeries and shops that appeal to locals and visitors alike.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Quiet Corner (Northeastern Connecticut)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The northeastern corner of the state is lovingly referred to as \"The Quiet Corner\" since it is one of the least densely populated areas of the Boston-Washington, D.C. Corridor. This part of the state is filled with popular local shops, farms and vineyards that attract a healthy number of tourists throughout the year, such as the Mansfield Drive-In Theatre & Marketplace and the Taylor Brooke Winery. During the academic year; however, the population of this quiet region comes to life as students make their way to the University of Connecticut (UConn). Of course, many also come to campus to see the Huskies\'' men\''s and women\''s basketball teams take on other Big East and top nationally-ranked teams.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Litchfield</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In the opposite corner of the state is Litchfield and Litchfield County. The area is most popular with weekenders and honeymooners with its plethora of romantic bed and breakfasts, country inns, unique restaurants and day spas. If you are looking for a quiet retreat, not far from New York or Hartford, Litchfield is where you can really get a taste of New England.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Connecticut River Valley</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Nestled along the 407-mile (655-kilometer) long Connecticut River, the Connecticut River Valley contains some of the state\''s oldest and historic towns. Old Saybrook, located at the mouth of the River, was first called the Saybrook Colony (settled in 1635) and was the original site of Yale University from 1701 until it moved to New Haven in 1716. Just up the river is Essex, attacked by the British during the War of 1812, which draws visitors today with the lovely Griswold Inn and Essex Steam Train & Riverboat. Halfway between Old Saybrook and Hartford is Middletown, seat of Middlesex County and home to Wesleyan University.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
