 (990,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are numerous museums, galleries, and other exhibition venues all over the city. First and foremost, the Tyrolean State Museum offers cultural insight into the state of Tyrol and offers Austria\''s largest collection of Gothic artifacts. A number of historic sites found in the city also double as museums, including the Hofburg, Ambras Castle, Goldenes Dachl, and Maximilianeum, which is thematically oriented towards emperor Maximilan of Bavaria. For art lovers, the city offers stops like modern art center the Kunstraum. Keep an eye out for events and take advantage of the guided tours for the most comprehensive visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you enjoy theater, Innsbruck offers a variety of ways to keep you entertained. Opposite the Hofburg is the Tiroler Landestheater, which boasts a broad program ranging from plays to musicals to operettas. There\''s also the charming Kellertheater at Adolf-Pichler-Platz and the quaint Theater InnStanz in the Pradi district. The most important addresses for classical music concerts are Dogana<em>, </em>located next to the Hofburg, and Ambras Castle. Large pop and rock music concerts usually take place in the Olympiahalle. Generally speaking, the city\''s best place for jazz and world music concerts is Treibhaus.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Innsbruck\''s two largest cinemas are Cineplexx and Metropol, where you can watch films in their original language. Apart from these, the city has quite a large film scene, mainly owing to the excellent work of the Cinematograph and Leokino arts cinemas.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Innsbruck has hosted the Olympic Winter Games twice, meaning there are countless sports events taking place regularly, among them the popular ski-jump in the Bergisel stadium. The Air&Style Association organizes the world\''s biggest snowboard contest, by now in Seefeld, half an hour from Innsbruck by car. In summer, there is the event\''s skateboarding counterpart, where international top riders from all over the world are fighting for the highest price money world-wide.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Night Life</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Innsbruck is a students\'' city: about a quarter of the city\''s population are students, and you can tell from the nightlife scene. One of the city\''s characteristics is the row of bars and pubs located in the viaduct, simply called <em>Bögen </em>by locals. Dozens of diverse bars stand side by side here, among them Plateau, Babalon, and Down Under. And of course, many places to go can be found right in the old town and its immediate vicinity, for instance the large restaurant-bar Elfer offering many different kinds of beer. The place to be on warm summer nights is the Hofgartencafé. The large discotheques are situated at the borders of the city while the ones in the centre are smaller. Blue Chip and the Couch Club are worth mentioning in that respect.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Annual Events</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Innsbruck hosts some big and internationally successful events each year. Some of these on the cultural level are the concerts held at Ambras Castle, particularly the <em>Festwochen der Alten Musik</em> during August, where international artists play old music on authentic, old instruments. Another internationally well-known festival is the <em>Innsbrucker Tanzsommer</em>, the dance and ballet event taking place in summer. The <em>Internationale Cinevision Filmfestival</em>organized by the Cinematograph and Leo cinemas during the months of May and June is also worth mentioning.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (991,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Innenstadt & Altstadt</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Inner City and Old Town together make up the heart of historic Innsbruck. It is well worth going on a walkabout though the area\''s narrow streets to soak up the atmosphere. There are lots of fascinating historical sights to see, such as the Hofburg and Hofkirche, the latter of which houses the tomb of Emperor Maximilian I. Other attractions include the women\''s chapter founded by Maria Theresia, legendary Goldene Dachl, imposing Domkirche St. Jakob with its famous cathedral square, Triumphpforte, and marble Annasäule monument.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pradl & Saggen</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">These two districts ring the Inner City from the north, south, and east. For an interesting and relaxing walk, try the Hofgarten and its charming parrot and butterfly houses. During autumn and spring, the exhibition center attracts throngs of visitors from the locality, as well as further afield. The area\''s autumn and spring fairs also bring in thousands of visitors every year who come to see novelties from Tyrol and beyond. Elsewhere, the ultra-modern Cineplexx Innsbruck caters to film buffs while a coffee at Sillpark is the perfect way to round out your day after a shopping spree.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Hötting & Höttinger Au</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The district of Hötting lies on the northern bank of the Inn river, which runs through the middle of the city. Formerly a residential area for the well-to-do, Hötting is today quiet and unobtrusive suburbia, not to mention home to the delightful Alpenzoo. The founders of this zoo had a distinctive mission in mind: to find endangered species in the wild, rear them in the zoo, then set them free again in their former Alpine habitats. You can get a rack-rail from the Alpenzoo to Hungerburg, the base station for the cable railway that takes you to the lakes and valleys lying high above Innsbruck. There is even a restaurant at the top offering a superb vantage point from which to observe the magnificent spectacle of night falling over Innsbruck. To make the most of this magical area, plan a visit to the Botanischer Garten, as well.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Wilten</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Wilten is situated at the southern extremity of the city center. The main road over the Brenner Pass goes through Wilten and presents an imposing view for motorists approaching Innsbruck from the south. Two outstanding edifices in Wilten are the Stift Wilten and Wiltener Basilika, a splendid example of Baroque architecture dating back to 1120. The cloister at Stift Wilten houses a valuable collection of art and a noteworthy church museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Olympisches Dorf</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Olympic village, a recent residential development, lies to the south of the city. It sprang up and gained its name as a result of the winter games held in Innsbruck. The village contains the Olympiaworld Innsbruck. Originally only used for sporting events, the impressive site now also plays host to concerts and other non-sporting activities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Amras</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Anybody leaving the city through the southern border is bound to spot the area\''s DEZ Einkaufszentrum, the largest shopping center of its kind in North Tyrol. If you let your gaze drift a little further, you\''ll also notice the 10th century Schloss Ambras. In addition to a striking white facade, this castle houses a well-known armory collection and a quiet park dating back to the Renaissance.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Igls</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Igls is a pleasant, peaceful neighborhood populated by affluent residents. In winter, the Bergiselschanze becomes the focus of intense competitions between the best ski jumpers in the world. Bobsled and toboggan slopes are also found nearby, including a bobsled ride designed for amateurs. All in all, Igls has earned itself quite a reputation amongst energetic and sporty visitors in Innsbruck, not least because of the hair-raising skiing opportunities at the Patscherkofel peak.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (992,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Istanbul is such a diverse city that it\''s almost impossible to split it up into definable districts. The only real distinction that can be made is between the European and Asian sides, which are separated by the Bosphorus Strait. Stretching from the Black Sea, straddling across the Bosphorus, touching the Sea of Marmara, Istanbul, with an estimated population of between 10-13 million, has become a city of unlimited scope.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
