 (1027,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are a plethora of galleries and museums in and around Johannesburg, so many that a week could easily be filled just doing the art routes. The Johannesburg Art Gallery houses a definitive collection of South African art and the Standard Bank Art Gallery in lies at the core of city center, and has an excellent exhibit scene. The Goodman Gallery in Parkwood and the Everard Read Gallery in Rosebank are among the oldest and most established galleries, always showing the crème de la crème of local talent. The unique CIRCA on Jellicoe, housed within a strikingly modern building, showcases contemporary art by native South African artists. Other prolific galleries in the city include the Gallery MOMO, the Stevenson Gallery and Wits Art Museum housed within the Wits University.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are cinema complexes all over the city, mostly housed within large shopping centers. Mainstream films are on view from all over the world, mostly from the US. \''art films\'' are shown in the Rosebank Mall cinema complex Cinema Nouveau, and also at embassies and the French Institute of South Africa, in Parkview. Other modern multiplexes in the city are the Nu Metro Bedford Centre and the Killarney CineCentre. For offbeat movies, The Bioscope near city center, offering a wealth of indie and world movies, is your best bet.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Music is everywhere, and everything from the operatic to the sassy can easily be found. There\''s get-down blues and jazz at The Orbit in Braamfontein and jazz at the Market Theatre Complex. For classical music lovers, Witwatersrand (Wits) University offers regular recitals. The Civic Theatre (in Braamfontein, not far from Wits University) and Linder Auditorium (about 20 minutes from there) also offer the classics. Larger arenas like the Johannesburg Stadium showcase big-name national and international artists. These visiting greats can also be found at some of the big casino complexes like Carnival City. Others like Bassline, Carfax and the Radium Beerhall are also cool venues for alternative music genres.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Johannesburg\''s arts scene has expanded exponentially in the last decade, with several independent theaters cropping up all over the city. The Wits Theatre at the Witwatersrand (Wits) University in Braamfontein often shows contemporary drama. The Joburg Theatre Complex comprises of a group of four theaters that stage everything from ballet performances and productions for children, to Broadway musicals and experimental plays. Another intimate theater space in the city is the POPArt Theatre, which showcases a number of avant-garde plays and comedic performances from time to time. Venues like the Lyric Theatre, the heritage Victory Theatre and the National Children\''s Theatre are also worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The city offers numerous museums, and your first stop should be Museum Africa, founded in 1935 as the Africana Museum. Since then it has built up a collection of geological specimens, paintings, prints and photographs that represent life in southern Africa from the stone-age to the nuclear age, and beyond. In addition, the fascinating photographic collection at the Bensusan Museum in Newtown (near the Market theater complex) has a good historic art collection. For something completely different, try the SAB World of Beer (corner of Bezuidenhout and President Streets in Newtown), which depicts the history of brewing, going back to 1895. This is the date that South African Breweries (SAB) was officially registered on the London Stock Exchange. Come and sample some excellent South African beer. Or to learn more about South African history, the Anglo Boer War Museum and the Apartheid Museum can\''t be missed.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Clubs,</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bars, Pubs & Lounges</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Clubs in Jo\''burg cater to every taste — from hip hop and drum \''n bass to hard house and pop. Tanz Café, in Bryanston, combines the essence of European and Argentinean dance cafés where the music is passionate, the dance floor is large and the menu is unique. And, of course, the city\''s many bars, from the cocktail-specialist Landmark, to the glitzy Skye Bar in Sandton, Johannesburg has a diverse scene for libations and tastes. When it comes to hard-core revelry, the Madison Avenue Rivonia, one of the hippest nightclubs in the city, will keep you partying well into the night. The Rumours Lounge is excellent for its laid-back partying vibes, while the And Club and the Sands Nightclub are both popular clubs for dancing the night away.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
