 (1037,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Great Outdoors</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Alaska is an outdoor lover\''s dream, with so much of the great outdoors surrounding the city to see and explore. One popular activity that will give you a bird\''s eye view is the Mount Roberts Tramway, just south of downtown. This aerial tram carries passengers 1800 feet up Mount Roberts, where there is a restaurant, a theater, spectacular views and hiking trails that can take you around the top or back down to the bottom. Mount Roberts\'' trails aren\''t the only ones in Juneau, there are actually more than 250 hiking trails all around the city that give visitors plenty of opportunities to get out into nature without ever leaving the city. One must-do activity when visiting Juneau is taking a trip to a glacier. There are several glaciers in and around Juneau. Also near the city is the Juneau Icefield, which consists of dozens of glaciers and is one of the largest in the Western Hemisphere. One of the glaciers that is part of the icefield is Mendenhall Glacier, which has a great visitor center and is an excellent place to start your trip to the glacier. It is popular to hire a guide or join a tour to explore Mendenhall Glacier, but there are also plenty of trails around the visitor center. During winter, Eaglecrest Ski Area is popular for skiing and snowboarding. During spring and summer (from May through September) is when the humpback and orca whales come to Juneau, so whale watching boat tours from companies like Juneau Whale Watch are an extremely popular and memorable activity. Kayaking and rafting are also popular summer activities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Arts & Culture</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There\''s plenty to do indoors in Juneau as well. There are a number of art galleries like the Annie Kaills Gallery or the Juneau Artists Gallery. The galleries all come together to put on the Juneau Gallery Walk the first Friday of every month. To learn about the native heritage of the area, head to the Sealaska Heritage Institute in the Walter Soboleff Building downtown, to check out their exhibitions on the native peoples and cultures of Southeast Alaska. More history can be found at the Alaska State Museum and the small but interesting Juneau-Douglas City Museum. For performing arts, Alaska\''s professional theater company, Perseverance Theatre, puts on mostly plays that are centered around Alaskan themes and culture.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1038,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Juneau is located in the southern part of the city, just across the Gastineau Channel and Juneau-Douglas Bridge from Douglas Island. Downtown is the main commercial zone of the city. Here you will find the State Capitol Building, historic landmark buildings like the Alaskan Hotel & Bar, the Governor\''s House, many museums, galleries, restaurants, shops, bars and more.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Douglas Island</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Located just across the Gastineau Channel from downtown and connected hy the Juneau-Douglas Bridge is Douglas Island. The island is generally split into two portions; North Douglas being rural and largely undeveloped, with a heliport and ski area, while downtown Douglas contains Sandy Beach, the only sand beach in Juneau, restaurants, Douglas Harbor, and most of the development on the island, including the school, library, theater and the few bars and restaurants.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Rest of Juneau</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Most of the rest of Juneau is located to the north of downtown. Twin Lakes, just north of downtown, is a largely residential neighborhood and is also home to the hospital. North of this is Lemon Creek, which has many of the large big box stores like Costco, as well as the Alaskan Brewing Company. Further north is the Mendenhall Valley, which is home to two major malls, and Auke Bay where the University of Alaska Southeast is located, as well as being a popular destination for fishing in Juneau. There\''s not alot south of downtown, but one notable attraction is the Mount Roberts Tramway, an aerial tramway that transports visitors to the top of Mount Roberts, where there are facilities like a nature center, shops, a restaurant and a theater.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NUL