 (1056,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoor Activities</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Whether you choose to hop aboard a glass-bottomed boat, snorkel or scuba dive, an underwater world of amazing beauty awaits in John Pennekamp Coral Reef State Park, one of the best diving sites in the world and home to 78 square miles (202 square kilometers) of coral reefs. Hiking trails and a visitor\''s center with a floor-to-ceiling aquarium are among the other attractions of this not-to-be-missed park. At the Theater of the Seas, you can swim with dolphins, sea lions and stingrays or become a trainer for a day, putting creatures of the sea through their paces. In the Middle Keys, the Dolphin Research Center offers another opportunity for swimming with dolphins. At the Windley Key Fossil Reef State Geologic Site on Windley Key, you can see what a coral reef looks like when it\''s left high and dry, and visit middens left behind by the earliest Native American residents of the keys. Looe Key Reef is home to beautiful corals, and Bahia Honda State Park offers sand dunes, waters as clear as crystal, and views that go on forever. For an offshore adventure, explore Indian Key State Historic Site. Although inhabited for a brief period in the 19th Century, the deserted island is now a ghost town, replete with ruins overtaken by vegetation and a rocky coast that\''s teeming with life. The island is accessible only via ferry or kayak. You can also visit the 280-acre Lignumvitae Key State Botanical Site, a hardwood forest that was the home and gardens of a millionaire who put it all together in 1919 in such style that the site is now on the National Register of Historic Places.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Keys have a long and fascinating history that you can learn more about at the many museums scattered across the islands. The Custom House Museum provides a detailed chronicle of Key West\''s history. Fort East Martello Museum and Gallery is dedicated to Key West historical artifacts. The museum also has exhibits dealing with the daily life of early Key West inhabitants. The Key West Shipwreck Historeum, on the other hand, delves into a more niche subject of the islands\'' history. At this museum, you\''ll learn about how some islanders would dive for shipwrecked goods. You can also visit the Flagler Station Over-Sea Railway Historeum, to learn more about the ill-fated Henry Flagler\''s railroad.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theaters</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you would like to enjoy the theater while in the Keys you have plenty of options. The historical Waterfront Playhouse has a modest theater and shows quirky and well-known productions, including <em>Cat on a Hot Tin Roof</em> and <em>The Best Man</em>. Another small theater that produces professional productions is Red Barn Theater. If you are in Marathon, the Marathon Community Theater is the place to be for small productions featuring local talent.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals & Street Fairs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">No matter when you visit Key West, there\''s always a festival or fair to look forward to. The German Oktoberfest has reached Summerland Key, with a parade, live music and endless pints of beer. If you come in December enjoy the beautiful and often humorous Key West Lighted Boat Parade. Key West is transformed into a pirates heaven for a day during Pirates In Paradise. In July the Hemingway Days Festival can\''t be beaten. One of the best annual events is the Conch Republic Independence Celebration. The festival is a ten-day celebration of a time when the Florida Keys briefly seceded from the United States. The United States Border Patrol was treating the Keys unfairly and in protest the Keys seceded and humorously declared \"war.\" After a minute and without any prompting the Keys surrendered and jokingly asked for foreign aid. The festival celebrates this historic turn of events with drag races, music concerts, a parade, and a \"battle\" against the US Border Patrol.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This little island boasts more bars per capita than anywhere else in the country and is revered for its vibrant nightlife. The Mallory Square Sunset Celebration is a nightly affair that draws locals and tourists alike with spectacular sunset views, street performers, and a celebratory air. From here, the crowd breaks up only to converge again in smaller pockets at Key West\''s many bars. Irish Kevin\''s is right in the thick of it with live music and stand-up comedy every night of the week, paired with drinking games and plenty of dancing. Duval Street is Key West\''s answer to New Orleans\'' Bourbon Street, with its dazzling neon signs and sidewalks teeming with party-goers. Down Duval Street you\''ll find more refined nighttime diversions at establishments like the Porch; set in a 19th-century, Victorian Mansion, this popular bar serves craft beer alongside an impressive wine list. The Little Room Jazz Club is a polished venue for live music, with an elegant decor, indoor and outdoor seating, a large-screen TV with a live feed from the Atlantis Aquarium and fine wine to boot. Virgilio\''s on the other hand, is best known for its stellar cocktail selection, and the Aqua Nightclub for its dueling bartenders, drag shows, idol karaoke and poker tournaments. With such a wide berth of venues to explore, many visitors opt for bar crawls to get a feel for the island\''s star-studded nightlife.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1057,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Key West</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Key West is a rather small island that is about 4 miles (6.4 kilometers) long and 2 miles (3.2 kilometers) wide. Whether you want to relax on the beach or spend the day shopping, Key West has plenty to offer. Duval Street is the center of Key West life, with many hotels, guest houses, inns and bed & breakfasts, plus dozens of shops, restaurants, and bars nestled amid the tropical locale. If you get thirsty, stop in for a cocktail and a snack at Southernmost Beach Cafe. Take a walk down the Harborwalk at the Historic Seaport and enjoy spellbinding views of the sprawling ocean alongside shops and restaurants. You can also witness turtle feedings at Turtle Cannery Museum. Then stop for a bite to eat at Conch Republic Seafood Company or Half Shell Raw Bar. If you get tired of the beach, head to Key West Butterfly & Nature Conservatory where you can observe about 60 species of butterflies. You should also go to Key West Aquarium where you can learn more about the marine animals and sea life that teems in the waters just off the shores of the Keys. The aquarium features a number of interactive exhibits, making this a particularly popular choice for families with kids.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Key Largo</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Key Largo is another island and is occasionally referred to as the \"Diving Capital of the World,\" its coral reefs attracting divers from across the globe. John Pennekamp Coral Reef State Park is a protected park where you can view coral reefs and colorful sea life. The state park also offers an aquarium, museum, and campsites as well as ample opportunity for activities like snorkeling, diving, and boating. Pennekamp Park is a treasure trove of local flora including wild orchids, gumbo limbo, wild cotton, strangler fig, tamarind trees, wild coffee, and mahogany trees. If you want to see endangered animals go to Key Largo Hammocks State Botanical Site where the mangrove trees grow a \"hammock\" which is basically a small island that attracts animals.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Islamorada</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Billed as the \''sportfishing Capital of the World\'', Islamorada\''s waters are home to the Conch, Alligator and Pickles reefs, and a vast array of marine life. It\''s a destination for scuba divers and snorkelers. A sunken ship off the shore of Islamorada is an especially popular spot for dives.Those interested in Keys\'' geology should visit the Windley Key Fossil Reef State Geologic Site; a reef that\''s no longer underwater. Catch a boat to the Lignumvitae Key State Botanical State Park - a virgin hardwood forest -, or visit the Indian Key State Historic Site, once the Miami area\''s county seat! Both of these are accessible only via ferry.You can also feed tarpon off the docks at Robbie\''s Marina or swim with dolphins, manta rays and sea lions at the Theater of the Seas.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Marathon and the Middle Keys</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This history of Marathon and the Middle Keys can be traced back to the 1800s, and a few residents of the islands are descendants of these early settlers. Bahamians raised tropical fruit for a living; New England fishermen searched the sea for its bounty; and in 1908, Henry Flagler\''s Overseas Railway reached Key Vaca, where the village of Marathon grew as headquarters for the railroad\''s final push to Key West. Here your adventure can include a swim with dolphins, an iguana introduction, a visit to a hardwood hammock or rainforest, and a loll on sandy beaches. Roaring jet skis and other water sports are available as well as fishing at the reefs, the flats or in the deep. To learn more about early Indian settlements, visit the Museums of Crane Point, which encompass the Museum of Natural History of the Florida Keys and the Florida Keys Children\''s Museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bahia Honda and the Lower Keys</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Big Pine Key is the center of life in the Lower Keys. Looe Key Reef off Big Pine Key is one of the Keys\'' top diving spots and one of the best reefs for diving in the world. In July each year, the Sanctuary sponsors a popular music festival promoting the preservation of the Keys\'' coral reefs. So popular is Bahia Honda State Park that campers reserve space months in advance to ensure a place in this waterfront paradise with its pristine beaches and warm waters.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
