 (1095,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Opera and Philharmonics</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For those who would like to experience some classical entertainment in this classic city, there is much on offer. The Philharmonic Hall offers a wide range of musical performances. There is a fresh new Opera stage in the city as well as a dozen or more theater companies.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Any performance at the <span>Slowacki Theater</span> is magical as the building itself is beautiful. To see the varied history of Poland\''s fairy tales portrayed on stage, visit the Groteska Theater in the Old Town. And for traditional theater performances, go to the Old Theater or Theater Stary as it is also known, which has entertained audiences since 1798. The Ludowy Theater showcases an impressive repertoire of Polish plays, while the Bagatela Theatre is a longstanding vestige of the early twentieth century.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Live Music and Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In Kazimierz you can recapture some of the lost Jewish tradition by attending <em>Klezmer</em> concerts and other traditional musical evenings. These take place at Klezmer Hois and Alef.Many of the city\''s bars offer live music, often jazz. These are great places to meet friends or new people. They vary in atmosphere and style from pub-style locals to underground bars in classic Gothic cellars. Traditional favorites are Harris Piano Jazz Bar, U Muniaka and Klub Indigo. But the best places where you can listen life music in the evening are: the Piano Rouge or Stalowe Magnolie, which offers jazz and pop music. There are also popular concerts of classical music in churches like St. Peter and Paul church, St. Adalbert church, Bonerowski Palace or Piwnica pod Baranami where visitors can hear Chopin music.Kraków - like all Polish cities — used to go to bed early, but not anymore. There are now many dance clubs that stay open until wee hours of the morning. For those who wish to have fun and go dancing there are a lot of options, including Frantic Club, Shaker\''s, or Baccarat.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Kraków has some fine museums, several of which are quite unique. Don\''t miss the famous Czartoryski Museum, the site of the famous painting of Leonardo da Vinci\''s \"Lady with Armine\" and Rembrandt\''s \"Landscape of Good Samarytanin\". For anyone with a love for art, the Museum of Contemporary Art in Krakow must definitely not be missed. The  Kraków History Museum, located in the baroque splendor of the Krzysztofory Palace is a riveting journey of history from the 16th through the 20th century. The Jan Matejko House exhibits exceptional paintings of the eponymous Polish painter and is worth a visit, as is the Manggha Center of Japanese Art and Technology.It is hardly surprising that the city that birthed several Polish artists who left their mark long after they were gone will be anything but teeming with a host of art galleries, exhibiting everything from nuanced, fine art collections, to avante-garde specimens of contemporary art. Some of the city\''s best art galleries that must not be missed include the MOCAK, the Nova Gallery, the Olympia Galeria, and the Bunkier Sztuki housed within Planty Park.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1096,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Old Town</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Old Town is one of the largest (and most concentrated) collections of historical buildings anywhere in the world. Occupying the very center of the city, this district is separated from the rest of the city by a belt of parkland. This green area (now popular with cyclists and walkers) was once where the defensive walls and a moat were located. Steeped in history, this medieval old town was one of the first towns to enter the list of UNESCO\''s World Heritage Sites. In its heyday, the Old Town was the seat of political power, which saw King Sigismund III Vasa\''s reign, until the shift to the current capital of Warsaw in 1596. A powerful surge of history grips the entire district, its storied past palpable even today. You will be mysteriously drawn toward the magnificence of the Rynek Główny, or the Main Square, known as Europe\''s largest medieval town square. Surrounding this glorious square are a wealth of monumental landmarks from a regal era, including St. Mary\''s Basilica (Kościół Mariacki), Church of St. Wojciech (St. Adalbert\''s) and Church of St. Barbara. A jumble of aristocratic buildings hearken back to memories of the city when it once teemed with nobles. The Town Hall Tower, reaches for the skies in its imposing form next to the Sukiennice, a Renaissance-era hub of cloth trade that also houses the National Gallery of Art.The Royal Road, Old Town\''s main thoroughfare as well as the historic path that once witnessed regal coronations, slices the district into parts, and is dotted with several landmarks like the St. Florian\''s Church and the Kraków Barbican. The Wawel, the royal complex that consists of the castle and the eponymous cathedral sits along a verdant stretch of the Vistula River in Old Town, still resplendent in its age-old glory. Traditionally this was where the best and most fancy shops were located, where the finest restaurants could be found and where the most desirable hotels were situated. These days, with the advent of shopping malls and entertainment centers well outside the center and with modern, well-equipped hotels also some distance away, this traditional dominance is being somewhat challenged.However, the ever-increasing number of tourists means that the restaurants are flourishing, the hotels are full and the shops very much cater to tourists. The locals too love nothing more than a pleasant Saturday stroll through the Old Town.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Kazimierz District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Brought to the world\''s attention by the movie \"Schindler\''s List,\" the traditional Jewish area is coming back to life after years of neglect.Kazimierz was named after Casimir the Great who gave the town its charter in 1335. In that era and for centuries afterwards, it functioned as a separate town. It had a separate administration and was also physically separated from Kraków by an arm of the Wisla river. A bridge was built in 1802 and finally the section of the river was completely filled in, forming what is now Ulica Dietla.Within the boundaries of Kazimierz is an area called Stradom. This was also originally independent but was incorporated into Kazimierz way back in 1415. There are many fine churches and historical buildings here.The Jewish area of Kazimierz is the site of a handful of synagogues and other important monuments, such as the cemetery. Some landmarks of importance include the Ethnographic Museum of Kraków, the Galicia Jewish Museum, and the Corpus Christi Basilica. Over the past few years many new cafés, restaurants and hotels have been opening up.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This area is made up of the sections of Kraków that lie outside the Old Town Walls. One of its districts is Zwierzyniec, which used to be the royal hunting grounds and now contains the popular 48 hectare Blonia Meadow. There are many other fine ancient buildings to be found here, including wooden churches. The district is known for its festivals and strong sense of tradition.Bronowice is a green and leafy suburb that was once a separate town. It is known throughout Poland as the location of the famous \"Wesele\" (Wedding), a popular Polish play. Other suburbs of note are Kleparz (north of the city), Wesola, Podgorze and Nowa Huta.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nowa Huta</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In 1949, the new Communist rulers of Poland decided that the country needed to be industrialized. Kraków, as a seat of intellectual power with a long history of rebellion and dissent, was seen as a distinct threat. A huge industrial and workers residential complex was built just outside the city. A massive metallurgical plant was constructed which immediately began spewing a toxic blend of dirt and pollutants. The monuments, churches, buildings and streets of Kraków were soon affected and began to decay. Today, much has been done to alleviate this problem and the air is getting cleaner.While Nowa Huta is the city\''s relatively newer district, it is also the most densely populated. It is well-known for its sprawling size and typical Socialist architecture. However, it does have several redeeming features: it is more open and spacious than the city\''s other districts, it is close to several forests and parks and it contains two picturesque artificial lakes. Some of the architecture here is also noteworthy. Notable landmarks include the PRL Museum, the  Arka Pana Church, and the Roman Catholic Parish of St. Bartholomew and St John.  Each district offers a different perspective on the past and together they make up what is one of the most historic and beautiful cities in the world.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
