 (1114,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater and Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If stage arts are your passion, you are in a some real treat in Kyoto. Here you will find colorful <em>kabuki </em>spectacles, stylized Noh drama, the craftsmanship of <em>bunraku</em> puppet theater, and the comedy of <em>kyogen</em> pantomime. You will delight to the eerie and otherworldly sounds of <em>gagaku</em> court music, and even the rituals of <em>Sado</em> (the tea ceremony) can be highly entertaining. Fortunately, you do not have to travel all over the city to witness such an array of Japanese traditions. Just pay a visit to Gion Corner Theater in the heart of the city, where a sampling of these many performing arts can be seen twice daily from March through November. For something really special, also check out the Pontocho Kaburenjo Theater, where you can see live performances of the traditional geisha dance, known as <em>Kamogawa Odori</em>, which combines dancing, singing and <em>Kabuki</em>-like theater.  Another must-see is the Minamiza Theater, which has been staging <em>Kabuki</em> theater since 1615.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you prefer your entertainment on the move, rather than viewed from a seat in the audience, you are also in luck. Perhaps no other city in Japan has such famous local festivals, such as Aoi Matsuri in May, the parade of floats at the Gion Matsuri in July, and the huge bonfires of the Daimonji Fire Festival in August. Each October, more than 2,000 people in period costumes take to Kyoto\''s streets in celebration of the \"Festival of the Ages,\" or Jidai Matsuri, wending their way from the old Kyoto Imperial Palace to the spacious grounds of Heian Shrine.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As the sun sets and you begin to yearn for a healthy dose of nightlife, look no further than the Gion district and the downtown streets nearby. This is the traditional playground of aristocracy and the working class alike, where <em>mizushobai</em>, or the \"water trade,\" has been practiced successfully for centuries--and still is! You will most certainly want to pay a visit to Pontocho Dori, opposite Gion and just west of the Kamo River. This long, narrow street is lined on both sides by bars and restaurants. It is a fun place to explore at night, and you will certainly want to pop into some of the more inviting spots, such as live house Taku Taku with its big-name bands and Butterfly Club with its stylish modern motif.  A word to the wise, however - some of the buildings you will see here actually <em>are</em> geisha houses. Your curiosity may be piqued, but venture inside with caution. Not only are they terribly expensive, they are usually off limits to non-Japanese visitors as well. But if you would like to see live geisha dances in Pontocho, without the high prices, they are performed at Kamogawa Odori at Pontocho Kaburencho every spring. For less traditional, more contemporary evening entertainment, take a stroll from Pontocho to parallel Kiyamachi Dori or perpendicular Kawaramachi Dori. These streets provide a lively collection of eateries and watering holes that offer all comers a convivial welcome. Drop in at Kyoto\''s popular Irish bar, K6, for a pint of Guinness; it\''s one of the city\''s best known drinking spots. For a night out Japanese-style, sit at the counter bar of a typical <em>nomiya</em> (drinking spot). After a long day of temple-hopping, there is perhaps nothing more relaxing than to sip sake (rice wine) and nibble <em>otsumami</em> (pub grub) in the company of friends because wherever you go, you will be among friends in Kyoto, one of the most hospitable and fascinating cities in the world.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Brewery Tours</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For <em>sake</em> lovers, the city has a wide variety of bars and breweries, mostly concentrated in the Fushimi district. Here, the quality of water, and history of rice cultivation has led to the production of some of the country\''s best rice wine or sake.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Art</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While much of Kyoto itself is like one big open-air museum, thanks to its elegant historic architecture and adherence to centuries-old cultural traditions, the city has an excellent selection of museums exhibiting everything from ancient Japanese art to more modern interpretations. A few of these include the Kyoto National Museum, Kyoto Museum of Traditional Crafts Fureaikan, and Kyoto International Manga Museum.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1115,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Kyoto</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Like other major cities in Japan, central Kyoto is packed with things to do and places to see. Spread across several wards, including Nakagyo-ku, Higashiyama-ku and Shimogyu-ku, visitors can find everything from high-fashion to ancient culture. Two important Buddhist temples, the Nishi Hoganji and Higashi Honganji, are located right near Kyoto Station, while elegant, Japanese style lodgings can be found at Hiiragi-ya. The popular Gion district, Kyoto\''s most famous Geisha district, is full of shops and restaurants, and is perfect for a stroll, particularly down Hanami-koji street, which is lined with traditional wooden merchant houses. For something more tranquil, the stepped approaches to Kiyomizudera are the ideal place to enjoy the sights and smells of cherry blossom season.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sakyo-ku</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Home of the beautiful and often-photographed Ginkaku-ji (Silver Pavillion) temple, Sakyo-ku covers the East and Northeast areas of Kyoto. Largely residential in the South, with strict restrictions placed on the construction of tall buildings, and mountainous in the north, this is a great destination for those that want to escape central Kyoto. The cold months of January and February bring the Setsubun Festival to Yoshida Shrine, while the Honen-in Jodo temple is a perfect place to enjoy the peace and tranquility of this ward all year. Sakyo-ku is also home to Kyoto University.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ukyo-ku</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Full of beautiful scenery and many historical and religious sites, Ukyo-ku covers a large area of Kyoto to the West and Northwest. A few of the prominent sites include Jingo-ji, a Shingon Buddhist temple that dates back to 781, and Tenryu-ji, a temple of the Rinzai sect that is well-known for its dry landscaped gardens. Visitors might also want to stay for lunch at Tenryu-ji Shigetsu, where they can sample the six flavors of Zen vegetarian cooking. For hiking enthusiasts, the Atago Jinja Shrine is located atop the highest point in Kyoto\''s western mountain range.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Kita-ku</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Though a mainly residential area, Kita-ku still has a number of things worth seeing, including Kinkaku-ji (Golden Pavillion) and the famous Daitoku-ji complex of Zen temples. But if you\''re visiting Kyoto in April, be sure to visit the Hirano Jinja shrine, famous for its cherry blossoms. Because of its location just north of busy Central Kyoto, seeing this part of the city is an easy and convenient diversion. Before you head back south though, finish off a trip to Kita-ku with an adventurous meal of blowfish at Uotake.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Arashiyama</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Lying to the west of Tokyo, Arashiyama is lauded for its natural beauty. Nestled in the base of the eponymous mountains, the area\''s top attractions are the otherworldly bamboo groves, the Zen Buddhist Tenryu-ji Temple with its ethereal gardens set amidst the mountains, and the hilltop monkey retreat of Kameyama-koen Park.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Fushimi</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Southern Kyoto\''s Fushimi district\''s claim to fame is the monumental mountain shrine of Fushimi Inari, belonging to the Shinto sect and welcoming thousands of tourists and pilgrims every year. Also known as the city\''s <em>sake</em> district, the district\''s canal-lined streets are home to a number of historic breweries like the Gekkeikan Okura Kinenkan that even has a museum dedicated to the art of <em>sake</em> production.&nbsp;</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
