 (1193,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Barranco</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The well-known district of Barranco is known for its leisurely strolls, bars and <em>bohemia</em>. Located, along the Chorrillos, at the southern tip of Lima Bay along the shoreline and the Avenida Bolognesi, it is the dividing line between the two different faces of this city: the historic residential area and the other a bustling working class area.The historic district lies between Avenida Bolognesi and the <em>malecón</em> (quayside), where mid-19th century streets, parks and gardens can be enjoyed. Follow the seafront southward to the beaches lining the coast, to arrive at the Bajada de los Baños, a romantic location to savor typical local dishes, or enjoy a drink while gazing out over a beautiful ocean view.The Parque Municipal is found just past this area. Retaining the aristocratic airs of yesteryear, most of Barranco\''s cafes, restaurants, bars and pubs—housed in mansions—are clustered around this plaza. Like the traditional Bar Juanito, most attract the local bohemians, artists and other patrons who come to Barranco for a good time.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Miraflores</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Miraflores is without a doubt the area with the most commercial activity, drawing throngs of tourists on a daily basis. Filled to the brim with shopping malls, cinemas, hotels, it boasts the highest concentration of cafes in Lima. Located along a sloping shoreline, its surrounding promenade leads to the beaches and parks along with the modern shopping complex, Larcomar.The district is also well-known for its nightlife and shopping. Grab a pizza along the street named after this dish, the <em>Calle de las Pizzas</em> or take to the floor in one of the modern dance clubs, with the latest techno and trance sounds. A number of casinos, boutiques, parks and luxury hotels are also located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The streets, plazas and alleyways of the historical center of Lima have a myriad of cafes and restaurants sewn into its sinuous stretch. There are also colonial and republican buildings, along the centuries-old streets, house museums, beautiful, cavernous Renaissance and Baroque churches, old mansions of particular historic interest like Casa de Osambela Oquendo and Palacio de Torre Tagle; as well as landmarks such as the Iglesia de San Francisco and the Lima Art Museum, close to the Justice Palace.From the expansive Plaza de Armas, you have the choice of wandering along one side of the Government Palace toward the charming little plaza in front of Iglesia de San Francisco. On the other side of the palace the alleyway known as Alameda Chabuca Granda is ideal for taste testing typical local sweets and if luck has it, catching a live concert of traditional Criollo or Afro-Peruvian music. There are a host of traditional old bars which serve food and drink in an atmosphere reminiscent of the days of yore, such as Cordano and the Queirolo, which makes its own wine.Lima\''s city nightlife is varied. For drinks, try the <em>choperías</em> (beer pubs) such as Piano Bar Munich on the Jirón de la Unión street. Stroll the alleyways of Santa Rosa and Los Escribanos and stop for a coffee, ice cream, snack, or browse through a bookshop. Though there are a few night-clubs in this area, it is not the safest of places to venture after dark.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">San Isidro</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Originally, this district was an upper class residential area where the scenic neighborhoods are arranged around attractive parks of large, stately trees, such as Olivar de San Isidro, and El Club de Golf. The ruins of Huaca Huallamarca is also one of its main landmarks. Today the area is best described as a shopping and financial district. As many as 38 embassies and consulates grace the streets of this district, along with banking institutions, synagogues, churches, and temples. The Ovalo Gutiérrez district is also alive with shops, cafes, and other activities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">La Victoria</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hemmed by Lima\''s central district on the west, La Victoria is considered one of the city\''s most populated districts in the city. It stretches from Avenida Grau to Avenida Mexico. The heart of this district is teeming with local stores, while the Pedro Canepa Park mall is the only commercial mall here. Strewn across the district are several green spaces and a few colleges as well. The suburbs of Balconcillo and Santa Catalina are largely residential, with the latter being the more affluent of the two. The Estadio Alejandro Villanueva, home ground of the Peruvian Alianza Lima team, is located here. Each November, the streets of La Victoria come alive with the procession of the Lord of Miracles, where a revered 17th Century painting of Jesus Christ is paraded, and a feast also marks the celebration.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outlying District of Callao</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This airport district has an important maritime port that serves the entire country. The Callao Port was established in 1537 in order transport riches from the new world back to Spain. Don\''t forget to visit the Fortaleza del Real Felipe which is located in the port and the natural beauty of the Isla San Lorenzo where you can sunbathe, explore aquatic caves and enjoy some delicious seafood. Though Callao is considered part of the greater Lima metropolitan area, Callao is administratively separate from the capital and more than 600,000 people reside in the district.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
