 (1202,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you have an eye for art, check out the mixed ancient and modern art collection at the Calouste Gulbenkian Museum. The gallery comprises two distinct circuits, showcasing everything from Greco-Roman and Persian pieces to 18th-century French and Dutch Renaissance works, respectively. You can also peruse exhibits dedicated to both national and international artists at the Museu Colecão Berardo in the Belém Cultural Center or check out specialty museums like the stunning National Tile Museum.History buffs have more than enough to stay busy in Lisbon, as well. Many of the city\''s historic sites also house adjoining museums. Can\''t-miss examples include early Jesuit church Igreja de São Roque and the Carmo Archaeological Museum, which was founded on the ruins of the Carmo Convent. Moreover, you\''ll be blown away by the Mosteiro dos Jerónimos UNESCO World Heritage Site and its maritime and archaeology museums.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parks & Gardens</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Those that enjoy quiet, relaxing respites from the busier parts of the city will enjoy the Parque das Nações area of Lisbon. Its calm natural atmosphere sets an excellent stage for such activities as tram rides by the Tagus or breezy walks along the marina. For a more traditional park setting replete with greenery, try the Eduardo VII Park situated north of Avenida da Liberdade. When it comes to gardens in Lisbon, the Jardim de São Pedro de Alcântara is your best bet. You\''ll not only find a charming garden but also a lookout boasting spectacular views of the Baixa district below. Once at the viewpoint, you can even enjoy a glass of port or savory snack from one of the site\''s many vendors.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Concerts & Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Lisbon hosts numerous national and international artists every year. Concerts are normally held at the Coliseu dos Recreios, Altice Arena in Parque das Nações, or the Belém Cultural Center. As music festivals go, Super Bock Super Rock takes over various venues around the city in June or July, showcasing some of the best bands of the pop and rock music scenes.Also in summer, particularly June, Lisbon throws parties in honor of its patron saint, Santo António. Marches and celebrations sweep the Portuguese capital, offering a truly unique cultural experience. If you visit during the festivities, be sure to catch the parade on Avenida República.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife in Lisbon is a mixed bag. While you will find options suited to varied tastes, all visitors should experience one of the many Casas de Fado found around the city. These clubs celebrate Fado music, a unique genre treasured by the Portuguese, and live performances are common in the Bairro Alto, Alfama, and Costa do Castelo districts. Another area with a thriving nightlife scene is the Docas. You\''ll find nightclubs beside the Tagus beckoning with world music, as well as bars and open-late restaurants. Beloved joints like Dock\''s Club offer common ground for locals and visitors to enjoy nights on the town and make lifelong memories.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1203,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Alfama</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Alfama is the oldest district in Lisbon and predictably houses many of the cities historic attractions. Tour the neighborhood on a tram dating back to the 1930s, stopping at historic sights like the Castelo de São Jorge, a Moorish fortress from the 11th century, and lovely Lisbon Cathedral. Surrounding the castle are charming streets lined with traditional Portuguese architecture and exuding warmth and friendliness. Visitors to the area will most certainly notice the hospitality of the Portuguese people, which in itself is one of the city\''s biggest attractions.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Barrio Alto & Baixa</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Barrio Alto is perhaps best known for its nightlife. You\''ll find a large number of restaurants, bars, and nightclubs in the area, not to mention plenty of people enjoying the scene. The downtown area of Baixa is a commercial area where myriad shops are found, including popular souvenir shops for visitors. Extending from the Baixa area is famous Avenida da Liberdade, which also boasts plenty of shopping options, notably haute couture and designer brands like Armani and Louis Vuitton.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Belém</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Situated at the mouth of the Tagus River, Belém houses a significant chunk of Lisbon\''s most renowned attractions and landmarks. In the 14th and 15th centuries, the imposing Torre de Belém was the departure point for historical expeditions in search of new worlds. Other beautiful monuments in Belém dedicated to Portuguese explorers include the Mosteiro dos Jerónimos and the Padrão dos Descobrimentos. Continue exploring and stumble on the Centro Cultural de Belém, also known as the CCB, which accommodates international art exhibits and events throughout the year. A truly special sight, the CCB also houses the Museu Berardo, where renowned modern art abounds. Just some of the artists who have had their works displayed are Dali, Picasso, Warhol, Pollock, and countless others, making this museum a Lisbon must-see. If you fall in love and want to soak up more of Belém on a stroll, head to the nearby Docas area for a scenic retreat.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Graça & São Vicente</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A venerable Lisbon suburb, the Graça and São Vicente areas have combined to make a lovely district overlooking the rest of the city. Its hilltop location yields some of the most awe-inspiring views around, notably from the Miradouro de Graca and Miradouro da Senhora do Monte viewpoints. Although it is predominantly residential and fairly quiet, the Graça & São Vicente district is oozing with local flair, making it an area well worth visiting for an authentic meal or walk about town.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Parque das Nações</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A modern district, Parque das Nações was created on the northeastern side of the Tagus River from bits of surrounding parishes. It was intended as a commercial and residential area, but following significant refurbishment in recent years, the district has become a popular spot for locals and tourists alike to pass time. Top attractions in the Parque das Nações area include the Lisbon Oceanarium and Casino Lisboa.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outside the City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Lisbon is surrounded by charming and intriguing towns that offer their own can\''t-miss sights. West of the city is beautiful Cascais, a coastal town dense with beaches. Cascais\'' rich history is evidenced by its wealth of historical landmarks and attractions. South, you\''ll also find Costa da Caparica, a fishing village that represents the traditional coastal lifestyle. While you may never get enough of Lisbon itself, discover wonders outside the city to experience all things Portuguese.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
