 (1280,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Melbourne is blessed with a sizable arts scene, led by the renowned Melbourne Museum and National Gallery of Victoria. At the Melbourne Museum, visitors can study up on topics ranging from Aboriginal culture to underwater wonders. Better suited to art lovers, the impressive National Gallery of Victoria showcases both domestic and international artists, displaying works by such names as Degas, Monet, Boyd, Picasso, and Nolan.Smaller and specialty museums and galleries include the National Sports Museum, Australian Centre for the Moving Image, ArtVo, and Immigration Museum. Two landmarks, the Shrine of Remembrance and Melbourne Cricket Ground, also offer educational experiences in their onsite museums. If you\''re traveling to the city and reserve some time to check out the arts and history scenes, you definitely won\''t be disappointed.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Live Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Melbourne is widely regarded as the live music capital of Australia. Everyone who is anyone in the Australian music scene plays here regularly, and almost-legendary venues are packed every night with fans looking for old favorites or the next big thing. You\''ll find any number of spots to get down to alternative rock, and those interested can also enjoy emerging funk, jazz, and hip hop scenes. Those with more discerning musical tastes have their own slew of options. Have a night out with the Melbourne Symphony Orchestra or Opera Australia. While in town, you can also check out the brilliant 85-piece Australian Pops Orchestra or delightful Australian Boys Choir. The sky is truly the limit when it comes to live music is this exciting city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Melbourne\''s lively theater scene offers everything from experimental works to mainstream, Broadway-style blockbusters like Miss Saigon or the Phantom of the Opera. Better still, the hosts its shows in truly beautiful and historic theaters, such as Her Majesty\''s and the Princess Theatre.  Ballet and dance are as good as any in the world, and the Australian Ballet performs 160 shows a year to packed houses. For something a bit funkier, Chunky Move diverges from traditional theater venues, performing bold works in club-type settings. OzOpera similarly abandons tradition and brings its own version of opera to everyday people in Melbourne and across Victoria. Otherwise, the city hosts a full range of cinemas, from Hoyts and Village blockbuster multiplexes to arthouses like the Astor. An international film festival is held every winter while summer in the city would not be the same without the Moonlight Cinema set in the beautiful surrounds of the Royal Botanical Gardens.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">English-style pubs have traditionally been the bedrock of Melbourne\''s nightlife scene, and the city is blessed with plenty. Every area will have one, which range from grungy to elegant venues. There are traditional watering holes like the quirky Builder\''s Arms. Usually open in the afternoon through midnight or later, many of these establishments serve food as well as providing beer gardens, satellite television, pool tables, or live music. Recently, a slew of stylish, intimate bars have evolved in the lanes and alleyways of the central business district. They draw an eager crowd of after-work drinkers and stay open late. Try a cocktails and comedy at Spleen on Bourke Street or simply explore until you find a place of your own—they seem to pop up in little recesses of the city overnight! Melbourne\''s club scene is large and varied but concentrated in a few different districts. King Street in the city center is home to several large and well-known establishments. South Yarra around Chapel Street attracts a hipper crowd to venues like Revolver while Brunswick and Smith Streets in Fitzroy cater to a more bohemian, alternative crowd with a smaller venue, the Night Cat. St Kilda, home to Monkey, is also a lively part of town. The Crown Entertainment Complex is home to a variety of establishments, from cabarets to wine bars to jazz clubs. Its casino is one of the largest in the world, housing a five-star hotel and plethora of shops and restaurants on the southern bank of the Yarra River.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals & Events</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Melbourne keeps a packed events calendar throughout the year. It hosts a major international arts festival known as the Fringe Festival, and the family-oriented Moomba Waterfest is an equally good time. There are separate celebrations for comedy, contemporary visual art, gardening, writing, fashion, and food. There are also Italian, Greek, Vietnamese, and Chinese festivals, not to mention happenings in St Kilda, Chapel Street, Williamstown, and Brunswick Street. Summer is the time for outdoor cinema, classical music, and jazz, and Melbourne also hosts trade fairs for industries as diverse as holidays, motoring, and aeronautics.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Melbourne is renowned for its major international sporting events, including the Australian Open Grand Slam tennis tournament, the Grand Prix motor race, marathons, cricket tests, and major golf tournaments. But perhaps its biggest sporting events are its most unique. The AFL Grand Final decides the champion of the national football code, and the famous Melbourne Cup horse race is held like clockwork on the second Tuesday of November, bringing the whole city, if not the nation, to a halt.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1281,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Central Business District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Laid out as a grid, the Melbourne city center is delightfully easy to navigate. The modern skyline of the financial district contrasts with well-preserved Victorian architecture, and the alleyways and arcades that snake through the city give it undeniable charm and character. Swanston Street, generally considered the city\''s main drag, runs from the ornate 19th-century domes of Flinders Street Station to the gleaming, billion-dollar Melbourne Central Shopping Complex. Elsewhere, the stretch of Collins Street between Swanston and Spring Streets is a more exclusive shopping strip. Known as \"the Paris end\" of the city, it is home to luxury boutiques, upmarket offices, and prestigious hotels. Running parallel is Bourke Street, the oldest and most successful pedestrian precinct in the city, where major department stores like David Jones and Myer are located. A block away, the entrance to Melbourne\''s Chinatown on Little Bourke Street is marked by an ornate Chinese arch. Spilling into the surrounding alleys, the worldly area represents one of the oldest Chinatowns outside Asia and plays host to a variety of restaurants and grocery stores.The area between Swanston and Spencer Streets is nine-to-five territory, Australia\''s corporate heartland and headquarters of many of its largest enterprises. Ambitious plans are afoot to further extend this area by redeveloping the derelict warehouses of the adjacent docklands. The Etihad Stadium was the first project to be unveiled, and if the developers have their way, the world\''s tallest building will soon follow. To the south and east lies a vast and beautifully maintained belt of parkland, containing the Fitzroy Gardens and Melbourne Cricket Ground, with the Royal Botanical Gardens lying just across the Yarra River.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Southbank</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">On the southern bank of the muddy and surprisingly narrow river lies the landmark Victorian Arts Centre and chic Southgate shopping and dining precinct. Further along is the glitzy Crown Entertainment Complex, which offers 24-hour entertainment, luxury stores, nightclubs, eateries, and one of the world\''s largest gaming facilities. Hugely controversial, it is one of the city\''s most popular, and popularly detested, sites. Whether the locals like it or not, it is also Melbourne\''s favorite visitor attraction. Directly opposite are the state-of-the-art Sea Life Melbourne Aquarium, Convention Center, and Exhibition Center.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Prahran & South Yarra</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Just outside of the city are Prahran and South Yarra, names often used interchangeably for roughly the same area. Home to Chapel Street, lined with boutiques and nightclubs, this is Melbourne\''s favorite playground. It\''s packed every weekend with young people out for only one thing—fun! Saturday nights see the street grind to a halt and transform into a traffic-jam disco as cars blare top volume techno music while the gay strip along Commercial Road buzzes alongside. The funkier, more relaxed Greville Street plays host to vintage fashion stores and a lively weekend market. South of Prahran is Toorak, which is synonymous with discreet wealth and home to many top executives.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">St Kilda</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Further out is St Kilda, which has transformed from a shabby red light district to a bayside resort and now serves as a popular place for backpackers and locals on sunny weekends. Its biggest attraction is the lively street life along Acland and Fitzroy Streets. The district also boasts Luna Park, an ornate and historic fun fair along the waterfront, as well as a lovely pier, weekend craft market, and the Prince of Wales hotel.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Carlton</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Carlton lies just north of Melbourne proper. Many of its quaint Victorian terrace houses have been converted into student accommodation for the nearby university, and the district\''s cafés and bookstores buzz with life. The new Melbourne Museum is located here in the beautiful Carlton Gardens. Lygon Street, arguably the city\''s premier dining strip, boasts a large Italian community, as well as restaurants serving Malay, Japanese, Vietnamese, and even Jamaican fare.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Fitzroy</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Even more cosmopolitan is Brunswick Street, one of Melbourne\''s liveliest and most distinctive streets. Originally a working class neighborhood, the Fitzroy area has emerged as the heartland of bohemian café culture. It hums night and day with colorful bars, nightclubs, and restaurants of every kind, as well as funky and unconventional stores.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Williamstown & Other Areas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A little further out, albeit still easily accessible by ferry or train, lies old Williamstown, a once-vital port. This quiet residential suburb has recently regained favor after many years in decline. Picturesque and historic streets, views over the sea, and pride in bygone days attract hundreds of weekend visitors throughout the year. Once home to Greek immigrants, the Richmond area has more recently become known as \"Little Saigon\" because of its growing Vietnamese community. You\''ll find delicious restaurants and shops along Victoria Street. Moreover, the factory outlet stores of Bridge Road and Swan Street offer some of the best bargain buys around. Tree-lined streets and beautiful town houses distinguish South Melbourne, which is popular both for its namesake South Melbourne Market and growing breakfast café scene. Port Melbourne is being transformed from derelict docks to inner city dwellings while Albert Park is home to the Grand Prix in addition to being a popular spot for joggers and dog walkers.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
