 (1328,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Milan\''s twice-yearly fashion weeks are at par with Paris and New York, and its streets are an ever-evolving tableau of the latest fashions. The locals strut the street in smart attire and daring outfits with as much poise as models on the runway. At the forefront of the latest trends and avant-garde fashion, Milan is a treasure trove for fashionistas and high-end shoppers. Most of the city\''s designer boutiques are clustered around the Quadrilatero d\''oro, edged in by Via della Spiga, Via Manzoni, Via Sant\''andrea and Via Montenapoleone. Milan is also home to the spectacular Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II, one of the world oldest shopping malls and the abode of Prada\''s flagship store since 1913. You don\''t have to break the bank to shop in Milan, however. There are several excellent outlet stores that offer designer clothing with discounts of up to 70 percent on the original price. Il Salvagente and DMAG Outlet are a couple of the most popular, while hidden gems like the Basement cater almost exclusively to locals in the know. For alternative fashion, head to corso di Porta Ticinese, corso Vercelli or the Isola area, behind Stazione Garibaldi. High-street shopping can also be had at Corso Buenos Aires, via Torino or corso Vittorio Emanuele.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Milan has plenty to offer in terms of great entertainment, culture and art. The city is home to the famous Pinacoteca di Brera and the Museo Cenacolo Vinciano, which houses artifacts relating to the Leonardo Da Vinci\''s <em>Last Supper</em> as well as the famous painting itself. There are a host of museums spread out across the city. The Museum of Science and Technology is a definite must for boffins and future Einsteins., while the \"Museums of the Center\" cover a range of topics including everything from the Revival period at the Museo del Risorgimento to contemporary history at the Museo di Milano. Piazza Duomo itself has the Duomo Museum, filled with tapestries, stained glass, and clerical vestments. Milan is rich with history, and close to the center stands the Castello Sforzesco, which has interesting archaeological and numismatic collections. Also in the vicinity are the Palazzo Bagatti Valsecchi and Museo Poldi Pezzoli. Although, not quite as grand as the Castle, they are just as interesting, replete with displays of textiles, furnishings and artwork. There are several art galleries as well that celebrate the city\''s long-standing penchant for the fine arts, such as the Pinacoteca Ambrosiana , the Civica Galleria d\''arte Moderna, and the Padiglione d\''arte Contemporanea. Veritable shrines of art, these galleries showcase Italian masters alongside established contemporary artists and emerging talents through a diverse program of exhibitions.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you\''re familiar with the world of classical theater and opera, one name is sure to spring to mind when you think of Milan: the world-famous Teatro alla Scala. Besides this legendary, historic venue, the city\''s principal theaters include the traditional Teatro San Babila, the Piccolo Teatro, founded by Strehler, and the Teatro Franco Parenti, which has devoted recent seasons to European culture. Milan has also recently rediscovered its passion for ballet and big-name musicals, such as <em>Singin\'' in the Rain</em>, <em>The Sound of Music</em> and the eternal <em>Rocky Horror Show</em>. Many of these are staged at the Teatro Ventaglio Nazionale. When it comes to classical music, the Teatro alla Scala and the Auditorium di Milano Fondazione Cariplo host performances by the symphony orchestra La Verdi, while the Conservatorio showcases lyrical concerts. more niche venues like the Nidaba Theatre and Blue Note cater to fans of jazz and blues music, adding diversity to the city\''s musical repertoire. Indie bars featuring local bands and underground acts, like Tunnel, are also aplenty.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Milan is a city that treasures cinematic brilliance and you\''ll find several multiplexes like the Colosseo and Eliseo that screen blockbusters and English films. For original language and foreign films, the Anteo SpazioCinema, Cinema Mexico and the Cinema Arcobaleno Film Center are top choices.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Milan has a lively, dynamic atmosphere day and night. The most crowded and trendiest nightspots are in the Brera, Ticinese and Navigli districts. Most of the fashionable bars are in Ticinese. In contrast,  Navigli is considered by some to be slightly retro, but is still adored by many; filled with lots of \"boho\" bars, it is just the place to go with a group of friends or in the company of your paramour. Brera and Isola are known as Milan\''s original hotspots; every bar here is fantastic. Glamor oozes from every door and this is a great area for an evening stroll. There is a huge amount of choice when it comes to clubs, discos, and bars. Friday is the day to go to Shocking Club and Hollywood is cool anytime, any day!</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
