 (1421,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Entertainment in Naples</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The people of Naples often have a buoyant, carefree personalities and are traditionally devoted to music, theater, and dance. The great cultural and creative legacy of the city has produced art of international appeal since the time of Ancient Greece. The plaintive, lyrical Neapolitan song tradition, for example, still charms the world.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theaters</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Naples, a city of passionate characters and everyday drama, has a theatrical tradition that runs deep. Actor-writers such as Eduardo Scarpetta, Carlo Giuffrè, and the beloved Eduardo De Filippo have given life to a great number of plays which are still performed throughout the city. Contemporary theater, particularly comedy, is also very much alive here.  Teatro Bellini opened as an opera house in 1864 and is now considered the most beautiful theater in Naples. Located near Piazza Dante, it offers a program of operatic and theatrical productions. Not far from the Bellini, on two streets which cut across Via Toledo, are two small theaters offering plays for young, cultured audiences: Galleria Toledo and the Teatro Nuovo. Though it is quite small, Sala Assoli, one of Teatro Nuovo\''s two performance spaces, has hosted spectacularly successful performances by some of Europe\''s finest actors and directors.Perhaps the best-loved of the Neapolitan theaters is the Sannazzaro, located on Via Chiaia not far from the Villa Comunale. It hosts popular theater, much of it linked to the tradition in Neapolitan dialect, and was a favorite of the most venerated local actors, including De Filippo, Nino Taranto, and Luisa Conte. Il Vomero, the posh, hilly district of the city, is home to another important theater, the Diana. Nearby, Teatro Cilea has a good theatrical school and offers works by local, contemporary writers. Other theaters to remember are the Palapartenope in Via Barbagallo, near the Palazzetto dello Sport, which hosts jazz and rock concerts. The Teatro dei Piccoli in Via Marco Polo offers a program of children\''s theater and music.The great Teatro San Carlo is another matter entirely. Adjacent to Piazza del Plebiscito, it is one of the city\''s most iconic monuments, and the oldest continuously active opera house in the world. It opened in 1737 and is considered second in importance only to the Scala in Milan, although it is larger and has impeccable acoustics. This temple of music has hosted world opera premieres for nearly three hundred years.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Naples has an intuitive, creative spirit, and it\''s also home to a treasure trove of first-rate museums. Visitors can tour palaces brimful with Baroque art, walk through preserved Roman ruins, marvel at the finest collection of Greco-Roman artifacts in the world, and see world-class contemporary art.The city\''s top museums are without a doubt the Museo di Capodimonte (Capodimonte Museum) and the Museo Archeologico Nazionale (National Archeological Museum).The Capodimonte Museum is southern Italy\''s largest art gallery, and has a vast permanent collection spread over 160 rooms and three floors, with works by Titian, Raphael, and Botticelli. The palatial building was originally designed as a hunting lodge for Charles VII of Bourbon. A small but worthwhile modern gallery houses Warhol\''s pop-tribute to Naples, <em>Mt. Vesuvius</em>. The museum\''s true highlight is Caravaggio\''s <em>The Flagellation of Christ</em>. It\''s secluded at the end of a corridor on the second floor, reverentially lit. The museum grounds are home to a regal public park, where families gather to picnic, kick a soccer ball, or catch the best views of the city. <em>Capodimonte</em> does mean, after all, \"the top of the hill.\" An hourly shuttle service runs between Piazza Trieste e Trento, the Catacombs of San Gennaro, and the museum.    Located down Corso Savoia from Capidomonte, the Museo Archeologico Nazionale is home to much of the Farnese collection, antiquities that Charles VII inherited from his mother, Elisabetta Farnese. Colossal sculptures from nearby sites in Pompeii, Herculaneum, and Stabiae stand on the ground floor. Highlights include <em>Ercole (Hercules)</em>, <em>Atlante Farnese (Atlantis),</em> and <em>Toro Farnese (Farnese Bull)</em>, a Roman copy of a Hellenistic sculpture depicting the death of the Queen of Thebes. Delicate mosaics mostly from Pompeii are on the mezzanine level. These include the striking, incomplete <em>La battaglia di Alessandro contro Dario (The Battle of Alexander against Darius)</em>, a wall-sized work considered the best-known depiction of Alexander the Great. A \"secret\" chamber beyond this section of the museum houses a small collection of ancient erotic art. The Catacombs of San Gennaro, an underground early Christian cemetery, became a pilgrimage site when San Gennaro, the city\''s patron saint, was buried there in the 5th Century. They are home to ancient mosaics, and sometimes host theater and music productions. The Capella Sansavero (Sansevero Chapel) is located smack dab in the center of Naples\'' historic center, and houses some very fine 18-century Italian art, including the remarkable <em>Cristo velato (Veiled Christ)</em>. Perched on the top of the Vomero neighborhood, The Museo San di Martino is 14th-century monastery with a large collection of Baroque art by Neapolitan masters. Visitors overwhelmed by the boundless collections of pre-modern art have some options. The Museo d\''arte Contemporanea Donnaregina, or, MADRE, houses contemporary art seen in most cosmopolitan cities, including works by Jeff Coons, Andy Warhol, Mimmo Paladino, and Damien Hirst. A horse sculpture called <em>Cavallo (Horse)</em> on the roof terrace is a treat. The Città della Scienza is an interactive science museum designed for children. It\''s located in Bagnoli, an ex-industrial district of Naples, in a 19th-century refurbished workshop near the sea.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Naples by night</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Naples has a vibrant nighthawk culture, and bars, pubs, sandwich bars, and spaghetti houses are full of young people from night until early in the morning.After the Second World War inhabitants took a liking to jazz, and more than a few great clubs remain, including Bourbon Street, Miles Jazz Club, and Libreria Berisio.Among the most popular dance clubs are the Blues e Blues and The New Twentythree. The mythical La Mela near Via dei Mille is a longtime favorite and true nighttime hotspot. L\''antiquario is a classy jazz club and bar with great cocktails. Cammarota Spritz draws locals and travelers to the Spanish Quarter with inexpensive, generous drinks, friendly staff, and good food nearby.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1422,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Districts of Naples</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This city is rich in age-old history and contradictions. As a visitor, it\''s best to decide which of its attributes you\''d like to focus on: the mysterious aspect which has its roots in legends, or the city\''s intriguing and turbulent history? The idyllic bay waters and villas, or the dense humanity of the most populated urban zones in Europe? Savor the peerless food or the peerless art?  The legendary saying is, \"See Naples and die.\"  It\''s not meant literally, but once you\''ve come to know Naples, the thinking goes, you\''ve seen it all, and can pass away peacefully because nothing else will compare.  The city is divided into 21 zones, and has so many monuments that it\''s rightfully known as an open-air museum. Meanwhile, here is a little guide to allow you to choose the most significant places of interest and tourist attractions, should you find yourself in this glorious city, with a limited amount of time.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 1: Chiaia - Posillipo - San Ferdinando</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The monuments of this triangle are probably the ones that have made Naples famous, and offer one of the best itineraries for visitors. Piazza Municipio, one of the city\''s most impressive public squares, is itself dominated by the Castel Nuovo, or Maschio Angioino; within walking distance are the Teatro San Carlo, the splendid Galleria Umberto I°, the Piazza del Plebiscito with its semicircular colonnade, the majestic Palazzo Reale, and the domes of the splendid Chiesa di San Francesco di Paola. Down towards the sea are Santa Lucia and Borgo Marinaro, where the Castel dell\''ovo stands in all its glory.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 2: Avvocata - Mercato - Montecalvario - Pendino - Porto - San Giuseppe</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Naples is characterized by its uniformity in town planning. In fact, the quarters that makes up the ancient center still faithfully adhere to the Greco-Roman plans for the ancient city of Neapolis, from which Naples takes its name. In these quarters are layer upon layer of history, unfolding before the eyes like the pages of an enormous history book. The alleyways overflowing with life in quarters such as San Giuseppe, Porto, and Pendino are the same ones in which Greeks would trade and build temples during the 4th Century. This is also the area which faces the bay; you must visit and take a long walk along the promenade from Via Partenope past Via Caracciolo until Mergellina, or stop by at Villa Comunale, which is blessed with trees dating back centuries, neoclassical statues, and striking fountains; it is here that you will find the oldest aquarium in Europe. The most important monument in the zone is the Villa Pignatelli, which today is home to a museum. The Museo Civico Filangieri is also located on Via Duomo and is housed inside the Palazzo Como, which was built during the Renaissance. Piazzetta Nilo is situated on Via San Biagio dei Librai, in which sits a 2,000-year-old statue, Statua del Corpo di Napoli. Following Spaccanapoli you can find other examples of Neapolitan culture: in Piazza San Domenico Maggiore lies the Basilica di San Domenico Maggiore and numerous palazzi from the Aragon and Spanish era, such as the Guglia which was dedicated to the Saint at the center. The Cappella di Sansevero is also worth a visit. Piazza del Gesù Nuovo yields such treasures as the Chiesa di Santa Chiara, the Chiostro di Santa Chiara, the 16th-century façade of the Chiesa di Gesù Nuovo, and the Guglia dell\''immacolata. The San Giovanni Maggiore was built on the remains of the 4th-century temple of Hercules and faces the piazza of San Giovanni, where the chapel of San Giovanni di Pappacoda houses a stupendous Gothic doorway. All of these places are representative, but not unique to the zones that developed and grew into the <em>centro antico</em>. The Spanish quarters consist of the elegant Via Toledo with its historic palazzi and churches that contain masterpieces of 17th-century Neapolitan painters; Piazza Monteoliveto, which contains Palazzo Gravina; the Fontana built in honor of Carlos II of Spain; and the church Sant\''anna dei Lombardi with its wealth of Renaissance treasures; Piazza Dante with the 18th-century façade of the National Boarding School il Convitto Nazionale; and Port\''alba, where the lazzari di Masaniello got the better of the cannons of the Viceroy.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 3: San Carlo all\''arena - Stella</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Piazza della Sanità is home to the 17th-century Chiesa di Santa Maria, under which are the San Gaudosio Catacombs; the zona dei Vergini e zona delle Fontanelle are ancient areas used for burial in Greco-Roman Naples. Here you will also find the Palazzo Reale di Capodimonte, a palace built in 1738 and surrounded by a large park and wood, which acted as a hunting ground. On the grounds, with views of the cityscape, is the Museo di Capodimonte. The museum is a must visit, and houses Caravaggio\''s 17th-century masterpiece, <em>The Flagellation of Christ</em>.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 4: Poggioreale - San Lorenzo - Vicaria</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">It is practically impossible to list all the monuments in the three <em>decumani</em> and the numerous side streets (<em>i cardi</em>) which run perpendicular to them, but mention must be made of the following churches: San Paolo Maggiore which is built upon the foundations of the Tempio dei Dioscuri (two columns of the temple are still visible) and San Lorenzo Maggiore, underneath which are important archaeological remains which the public are able to visit. These two churches are located in Piazza San Gaetano, the ancient Roman marketplace along Via dei Tribunali. The church and street of San Gregorio Armeno are also worth a visit; the church was built on the site of a temple. Via dei Tribunali ends in front of Castel Capuano, the oldest fort in the city built for Norman kings. Behind it lies the Porta Capuana. Walking along Via Duomo, you will come across the Cathedral dedicated to San Gennaro, the city\''s patron saint. The cathedral seems to be in a place that does not seem grand enough for such an important building. You will also find the Duomo, which incorporates the ancient basilica of Santa Restituta built on the orders of Constantine, and the Battistero di San Giovanni in Fonte, which is the oldest baptistery in the western world. Beneath the Duomo lie ancient archaeological sites, which you can visit. The stratification begins with the ancient Greek and finishes with the Middle Ages. The Museo Archeologico Nazionale is one of the most important museums of its kind and is located in Piazza Museo. The Porta San Gennaro is located in Piazza Cavour and is one of the oldest gateways in the city. Via Santa Maria di Costantinopoli has many palazzi such as L\''accademia di Belle Arti and many dazzling churches. In Piazza Bellini one can still see traces of ancient Greek city walls. Other places of interest in the immediate vicinity are: Via Foria; Piazza Carlo III, which has an enormous façade; the Albergo dei Poveri; the Orto Botanico; Corso Garibaldi and the piazza of the same name, which is now the headquarters of Stazione Centrale.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 5: Arenella - Vomero</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">These are hill zones which were developed at the end of the 19th Century as a residential district for the Neapolitan bourgeoisie. Il Vomero underwent radical changes in the 1950s and 1970s, which made it into one of the busiest areas in the city. It is linked to surrounding areas by three funicular railways, and retains some of the city\''s most important monuments. The Castel Sant\''elmo and the Certosa di San Martino were built around 1350 and dominate the city from above. Today, La Certosa houses the Museo di San Martino, which shows collections, paintings, sculptures, documents, and relics of Neapolitan tradition. Villa Floridiana was given by King Ferdinando of Bourbon to his second wife. At the center of this park stands a small palace which is now a museum (Il Museo della Ceramica Duca di Martina). Visitor\''s should not let a visit to the catacombs of San Gennaro pass them by. The catacombs were dug from the yellow tuff of the Aminei hills in the Capodimonte at the beginning of the 2nd Century. The galleries, which create a kind of underground basilica, leave a lasting impression. The sepulcher of San Gennaro and the tombs of the bishops, where lies the bishop of Carthage, are also nearby.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Quartiere 10: Bagnoli - Fuorigrotta</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A modern residential zone where the Rai and the Politecnico have their headquarters, the Fuorigrotta is also the new home of the Università Federico II and sports complexes such as the Stadio San Paolo. The trade show venue Mostra d\''oltremare, and the Edenlandia theme park, are located here. Bagnoli, a former industrial zone, is now home to the Città della Scienza, an interactive science museum housed in one of the old shed steelworks on the banks facing the island of Nisida.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Province of Naples</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Outside of the city of Naples, there are fantastic day trips and sights to see via train or boat! The nearby cities of Salerno, Ercolano, Pompei and Sorrento attract visitors from all over the globe. Looking eastwards, behold the Bay of Pozzuoli along with the islands of Capri, Ischia, and Procida, and the historical Campi Flegrei.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1423,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">People who visit the Music City for the first time are always surprised by the lack of public transportation. Like many large cities in the Mid-South, Nashville has spread out, taking over land from plantations and farms and now covering a large area that limits the ability to walk from one district to another. Granted, there are a few public bus routes and many taxi companies, but Nashville is a lot like Los Angeles: people here like to drive. There are more parking lots downtown than office buildings, and yet parking remains at a premium. If you arrive by plane, your first step should be to rent a car. Don\''t depend on public transportation—it\''s just not a dependable or convenient option.  The one exception to this overriding need for a car is if you plan on spending most of your time downtown. It\''s a short walk from tourist-friendly Second Avenue to famed Printers\'' Alley and all parts in between.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
