 (1459,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">New Orleanians love to throw a good party - keep in mind this is a city that dances in the street after a funeral. So don\''t fret if you miss the big money draws Mardi Gras and Jazz Fest. There are still plenty of festivals to go around, including Southern Decadence with the ultimate drag parade down Royal Street; the French Quarter Festival in April that attracts local and international bands as well as some of Jazz Fest\''s favorite food vendors; and the Creole Tomato Festival, a smaller affair, but just as delicious.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music & Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A ton of musical history and a citywide penchant for \"shakin\'' it\" make New Orleans ground zero for catching great music all year long. While Bourbon Street is the undisputed heart of New Orleans\'' live music and nightlife realms, if you go local and hit clubs outside the French Quarter you\''ll find yourself rarely paying more than a USD5 cover charge with standard bar prices. Frenchman\''s Street and Decatur Street also boast a wealth of more authentically local establishments, while the Warehouse District is where you\''ll find the city\''s trendiest clubs.New Orleans is most famous for jazz. This is where this musical genre was born, and the natives haven\''t forgotten it. You can capture the various evolutionary forms of this African-European musical merger throughout the city. Fans of Dixieland should stick with the Quarter\''s top venues: Fritzel\''s and Preservation Hall - understandably touristy, but undeniably soul satisfying. Modern Jazz buffs will enjoy the omnipresence of Ellis Marsalis, father of Wynton and Branford, as he appears in various combos at Snug Harbor on Frenchmen Street. The next most popular New Orleans musical requests? Cajun and Zydeco -additional examples of the melding of European and African stylings. Both genres fall under the \"unapologetic dance\" heading and draw on their strong regional country roots with accordions, washboards and smatterings of French lyrics. Tipitina\''s Uptown hosts a Fais-Do-Do every Sunday night featuring the traditional selections of Bruce Daigrepont. The sessions serve as a weekly reunion of Cajun aficionados from around the city, but beginners are welcomed wholeheartedly as well. At Mid-City Lanes Rock and Bowl, the pine floor boards creak as Zydeco bands play to enthusiastic throngs every Thursday night. Finally, check out Mulate\''s on Julia Street, a great place to brush up on your waltz and get some good grub. Speaking of dancing, international enthusiasts can get their tango/reggae/salsa groove on at Mimi\''s in the Marigny on Wednesday nights and the Loft 523 on Tuesdays. As for funk, check out live performances by former Meters man George Porter Jr. and Walter \"Wolfman\" Washington at the Maple Leaf Bar on Oak Street Uptown or the French Quarter\''s House of Blues. It\''s back into the Quarter and the Blue Nile for bigger name out-of-town acts. Other nightlife attractions to be found in the area include karaoke at Cat\''s Meow on Bourbon Street, and bass bumping house and disco tunes at neighboring Bourbon Pub and Oz, two of the more integrated gay clubs in the city. Wind things down with a visit to Kerry Irish Pub on Decatur Street. This spot preserves the integrity of Irish pub culture: quiet conversation, respect for local musicians and relaxed service. Once you\''ve had your fill of New Orleans live music scene, nightclubs like the Warehouse District\''s Republic and Metropolitan, and The Beach on Bourbon are the best bets for fantastic DJ sets, swanky decor and a seemingly endless night of dancing.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums range from the nationally significant D-Day Museum and Confederate Museum to the more obscure Pharmacy Museum - a celebration of the 19th-century apothecary. Most political, sociological and architectural exhibitions of interest can be found in the French Quarter, home of the Louisiana State Museum and it\''s various branches, as well as the Historic New Orleans Collection and important historical residences. Art lovers will enjoy the huge collection of international art work and archaeological finds at the New Orleans Museum of Art (NOMA). A small showcase of African American art is viewable at the Villa Meilleur in the Faubourg Treme District and the McKenna Museum of African-American Art. There are several smaller contemporary art galleries as well, such as the Arthur Roger Gallery, the Contemporary Arts Center, Gallery Orange and Guthrie Contemporary.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Straddling the line between museum and art gallery, the Contemporary Art Center (CAC) is housed in a spectacularly renovated warehouse on Camp Street that offers two floors of touring artwork. The upper-level gallery usually features nationally acclaimed artists and the lower level gallery is a showcase for local artists working in the same medium is represented on the second floor. The CAC also stages a variety of art appreciation events, concerts, and cutting-edge theater productions. For more mainstream performing arts events the place to be is downtown. Theater lovers have a variety of options to choose from - contemporary performances by the Southern Rep; the Saenger Theatre on Rampart Street, host to national touring companies and A-list comedians; and the cozy Le Petit Theatre du Vieux Carre in the Quarter, where classics and Broadway musicals are performed by local acting vets. Ballet and opera lovers can view local and touring ensembles at the Mahalia Jackson Theatre Of Performing Arts in Louis Armstrong Park, while the Louisiana Philharmonic Orchestra plays various venues around the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">All manifestations of material goods are yours for purchasing. Try Magazine Street, lower Garden District to Uptown, for funky, used and questionably French items; Royal Street, for classic antiques; and the Central Business District\''s Canal Place and sprawling Riverwalk for fashion. Music buffs take note of the Louisiana Music Factory across from the House of Blues, as well as the GHB Jazz Foundation at the French Market, stocked with Dixieland, traditional and classic jazz recordings.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Casinos</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">It was only a matter of time before the ultimate addition was made to the Quarter\''s increasingly adult playground atmosphere. Located at the corner of St. Peter and Canal Streets, one of the newest links in the Harrah\''s Casino chain, the resort houses 100,000 square feet of slots and table games, dining and entertainment.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Children\''s Activities</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Audubon Zoo, at the rear of Audubon Park , and its sister site, the Aquarium of the Americas, at the Riverfront, are excellent family diversions. Both facilities are impressive showcases of creatures found regionally and across the world, including such rarities as white tigers and 450-pound sharks. The Aquarium of the Americas is also home to New Orleans\'' IMAX theater. Outdoor enthusiasts can choose between two gorgeous oak-filled parks: Audubon Uptown or New Orleans City Park in Mid-City, the nation\''s fifth largest urban park. Both public greens offer golf courses, play areas and horseback riding.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Natives of New Orleans are passionate about sports and support their teams with much enthusiasm at home games. The city boasts a long and illustrious sports history, a legacy that is carried forward to this day. The city plays host to a number of major sporting events each year, including NCAA college football and basketball playoffs, the Super Bowl, the Sugar Bowl, the Zurich Classic PGA Tour and horse racing at the Fair Grounds Race Course. The city\''s Superdome is also the home of the New Orleans Saints (NFL), while the Smoothie King Center hosts the New Orleans Pelicans (NBA).</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1460,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">French Quarter</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The French Quarter, or <em>Vieux Carre</em> in French, is the oldest neighborhood in New Orleans. It lies in a bend of the Mississippi River and consists of fairly narrow streets, reminiscent of European city planning, that reveal hidden courtyards overhung with wrought iron balconies. The architecture in the Quarter largely dates to the late 18th and early 19th Centuries, and draws on French and Spanish influences. In the daytime, the French Quarter, especially the area around Jackson Square, is filled with tourists, street performers, and the occasional conman. At night, the French Quarter transforms into the vibrant party scene. Barhopping college students, adventurous suburbanites, tourists, and others spill from the many bars that line Bourbon Streets with drinks in hand, their smiling faces lit by the neon glow of street signs.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lower Canal Street</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Once the main shopping district of New Orleans, lined with popular department stores and theaters, Canal Street lost much of its grandeur to a sluggish economy in the 1970s and 1980s. Today, Harrah\''s New Orleans and an expanded convention center have helped this part of Canal Street to develop into a ten block strip of hotels, souvenir shops and electronics stores. The Outlet Collection at Riverwalk, which is near the Aquarium of the Americas and the Ernest M. Morial Convention Center, also makes this a popular stop for tourists.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central Business District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The scattered, mismatched skyscrapers and superbly unusual Superdome of the Central Business District form the recognizable skyline of New Orleans. Several modern hotels, as well as older and established accommodations, are located in the heart of the CBD and the New Orleans\'' business community. Bustling during the day with local businesspeople, this area is quite subdued at night. Since the district empties each evening, many of the guests from the hotels in the neighborhood head for the Quarter.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Garden District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Garden District is New Orleans\'' premier residential neighborhood, intersected by the famed Saint Charles Avenue, lined with tremendous oak trees and home after home epitomizing the antebellum\''s Greek Revival style of architecture. Only a walking tour will do this dazzling district justice. If you visit the city, you must see the lush, overgrown gardens and grand mansions that dapple the streets of this neighborhood. The Garden District has many well-known residents, including Trent Reznor, Archie Manning, and Anne Rice.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Mid-City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mid-City usually goes unnoticed by the average tourist until Jazz Fest, when thousands of eager visitors, bedecked in shorts and tank tops, crowd onto the Esplanade bus to reach the New Orleans Fairgrounds. Quiet and verdant with trees, Mid-City attracts locals with its wide offering of moderately priced restaurants. Here, you will also find the New Orleans City Park, and the New Orleans Museum of Art. For tourists, Mid-City is home to impressive above-ground cemeteries, including Metairie Cemetery, Oddfellow\''s Rest, and St. Louis Cemetery #3.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Uptown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oak-lined streets, Victorian mansions, and college cafes are staples of New Orleans\'' thriving Uptown neighborhood. St. Charles Avenue and Pyrtania Street offer examples of Colonial Revival architecture. The neighborhood is also home to Tulane and Loyola Universities. In addition to the mansions and universities, many pleasant coffee shops, antique stores, and restaurants crowd the small spaces between the fantastic homes of New Orleans\'' upper class. Residents and visitors alike can be seen jogging the two miles through Uptown\''s gorgeous, Spanish moss-filled Audubon Park each morning.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Warehouse District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Having outgrown the once-appropriate title, this historic New Orleans\'' neighborhood is no longer frequented by blue-collar factory workers. Instead, it is now a vibrant arts district populated by the city\''s young professionals. Some of the best art galleries in the city sit alongside restaurants that offer excellent cuisine. In addition, locals and tourists crowd into the streets of the district during festivals such as Art for Art\''s Sake, when plenty of wine, cheese, gumbo, and art clutter the sidewalks and shops of the Warehouse District.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
