 (1489,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oakland is home to a good number of museums that focus on all sorts of topics. The most notable of these is the Oakland Museum of California, which explains all different aspects of Oakland and California\''s history, from early Native American inhabitants to Hollywood\''s Golden Age to modern day local artists. The museum also has an impressive and interactive Natural History gallery as well as its popular outdoor sculpture garden. The Oakland Aviation Museum, located at the Oakland International Airport features a collection of vintage aircrafts, as well as several other interesting exhibits. The Pardee Home Museum near Preservation Park, a sort of outdoor museum in itself, features an antique carriage house and tank house.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historic Landmarks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As Oakland has been around since before the Gold Rush, naturally it is home to many historic buildings and landmarks. Perhaps the greatest of these is the Dunsmuir House & Gardens, a 37 room mansion built on 50 acres in the Oakland Hills. The house, gardens and carriage house play host to numerous events throughout the year. Christmastime at the Dunsmuir is a spectacle not to be missed. In Old Oakland, Preservation Park is a collection of 16 Victorian houses from the late 19th and early 20th Centuries. Centered around a picturesque fountain circle and bandstand, the park shows what Oakland looked like 100 years ago. The Camron-Stanford House offers guided tours at Lake Merritt\''s only remaining historic building, the former home of some of Oakland\''s most wealthy residents in the late 19th Century. Slightly different from a preserved Victorian home is Heinold\''s First & Last Chance Saloon, a National Literary Landmark and a favorite haunt of Oakland author Jack London, Heinold\''s tilted bar still exhibits damage left over from the great earthquake of 1906. The most modern of Oakland\''s architectural landmarks can be seen from most parts of the city, the Oakland California Temple in the Oakland Hills is the main worshiping place of Oakland\''s Mormon population, and the decoration around the holidays illuminates the whole hillside with incredible lights and nativity scenes.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Kids & Family Fun</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oakland has lots to do to entertain the children, along with the whole family. The main kids attraction in Oakland is Children\''s Fairyland, the first child-oriented theme park in the United States, which even provided Walt Disney with some of the inspiration for Disneyland. Fairyland has small rides, animals, play structures and puppet shows, among other fun features. Another family favorite with animals and rides is the Oakland Zoo. Home to all kinds of animals, from elephants to river otters and baboons, as well as a train ride and a sky ride, the Oakland Zoo is a great spot for birthday parties or just a fun day out with the family. Another fun and educational family spot in the Oakland Hills is the Chabot Space & Science Center, which features a number of large public telescopes, a planetarium and more that the kids will love. In the summers you can head out to Alameda for the Sand Castle & Sand Sculpture Contest at Robert W. Crown Memorial State Beach in Alameda, where you can check out these extraordinary temporary creations.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema/Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oakland is full of all kinds of theaters, both new and old. Probably the most historic theater in the city is the magnificent Paramount Theater, which has been around since the 1930s and is home to the Oakland East Bay Symphony and the Oakland Ballet, as well as hosting special events and concerts, and showing old movies, complete with intermissions on occasion. Oakland\''s other historic live performance theater is the Fox, renovated in the beginning of the 21st Century to its original Art Deco splendor, which hosts concerts and comedians all year round. Oakland\''s most beloved (and historic) movie theater is the Grand Lake Theater, which shows all the latest hits, and features the \"Mighty Wurlitzer Organ\" performances before movies start on Friday nights, along with a raffle. Aside from these historic theaters is the more discreet Piedmont Theatre, which often screens foreign and independent films, and the modern nine screen Regal Jack London Stadium 9.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoors</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Despite being the eighth largest city in California, Oakland has an abundance of outdoor parks and recreation areas to make you forget you\''re surrounded by urbanity. Right in the middle of the city, you can rent a boat at the Lake Merritt Boating Center and drift around this 155 acre landmark, taking in the necklace of lights, or hire a gondolier to tour you around the lake. Merritt isn\''t the only lake in the city, however. You can also visit Lake Temescal for some swimming or fishing for catfish and rainbow trout, or Lake Chabot just a few miles outside the city in Castro Valley, where you can also fish, swim, and boat, or just hang out and relax by the water. You can visit Oakland\''s very own volcanic remains at the Sibley Volcanic Regional Preserve, where you can climb the Round Top peak, comprised of millions of year old volcanic debris, or simply hike or ride a horse on one of the numerous trails that run throughout the park. Another favorite Oakland park is Redwood Regional Park in the Oakland Hills, where you can stroll through the California Redwood trees, go swimming at the pool or barbecue in the Roberts Recreation Area. Also in the hills is Huckleberry Botanic Preserve, where you can meander around looking at native coastal California plants and flowers. If hiking trails and hills aren\''t your cup of tea, you should head over to Alameda and Crown Beach where you can relax on the beach with views of San Francisco.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1490,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown/City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Oakland has undergone a sort of revitalization in past years, and is now a thriving and desirable business and cultural center for not only the city, but the whole Bay Area. Oakland\''s downtown encompasses a good amount of historical interest too, with Old Oakland (between Broadway, Clay, Seventh and 10th streets), which features Victorian buildings dating back to the 19th Century, Preservation Park.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Uptown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Uptown Oakland is one of the city\''s most active neighborhoods. Uptown has one of the largest concentrations of trendy restaurants, bars and art galleries in the city, and has since Oakland started really revitalizing in the early 2000s. The area is home to many popular entertainment venues as well, like the historic Paramount and Fox Theaters and the New Parkway Theater. Some of the popular eateries and watering holes include Flora, Luka\''s Taproom and Dogwood. Uptown is also the site of Oakland\''s flourishing Arts District, which is home to numerous galleries like the Johansson Projects and Mercury 20, and is also the site of Oakland\''s monthly First Friday festival, which takes place (as the name implies) on the first Friday of every month.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jack London Square</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the most popular attractions in Oakland, Jack London Square, is located along the waterfront, at the end of Broadway. Named after the famed <em>Call of the Wild</em> author Jack London, the charming waterfront promenade is home to the cabin in which the author lived during his time in Alaska (now relocated, of course), which sightseers can now visit and toss a coin in for luck. Right next door, you can visit the oldest bar in Oakland, where Jack London himself used to spend time, Heinold\''s First and Last Chance Saloon. A beautiful shopping and nightlife district with views of the bay and Alameda Island, Jack London Square offers a host of entertainment, shopping and dining opportunities, most notably the well-known Yoshi\''s restaurant and jazz club. Jack London Square is also the home to several modern loft buildings as well as Oakland\''s Amtrak train station and ferry terminal.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Chinatown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oakland\''s Chinatown is one of the oldest and most authentic Chinatowns in the United States, dating back to the mid-19th Century. Located right next to downtown, the borders of Chinatown run from 12th Street in the north, to Oak Street to the east, I-880 in the south and the entrance to the Webster Tube (to Alameda). Chinatown includes a more residential section as well as a bustling commercial section, which centers mainly around the Pacific Renaissance Plaza at 10th and Webster Streets, and includes almost every kind of shop imaginable, as well as some incredible food at places like Golden Lotus and Shan Dong. Although called Chinatown, the area is actually an incredibly diverse Pan-Asian community, with residents hailing from everywhere from Japan and Korea to Vietnam and Cambodia.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lake Merritt</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Lake Merritt was originally the United States\'' first wildlife refuge, and today is an Oakland landmark, around which many bustling smaller areas are centered. The Lake Merritt neighborhood includes Grand Avenue, best known for the historic Grand Lake Theater with its Mighty Wurlitzer Organ and unabashed political marquee statements, as well as Lakeshore Avenue, which is packed full of great restaurants and shopping, and Adams Point, a mostly residential area. The lake also serves as a popular walking or hiking route, totaling 3.5 miles around. The lake is also surrounded by various parks as well as Laney College, and the Oakland Museum of California. If you\''re with the young ones, check out Children\''s Fairyland, America\''s oldest fairy-tale theme park. And don\''t miss Lake Merritt at night, when you can see its necklace of lights reflecting on the water.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Piedmont Avenue</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Named after the neighboring city of Piedmont, which is somewhat of an island city completely surrounded by Oakland, Piedmont Avenue is a charming, slightly upscale dining and shopping district. Also home to the Oakland branch of Kaiser Permanente Hospital, the neighborhood is generally accepted as being bordered by Broadway, Oakland Avenue, the City of Piedmont and the Mountain View Cemetery. Piedmont Avenue is where you will find the famous (thanks to Pixar) Fenton\''s Creamery. Aside from eating, there is also an abundance of small boutique shops, as well as the Piedmont Theatre.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Rockridge/College Avenue</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Rockridge/College Avenue Shopping District has everything: cute shops, boutiques, markets and restaurants stretching for almost a mile from Alcatraz Street until College Avenue ends at The California College of Arts campus; homes run west towards the freeway and east into the hills. Cute without being cloying, bustling Rockridge is a vital and in-demand neighborhood with one of the most bustling commercial districts in the East Bay.  Food is king in Rockridge: The European-influenced Rockridge Market Hall is a labyrinth of stalls selling exquisite stuffed pastas, olive oil, imported cheese, fresh-baked bread, teas, coffees, fish, wine, meat, beautiful produce, and flowers. La Farine is another longtime Rockridge bakery with an ardent following. Oliveto Cafe & Restaurant, Zachary\''s Chicago Pizza and other Rockridge restaurants have left their mark on the Bay Area\''s culinary map as well. Shopping is another Rockridge specialty. Visit Diesel for books and various literary events while Maison d\''etre stocks elegant yet accessible home goods.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Temescal</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">What was once a rather run-down, unexciting area, has been transformed into the ever growing and popular Temescal district. Now known as Oakland\''s Gourmet Ghetto, up and coming chefs and brewers flock to this area around Telegraph Avenue and 51st Street to set up shop. Innovative restaurants like Pizzaiolo and Doña Tomas mingle with beloved Temescal bites like Bakesale Betty and craft beer tap rooms and breweries to create a vibrant neighborhood which is home to hipsters, and yuppies alike.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Montclair</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Montclair District, which encompasses both residential areas as well as the central Montclair Business District, also known as Montclair Village, is situated at the base of the Oakland Hills and up, and is bordered by Highways 24 and 13, Skyline Boulevard and Joaquin Miller Road. Besides being a nice, compact and walkable area to stroll or shop in, Montclair also features Montclair Park, complete with a large pond home to numerous ducks, as well as several unique play structures for the kids. Situated right next to the park is the historic firehouse designed by famed Bay Area architect Julia Morgan, in the Hansel and Gretel style. In fact, Montclair is home to many fairy-tale inspired buildings, which can be seen all over in the village, as well as farther up into the hills. Montclair is also home to many boutique stores and great restaurants.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Oakland Hills/Mills</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mostly residential, the hills of Oakland over to the area around Mills College (a historic all woman\''s college which dates back to the founding of Oakland), boast incredible views of the San Francisco Bay and city at all hours of the day and night. However, despite its mostly residential status, the Hills are home to several not-to-miss attractions such as the Oakland Zoo, the Dunsmuir House & Gardens and the Chabot Space & Science Center, among others.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Airport</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The flatlands around the Oakland International Airport are home to various travel-convenient hotels, as well as the Oracle Arena & Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum, home to the Oakland Athletics baseball team, Oakland Raiders NFL team, and the Golden State Warriors basketball team. And while this area is not as attraction packed as other areas of the city, it does contain a fairly large concentration of accommodations convenient to the airport, and catching an Oakland sporting event is an exciting experience you won\''t easily find elsewhere.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
