 (1574,'A close-up view of the Liberty Bell, a symbol of liberty and justice in America.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1575,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the world\''s best collections of Impressionist paintings is the Barnes Foundation, in the suburb of Merion. All of the pieces here are instantly recognizable from reproductions, but only a small number have ever traveled, and then only recently. The Philadelphia Museum of Art and its small companion, the Rodin Museum, represent a brief history of world art on the Ben Franklin Parkway: Ancient Egypt, Impressionism, Expressionism, Cubism and Post-Modernism comes with guided tours and souvenir reproductions available in the gift shop. The Penn Museum has an excellent collection of archaeological and anthropological artifacts including a massive Egyptian sphinx, while the National Liberty Museum offers an inspiring look at those who have shaped the history of nations.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historical Sites</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Because of the city\''s rich history, there are plenty of historic sites that are innovative in the way they educate and entertain at the same time. One of the most famous Philly landmarks is the Liberty Bell, the bell from the Pennsylvania Statehouse commissioned by William Penn in 1751. Another key piece of American history found in this fair city is Independence Hall, the birthplace of the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution. For some literary history, the Edgar Allan Poe House, where the famous poet penned \"The Fall of the House of Usher\" and \"The Tell-Tale Heart,\" among other masterpieces. Another famous residence, Franklin Court, was once the home of Benjamin Franklin, and now houses seven different museums chronicling different aspects of this historic American\''s life and contributions to the world.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Every possible sound is available in Philadelphia on Wednesday through Saturday nights. On other nights, the choices are narrower, but if you look carefully there\''s always something going on. Philadelphia has always been a popular stop for national acts. There are concert halls that range from the massive stadiums of the Susquehanna Bank Center to the comfortably mid-size Trocadero, Tower, Electric Factory or Keswick, right down to the overheated and cramped rooms of the legendary bars where everyone from Bruce Springsteen to the Roots paid their dues. There is a string of clubs along Delaware Avenue on piers jutting into the Delaware River and more around South Street. It is possible to find a string quartet, opera or symphony performance every night of the week. With the Curtis Institute and the various college programs, the quality of street performers brightens the parks and sidewalks in the spring. The Philadelphia Orchestra is legendary for conductors like Leopold Stokowski, Eugene Ormandy, Ricardo Muti and Sir Simon Rattle.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater & Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For nearly a hundred years, Philadelphia was mainly known as a \"tryout\" town. New York producers would try out material here before opening on Broadway. These days it\''s more likely a play will originate here. The Walnut Street Theatre has produced the American premieres of two Tom Stoppard plays that were hits on London\''s West End, but have never played New York. InterAct Theatre Company hosts a new play reading every January which supplies work to regional theaters across the country. Keep an eye out for anything by Brat Productions, a young edgy company that often stages strong works in a bar. The first ten days of September, the Philadelphia Fringe Festival takes over the Old City district with a mix of local acts and visiting troupes from the Edinburgh, Toronto and New York. There are still national touring companies that perform big Broadway musicals at the Forrest, maintaining a healthy balance of new and recognized work. From the Pennsylvania Ballet to The Philadelphia Dance Company (known as Philadanco), the dance performance scene here is low profile, but substantial. The city often acts as a lab for companies that are seen and celebrated in New York or Washington. Once again, because of the numerous collegiate dance programs, there are always visiting professional and resident performers to see.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Children</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Philadelphia pays particular attention to its younger visitors. The National Park Service provides tours and multimedia, interactive, educational displays at Independence Hall. At the Please Touch Museum, children are encouraged to put their mitts on everything and the entire museum is scaled to kids. There are similar setups in the Academy of Natural Sciences and the Franklin Institute. Don\''t forget the popular petting pen at the Philadelphia Zoo. Many of the larger chain bookstores around town have Saturday programs for children with readings and performances. The Free Library often has scheduled activities, including readings, films and performers. Then there are the children\''s theater programs at the Arden and Annenberg. To make your travels more convenient, children under the age of 12 years ride for free on SEPTA\''s buses and subways on Saturdays.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">From hipster hangouts in the University District to jazz in the Northern Liberties, Philadelphia\''s after-dark scene is diverse. Beer has a special place in Philly\''s heart and the sheer number of microbreweries and beer pubs will attest to that love. Among the many many choices, a few stand out as exceptional.These include seasonal beer gardens as well as year-round spots like The Abbaye and Monk\''s Cafe. Happy hours can be had at upscale Barclay Prime while the craft cocktails at The Franklin Bar will leave you savoring every sip.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">From indie shops and home-grown labels to national and international retailers and some of the largest malls in the country within easy access, Philly is a shopper\''s haven. Two must-sees are the King of Prussia Mall, outside the city center and the historic Reading Terminal Market. Stroll down Rittenhouse Row and check out the trendy boutiques and luxury labels or hit Midtown Village for local shopping in a lively atmosphere. Thanks to the college crowd, University City is teeming with plenty of high street labels and brand-name stores. If you\''re on the hunt for bling, you\''ll find it on Jeweler\''s Row. Other hotspots include Northern Liberties for its vintage and independent stores, East Passyunk for the Italian Market, the Old City for fashion-forward buys, and South Street for a bit of everything!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports fans will find much to be enthused about in this city. Home ground of major teams like the Philadelphia Eagles, The Philadelphia 76ers, and the Philadelphia Phillies. All major league sports are represented in Philly and you\''ll find pro teams battling it out in the South Philadelphia Sports Complex where major venues like the Lincoln Financial Field and Citizens Bank Park are located.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1576,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Society Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Start your visit to the neighborhood around Independence Hall. This is where the Liberty Bell rang out and where the Declaration of Independence, the United States Constitution, and the Bill of Rights were written and signed. Sit under a tree in the gardens and mail postcards home from Benjamin Franklin\''s Post Office (besides everything else, he was the first Postmaster General). This area is Society Hill, where you can tour Independence National Park, then do some shopping and have a cocktail at an intimate bar; then head up the block to a play, concert, or movie; discuss the show over a late dinner and head out again to hear live music, all within a few blocks.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Old City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">North of Market Street is Old City, which is Philadelphia\''s version of New York\''s Soho, with wonderful restaurants like Chlöe and Cuba Libre, small art galleries like Gallery Joe, and a growing number of theaters and performance spaces like Painted Bride; this is the fashionable young hip scene in all its shades. Much of the activity in this region is concentrated around 2nd Street. The three-decade-old Arden Theatre is located here and is a great place to catch a performance. End the evening with a drink and a bite to eat at the ever-popular Continental, an Old City staple.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Penn\''s Landing</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">East of the Old City, along the Delaware River, Penn\''s Landing is a backdrop for outdoor festivals and free summer concerts, as well as fireworks on holidays. You can also take a ferry across the river to the aquarium. In the summer, open-air clubs north of the Ben Franklin Bridge (such as Dave and Busters or the River Deck) take advantage of the breathtaking view.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Chinatown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">West of Old City, between 8th and 13th Streets, is Chinatown. These days Chinatown is about half Chinese and half a combination of Vietnamese, Thai, Japanese, Burmese and Pan-Asian, and rivals any Chinatown in the country. It\''s also home to the Pennsylvania Convention Center and the Reading Terminal Market. Start your exploration at the brightly hued Friendship Gate as you stroll around this eclectic neighborhood of interesting shops, Asian restaurants, and a plethora of cultural festivals.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Rittenhouse Square</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">On the west end of Center City is the fashionable Rittenhouse Square district, where you can buy great clothing and then wear it to dinner at the restaurant next door (possibly Monk\''s Cafe or Alma De Cuba). Lovers of the offbeat might venture into the Mütter Museum, a veritable cavalcade of creepy medical mysteries. For a bit of people-watching, there\''s no place better than the Ritterhouse Square Park, for which the district is named. It\''s here that you\''ll find people of all ages and walks of life enjoying the sunshine, lounging, playing with their pets or enjoying the many festivals that are hosted here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Avenue of the Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Broad Street, south of City Hall, is the Avenue of the Arts. The orchestra, the ballet and the Wilma, Gershman, and Prince theaters all reside here, interspersed with great restaurants and jazz clubs. Modeled on Parisian boulevards, the Ben Franklin Parkway presents a wonderful, tree-lined walk past Saints Peter and Paul Cathedral, several expensive hotels, the main Library and several museums. At the end of the Parkway, atop a hill, is the Philadelphia Museum of Art.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">South Philly and Bella Vista</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is where rich Italian history and new communities of Vietnamese and Thai are just the tips of the iceberg when it comes to great dining. Cantina El Caballito brings the spice, and the old Italian Market has got a little something for everyone. The main avenues of Ninth Street and Washington Avenue are a great place to experience Philadelphia\''s international flavor.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West Philly</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Across the Schuykill River in University City, the University of Pennsylvania and six other major schools are the centerpieces of a deep blend of students, immigrants and old neighborhoods. Take in some art at the Institute of Contemporary Art and then dine at the White Dog Cafe. Other highlights include the Penn Museum, a leading museum of archaeology and anthropology at the <span>University of Pennsylvania. Head on over to Distrito for Mexican small plates and potent margaritas in a lively space. </span>Powelton Village with its Victorian homes and leaf-lined avenues is a lovely retreat from the city center. This historic district is home to a creative set that\''s highlighted in institutions like the Philadanco dance company and the <span>Tiberino Museum.Spruce Hill extends from South Market Street to Woodland Avenue and this multicultural neighborhood is home to The Rotunda, a community arts space that has a variety of interesting exhibitions. The historical homes lend the neighborhood a distinct character.</span></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northern Liberties</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">North of Old City, this is the \"new frontier\" of the hip scene. Once an industrial and manufacturing district, Northern Liberties has gone the way of many similar neighborhoods, witnessing something of a renaissance in the recent years. NoLib, as it\''s locally known, is a vibrant hub of stand-alone boutiques, bars, pubs and entertainment venues. The Standard Tap will take care of your eating-and-drinking needs, and Johnny Brenda\''s will keep you entertained into the wee hours with its packed concert calendar. For dancing, head for the Barbary. After that, Silk City Diner at 5th and Spring Garden is the place to go for a grilled cheese sandwich at 4a on a Sunday morning or the best <em>huevos rancheros</em> for breakfast.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
