 (1613,'<h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> Portland has a number of interesting museums, from fine art to historic buildings to the truly unique. See the works of master artists Andrew Wyeth, Monet and Picasso at the Portland Museum of Art, the oldest public art institution in the country. History and poetry buffs will love a visit to the Wadsworth-Longfellow House, the childhood home of the famous poet. And for something a little different, learn about Bigfoot at the International Cryptozoology Museum. Portland is also home to many local galleries, like Greenhut Galleries, which has been around since the 1970s.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> With a lively arts scene, Portland has a good selection of places you can usually find a show to see. The historic State Theatre hosts big name and local musical acts almost every night, while the Port City Music Hall provides a more intimate venue for concerts. At the Lyric Music Theater, you can catch a musical presented by an all-volunteer cast and crew. If drama is more your speed. Portland Stage puts on a thoughtful repertoire throughout the year.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">Outdoors</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> No matter what season, there\''s always great outdoor activities around Portland to get you out in the fresh air. The city has a great system of bike paths and scenic trails for those looking to explore on two wheels. Since Portland sits right on the water, it\''s no wonder that water sports like kayaking and paddleboarding are popular during the warm summer months. There are many companies who rent out boats and boards, like Portland Paddle. In winter, head to Smiling Hill Farm for snowshoeing or Gilsland Farm Audubon Center for cross-country skiing.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1614,'<h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> Old Port District</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">  The Old Port is a historic district that is to the south and southeast portion of the Portland Peninsula. It is generally considered to be half of Portland\''s downtown area, along with the Arts District. The area is well known for its quaint cobblestone streets lined with boutiques, galleries and restaurants. Visit Old Port and grab a meal at Central Provisions, shop for souvenirs at the Blue Lobster, or take a walk down to the waterfront for some sea air.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> Arts District</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">  Located mostly around the upper section of Congress Street, the Arts District is home to some of the city\''s best cultural attractions. Visit the free Portland Museum of Art, or if you\''ve got kids, the Children\''s Museum of Maine with its fun, interactive exhibits. The district is also where you\''ll find the historic State Theatre as well as many art galleries. The Arts District hosts a First Friday Art Walk, in which many of the local businesses host open houses where visitors can see what is going on in Portland\''s arts community.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> West End</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">  As the name implies, the West End is located on the western portion of the peninsula. The West End is best known for its historical interest. This area has been referred to as \"one of the best preserved Victorian neighborhoods in the country\", due to the large number of historic homes and buildings in the area. The West End is also home to the Western Promenade, a park which dates back to the mid-19th Century.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> Munjoy Hill</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">  On the eastern end of the peninsula is the neighborhood of Munjoy Hill, which contains the hill itself. While mostly residential, this area is home to a few landmarks, including the lighthouse-like Portland Observatory. Another prominent feature of Muntjoy Hill is the Eastern Promenade, a park with incredible views of the water and Portland Head Light.</div><h3 class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\"> Peaks Island</h3><div class=\\\"WorldGuide\\\">  Just three miles into Casco Bay is Peaks Island, accessibly by ferry. While fairly small, the island is a popular destination for visitors who want to visit one of Maine\''s many scenic islands. Visitors to the island love browsing for local honey or art in one of the islands cute shops or galleries. There are also a couple of museums on the island, including the quirky Umbrella Cover Museum. While you\''re on island grab a lobster roll at Peaks Island House with a view of the bay.</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1615,'Country|United States of America|Population|66,818|Elevation|62 feet / 18.9 meters',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1616,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Portland is an eclectic city, where sophisticated and alternative styles coexist peacefully. It is known for its friendliness, rich culture and variety of outdoor pursuits. A temperate climate, thriving economy and close proximity to both the Pacific Ocean and the Cascade Mountains are among the many reasons Portland has garnered high rankings on multiple \"Most Livable City\" lists.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
