 (1699,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With Haskolabio and Laugarasbio, there is no dearth of onscreen entertainment in Reykjavik. The former is located in a university campus and is packed always with students. Hollywood blockbusters rule here with a sprinkling of European cinema thrown in for the avid movie fan. All the venues boast state-of-the-art sound systems and comfortable seating arrangements. At the Red Rock Cinema, film shows on volcanoes are held on all 365 days of the year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A visit to the National Museum of Iceland gives visitors a thorough chronicle of the history of Iceland, right from the medieval to modern times. But for a taste of the real Iceland, step into the farm fresh environs of the Arbaer Museum. This open air museum houses homes built in the 1800s. Moreover, visitors can admire the traditional Icelandic costumes worn by the staff. More than 1.5 million photographs, negatives and prints are a part of the Reykjavík Museum of Photography and photographic exhibitions of local as well as international shutterbugs are organized in this creative space. The Aurora Reykjavik center hosts a multimedia show that celebrates the magic of the Northern Lights and is a must-see while visiting the city.For a peek at retro Icelandic and international art the National Gallery of Iceland is a top choice, but for those in a funky mood the Kling & Bang Gallery will inject visitors with sass and spunk. The Gallerí Lana Matusa Art Ceramic Studio exhibits traditional Icelandic ceramic art. The authentic lava artifacts of elves and trolls tell a different story altogether.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Icelandic Symphony Orchestra is an outstanding institution that brings classical music to life. Apart from the arias and Mozart interludes, visitors may tune into to lilting melodies of classic Icelandic sagas. This symphony travels extensively with a rich repertoire and has shared the stage with the likes of Luciano Pavarotti, Yehudi Menuhin and André Previn. The Icelandic Opera shows off with musical interpretations of Mozart\''s <em>The Marriage of Figaro</em>, the Humperdinck classic <em>Hansel and Gretel,</em> Puccini\''s <em>Carmen, </em>and many more. Some of the city\''s best performances and most illustrious guests grace the state-of-the-art Harpa Reykjavik Concert Hall and Conference Centre with their presence, while the National Theatre of Iceland hosts an eclectic line up of concerts, plays and live performances through the year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Anybody and everybody will point towards the Icelandic Dance Company for those who want to get rid of their two left feet. Folk Icelandic dances and jazz ballet are the mainstays of this organization. It is the most respected of all the dance institutions in Iceland and offers children\''s dance programs too. Tap, spin, swirl or whirl, it\''s your choice!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightclubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Like every city, Reykjavik throbs with its very own bohemian brand of nocturnal life. Hip hop, rock, house and lounge music all dwell together at the city\''s energetic venues, concentrated around the vibrant shopping street, Laugavegur and its surrounding streets -Bankastræti and Austurstræti. To be dressed to kill is the mantra as the night lives on. Top choices include Kaffibarinn, a favorite with musicians; Húrra for live music and some of the city\''s best electro music; and Club Kiki, the city\''s top gay bar. For those who like to dance till they drop, no one sets the mood than Pablo Discobar, a hot favorite on the party scene.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Coffee Culture</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Need a good break from the hectic partying? Then head to the several coffee houses in the city to drink or just inhale the intoxicating \''kaffi\''. At Laugarbakkar the caffeine is contagious and so are the lively musical performances. For coffee more easy on your wallet, it\''s Kofi Tomasar Fraenda. This venue attracts the hip teen crowd but you could squeeze yourself in.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1700,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">City Center and Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Reykjavik\''s city center is where the action is. The downtown area is host to a large number of attractions concentrated in a small area, making it easy to explore in a short time. These include The Settlement Exhibition that throws light on the city\''s Viking origins, as well as the National Museum, replete with a vast number of national treasures from the settlement to modern times. Other landmarks worth mentioning are the eye-catching Hallgrimskirkja, Iceland\''s largest church and a monument that has captured the imagination of visitors for years.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Hlemmur</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The city\''s main shopping street, Laugavegur translates as \"Wash Road,\" that hearkens to its past as a major thoroughfare for people traveling to the hot springs and is found in the vibrant Hlemmur neighborhood. This is where the city\''s trendiest boutiques, niche stores, design inspirations, and hip bars can be found. Among the myriad shops found here, a few like Spúútnik, Myconceptstore, and Systur & Makur are have earned iconic status.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Old Harbour</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A short distance from the city center, the picturesque Old Harbor has a number of interesting attractions like the Saga Museum, Whales of Iceland Exhibit and the Solfar Sun Voyager sculpture.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Laugardalur</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For outdoor recreation and sports, few places beat Laugardalur, a beautiful district located in the east of the city center. Visitors can dive into the outdoor thermal pool, appreciate the variety of Icelandic flora at the Botanical Gardens, or spend a day with the animals at the Family Park and Zoo. Sports enthusiasts should head to Laugardalur Arena, the city\''s largest sporting venue that hosts international and national games. The Laugardalsholl, an indoor stadium that hosts everything from concerts to chess tournaments is located here as well. Every year music enthusiasts flock to Laugardalur for the spectacular Secret Solstice Festival that\''s held here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Greater Capital Region</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Including Reykjavik, the Greater Capital region is made up of six distinct districts. These include Kopavogur, Hafnarfjörður, Garðabær, Mosfellsbær and Seltjarnarnes. Kópavogur is a mini city that gets attention because of its active nightlife. Second to Reykjavik in population, Kópavogur is a nouveau-riche city, bustling with shopping arcades, art performances, restaurants, pubs, and other places of business and enjoyment. Its sports facilities are considered the best in the country.Garðabær is the sixth-largest town in Iceland. Considered different from other municipalities because of its housing projects, Garðabær is fast becoming an urban hangout for most of the young people that live here. Among the highlights are the countless music concerts and an annual jazz festival that draw crowds from all of Scandinavia. <span><p style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt\" dir=\"ltr\">Hafnarfjörður is a major town on the outskirts Reykjavik, it is the next best place to be in Iceland after the capital city. Its cafes, tourist agencies, restaurants, and accommodation are quickly earning Hafnarfjörður a prominent place on the map.</span>Mosfellsbær is nature\''s bounty within the Greater Reykjavik area. It\''s a great place for hiking, mountain biking and other recreational sports. Horseback tours and golf at Hlíðavollur and Bakkakotsvollur are major attractions here.Seltjarnarnes is a residential area is well known for its migratory birds. During high tide Seltjarnarnes gets separated from the mainland. The late summer sunset is one of the most spectacular sights in the world. The only astronomers\'' club in Iceland is situated here.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,