 (1723,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Rotterdam, a dynamic city in the province of South Holland, is home to the world\''s second largest harbor. The harbor, which stretches for 23 miles (37 kilometers) along both banks of the Nieuwe Maas River between Rotterdam and the Hook of Holland, is an unbelievable sight. As an international gateway, all shipped goods destined for cities all over Europe pass first through Rotterdam. Rotterdam\''s harbor is modern and efficient - the pride of the Netherlands and carefully controlled by the Douane, the official customs of Holland. The city is basically divided into five sections: north, south, east, west and center. Of course Rotterdam takes in more than just the city itself; the Europoort extends to the outlying suburbs of Spijkenisse, Capelle aan den IJssel and a number of other residential areas along the way.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
