 (1729,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Ahoy is not the only large concert center in Rotterdam. Right in the heart of the city you\''ll find the enormous concert and congress center De Doelen, a world-class venue, which hosts numerous important functions and concerts year round.Rotterdam offers entertainment-seekers something to suit every taste. Rotterdam boasts the world\''s largest harbor. Not surprisingly, much of Rotterdam\''s entertainment is centered around this. During the summer months, the river is used as a stage for major concerts, and entertainers like Lionel Richie and Andrea Boccelli have graced the harborfront in the past. See the world-class Philharmonic Orchestra when they play at the river concerts, among a number of other venues around the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Rotterdam also hosts a number of European and world film festivals each year, such as the International Film Festival Rotterdam and the Architectuur Film Festival Rotterdam. These festivals attract both local film buffs and aficionados from across the globe. Rotterdam has a number of cinemas such as Cinerama, Lantaren, and the huge Pathé multi-cinema complex. All of these cinemas are conveniently located right in the heart of the city, and you\''ll find an abundance of restaurants and cafés within their vicinity as well.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The neighboring city Capelle aan den IJssel boasts the wonderful theater The Isala, which has been popular with theatergoers since opening its doors to the public over a decade ago. The ro Theater, one of the major Dutch theater companies in the country, performs regularly at its namesake venue on William Boothlaan, as well as at the Rotterdamse Schouwburg. The Nieuwe Luxor Theater and the Oude Luxor Theater host myriad performances throughout the year that range from concerts and theater, to dance and opera. The Theater Zuidplein, also one of the city\''s hallmark theaters, boasts of a rich theatrical program.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The museums of Rotterdam are often overshadowed by the famous museums of Amsterdam. However, if you take some time to explore, you\''ll find yourself pleasantly surprised.The pride of Rotterdam is the architecturally famous Boymans Beuningen Museum of Art. This is the perfect place to start a museum tour of Rotterdam. Here, the artwork of Holland\''s famous artists abounds. The World Museum on the riverbank nearby the Euromast recently reopened after undergoing major renovations. There are many other museums in Rotterdam, both large and small, historical and modern. Some like the Kunsthal, the Kijk-Kubus, the Nederlands Fotomuseum, and the Natuurhistorisch Museum Rotterdam are  well worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Rotterdam\''s shopping typically centers around its downtown area, with a fine network of busy streets offering plenty of satisfying shopping experiences. Linjbaan, Hoogstraat and Meent - some of Rotterdam\''s main shopping avenues cannot be missed. The Market Hall in the heart of the city is its most thriving shopping destination. Outside the downtown area, malls like Winkelcentrum Zuidplein and Alexandrium keep you more than occupied with their offerings. If you\''re a book lover, don\''t miss the eternal charm of Donner Books that sits on Coolsingel.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1730,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Once almost totally destroyed by enemy invasion, Rotterdam is now a bustling, modern world city, and its city center boasts one of the country\''s tallest office blocks, which includes the 492-foot (149-meter) high Nationale Nederlanden insurance building, also known as the Delft Gate Building, and the magnificent elliptical-shaped Beurs-World Trade Centre. A shopping center of world standard, the World Trade Centre features the Koopgoot, famous upper class department stores such as De Bijenkorf, and accommodation second to none. Besides being a great place to shop and visit the local tourist attractions, the city center is also home to several luxury hotels, although there are also a number of budget style accommodations here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The north of Rotterdam is known as a green belt. A number of children\''s farms and green recreational areas such as the Kralingse Bos Forest and Plaswijck Park are located in this affluent neighborhood. Rotterdam north (suburb of Overschie) is the location for Rotterdam\''s very busy European airport,</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Zestienhoven. Located just minutes from the city, the airport is very popular with business people and tourists.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">South</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">To the south of Rotterdam you\''ll find the famous De Kuip Stadium, home base for the international Feyenoord F.C. But football is not the only form of entertainment to be found in the south - you\''ll also find one of the country\''s largest entertainment venues, the Ahoy, where top name celebrities from all over the world, both in sporting and entertainment fields, strut their stuff for the Rotterdam public. Opposite the Ahoy is Zuidplein, one of Holland\''s largest shopping centers.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">East</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The east of Rotterdam boasts another one of the country\''s enormous shopping centers: the Alexandrium. This enormous shopping center is divided into sections. This luxurious shopping center is the location for some of the best home furnishing stores the country has to offer. Other than this retail attraction, there isn\''t much to see around this area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In Rotterdam\''s western sector you\''ll find Europoort and associated businesses and industries The west of Rotterdam is abuzz with industrial activity 24 hours a day.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Capelle aan den IJssel</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Bordering Rotterdam is the small town of Capelle aan den IJssel. Capelle, which lies on the banks of the IJssel River, has a very attractive traditional Dutch center as well as some wonderful new residential and shopping areas. Winkelcentrum De Koperwiek shopping center, in the heart of Capelle, is a modern well-equipped shopping precinct. Now the center also offers the Isala Theatre, which opened in 1999 and has presented a host of famous Dutch personalities and productions to the people of Capelle. On Thursdays Capelle\''s city market opens its stalls in the market square just behind De Koperwiek.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Other Areas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">To see harbor workings with a little more \''old Dutch\'' feel to them you must visit Dordrecht, just south of Rotterdam. Here the old warehouses (most now family homes) and barge-lined canals still exist today. The Dordrecht Museum, formerly an old mental asylum, now houses a wonderful collection of works by famed Dordrecht artists such as Albert Cuyp, Nicholas Maes and Ferdinand Bol. Many of the magnificent works of art give the visitor to the museum an insight into Dordrecht as it was in the 17th Century. Rotterdam is surrounded by lush, green countryside where the most fascinating little towns such as Schoonhoven (the famous Silver City of Holland), Delft (famous for its Delft Blue pottery) and Brielle (the ancient walled city), can all be found within a half hour\''s train ride from Rotterdam.About 16 miles (25 kilometers) from Rotterdam lies the incredibly beautiful historical city of Gouda. The city exudes the very essence of true Dutch spirit and architectural ingenuity. Presiding over the city center is the magnificent town hall, a majestic building that is reminiscent of a fairytale castle. The shuttered windows add the finishing touch to this unbelievably pretty building. Just behind the market square is the beautiful Gothic style St. Janskerk. This elongated church, rebuilt after it was all but wiped out by fire in 1552, is famous for its magnificent stained glass windows. To prevent air-raid damage or theft the windows were removed and stored safely for the duration of World War II. St. Jan\''s Church is the longest church in Holland.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
