 (1746,'Blue skies over the city\''s skyline and snow-capped Wasatch Mountains.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1747,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts and Movie Theaters</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Looking for live entertainment? Consider the Capitol Theatre, home to the Utah Opera Company and Ballet West. Capitol Theatre also hosts traveling Broadway shows. Kingsbury Hall, on the campus of the University of Utah, is also a good bet for live entertainment, concerts, traveling plays and student productions. The sprawling Rose Wagner Performing Arts Center, a complex comprising of three venue, hosts performances by the Ririe-Woodbury Dance Company, Plan-B Theatre Company, and the famous Sundance Film Festival. The downtown-based Eccles Theater is a prime hub for riveting Broadway shows and concerts, whereas the Sorenson Unity Center has an excellent program of community theater. Smaller venues like the Art Factory and DF Dance Studio host plenty of cultural entertainment as well.   If you prefer the two-dimensional screen to the live stage, stadium seating, wall-to-wall screens, digital surround sound, plush seating, hot popcorn and all the extras, then you are in luck. With theaters like Megaplex 17 at Jordan Commons and The Century 16, there is always a theater nearby. The independent film fan should plan on visiting Salt Lake in late January and early February for the world famous Sundance Film Festival, offering a chance to rub elbows with the Hollywood crowd. Else, head to gems like the Tower Theatre or the Broadway Centre Theatre in the city. For those who wish to be educated as well as entertained, the Clark Planetarium offers star shows presented in a dome shaped theater. At night the same theater entertains with a spirited shows like the 3D-laser light show synchronized to popular music.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While Salt Lake City is not predominantly known for its museums, the smattering of museums it is home to are some of the most highly-rated museums in the state. The Natural History Museum of Utah, located against the rugged backdrop of the mountains, blends beautifully into the scenery. Along with its visually striking appearance, it also features a staggering variety of natural history exhibits, while the landscape of the Intermountain West is also a special feature at the museum. The Church History Museum, located near Temple Square, chronicles the religious heritage of the centuries-old Latter Saints Day Church through a diverse range of artifacts and exhibits. Alluding to the city\''s historical past is the Pioneer Memorial Museum, a splendid manor consisting of rich memorabilia sourced from the city\''s pioneers. Others such as the Leonardo Museum, the Utah Museum of Contemporary Art, and Utah Museum of Fine Arts are not only fine repositories of a range of artistic periods, but also make for imposing architectural marvels. Smaller museums include Fort Douglas, the Beehive House, and the Chase Home Museum of Utah Folk Art.Besides Salt Lake\''s rich trove of art museums, its blossoming arts scene also features a few premier private art galleries. From the Hope Gallery on Main Street that boasts of a wonderful personal art collection, to the 15th Street Gallery\''s astonishing collection consisting of award-winning artists and their artworks, Salt Lake City has a broad art palette.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The biggest ticket in town is basketball, and for those who love the game, Salt Lake City has a double bonus. The Vivint Smart Home Arena in downtown is the home ground of the basketball\''s Utah Jazz team. Less than three miles east, the Huntsman Center is home to the University of Utah Utes. Smith\''s Ballpark is one of the most inviting baseball parks in the country, home to the Salt Lake Bees.   Salt Lake City is also lined from top to bottom with golf courses that are competitive and diverse. The surrounding natural beauty makes the courses works of art in their own right.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoors</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With nearly a dozen ski resorts within an hour of downtown, you are never far from the swish. If you want to stay near the city, try Alta Ski Area, Brighton Ski Resort, Snowbird Ski and Summer Resort or Solitude Mountain Resort. If a smaller town setting is what you desire, Park City lies minutes east of Salt Lake, nestled in a gorgeous mountain valley. Park City is home to world-class resorts such as the The Canyons, Deer Valley Resort, Park City Mountain Resort and Sundance Ski Area. Whether your interest lies in downhill, cross-country, night skiing, snowboarding, sledding, snowshoeing or any other snow sport, you will find it here. Even the greatest snow on earth is only here for six months a year. When you put the skis and sleds away, break out the hiking boots, picnic baskets and rock climbing gear. The numerous canyons that surround the Salt Lake valley are filled with hiking trails without number. There are five National Parks just a few hours south of Salt Lake. If you enjoy red rock vistas, enormous canyons, rock arches, bluffs, petrified sand dunes, towering plateaus or just plain breathtaking scenery, do not miss the national parks that lie beyond the city limits.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Water & Amusement Parks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are a few places to enjoy the water as well, although surfboards will have to be traded for floating tubes, the sand for mats and the beach for a water park. Seven Peaks Waterpark Salt Lake City has much to offer. Fifteen minutes north of downtown Salt Lake, perched on the foothills of the Wasatch Mountains, you will find Lagoon, Utah\''s only amusement park, and a thrill seeker\''s delight. It boasts several thrill-seeking opportunities including an old wooden roller screamer and Colossus, a high-speed coaster with a double loop. Other intense rides include \"The Rocket\" a 217-foot tower that pushes you to the top and then lets you free fall back to the ground.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">July 24th is a state holiday in Utah that celebrates Pioneer Day. The day is set aside to remember the first colonists that set their sights on the West. It is the day to remember the overwhelming feat of wrestling a desert valley atop the mountains into a prosperous city and state. The festivities officially begin in the morning with one of the largest parades in the country, and continue until nighttime when several locations offer Independence Day-style firework displays. Travelers to the state are welcome to join the celebration, although it is wise to make plans and reservations early as hotels fill up fast. Be warned that outer and inner-city travel is a mess the morning of the parade. Other prominent festivals include the world-renowned Sundance Film Festival, the Utah Arts Festival and the Craft Lake DIY Festival.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1748,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The downtown area is a mixture of contrasts with old and new buildings side by side. The stately Temple Square is flanked by high-rise office buildings. Brigham Young\''s Beehive House creates a 19th-century oasis across the street from office towers of the 21st century. Arranged on a logical grid pattern with Temple Square at its center, all addresses in the city can conveniently be found with little effort.  Business and tourism are the lifeblood of the city, but between the office buildings lay the cultural and entertainment centers that present numerous diversions at the end of the business or ski day. The Capitol Theatre, home of Ballet West, is both an architectural and cultural gem. One of downtown\''s classic older buildings, the theater has been renovated into a modern venue for Broadway productions and intimate concerts. It is only a pleasant stroll from any of the downtown hotels and is close to some of the city\''s finest restaurants. Equally accessible from anywhere in downtown is Abravanel Hall (home of the Utah Opera Company) and the Vivint Smart Home Arena. The volunteer hosts at the Salt Lake City Convention and Visitors\'' Bureau in the Salt Palace Convention Center can always recommend a variety of activities, favorite restaurants or sites to visit.  Capitol Hill in Salt Lake City is truly a hill! A walk from downtown up State Street to the Utah State Capitol Building offers a sampling of the grandeur of the homes of mining and financial barons. Several of these old residences provide a good sense of Salt Lake City as it was at the turn of the 19th century. The private homes on the hill also offer an eclectic blend of Victorian, Italianate and \"wealthy pioneer\" architectural styles. Just to the west of the Utah State Capitol is the Pioneer Memorial Museum, which also provides a sense of life in the \"Beehive State\" in its early days.  Central City, another significant downtown hub is dominated by Trolley Square, located not far away from the leafy locality surrounding Liberty Park. Once the home of the trolleys that were the transportation mainstay of Salt Lake City, the trolley barns of Trolley Square now enclose some of the best restaurants and shopping in the city. Including the local favorite Desert Edge Brewery at the Pub, the numerous dining establishments are each a pleasure. Shopping ranges from the eclectic to the stylish and from the mainstream to the uncommon. Trolley Square is an ideal setting for an afternoon of shopping or an evening of dinner, drinks and a movie. The Leonardo, an eminent art museum, and the Tracy Aviary, an eight-acre (3.23 hectare) attraction spread out over Liberty Park are also located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The University of Utah</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The university district and the university itself offer a number of delights. On the campus of the University of Utah are the Utah Museum of Natural History and the Utah Museum of Fine Arts. Kingsbury Hall is a concert and performance venue that is a special pleasure for jazz performances, dance productions and theater. The University\''s Huntsman Center hosts the sporting exhibitions of the University of Utah Utes, while the nearby Red Butte Gardens is a four-season experience that, once again, integrates the city with Utah\''s diverse natural environment.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sugar House</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Sugar House, one of the city\''s oldest neighborhoods finely balances the charm of its regional essence with the constant waves of urbane trends. Adding to this newfound urbanity is the vibrant student-life that surrounds Westminster College. A stunning neighborhood in appearance as it is in spirit, Sugar House\''s main attraction is the verdant eponymous park that is sprawled across the landscape, with the Wasatch Mountains in the backdrop. At its periphery is a lovely sprinkling of dining establishments, boutiques, art galleries and gastropubs to keep the young entertained.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">9th & 9th</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Located east of Liberty Park, the 9th and 9th neighborhood is a compact area that underwent a vibrant revival in the summer of 2007. Since then, it has flourished as an offbeat avenue in the city for avid shoppers, and also hosts an array of street murals, kinetic sculpture art displays and other sidewalk attractions. A number of trendy boutiques and coffee shops are spread out around the intersection of 900 East and 900 West.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outside the City</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Like many metropolitan areas, Salt Lake City has sprawled past its designated boundaries into numerous suburbs and outlying areas. North of the city center lie Farmington, Hill Air Force Base and Ogden, home to the Hill Aerospace Museum, Eccles Dinosaur Park and Lagoon Amusement Park. West of the city center is home to Salt Lake International Airport and much of the area\''s rapidly expanding industry. To the east of the city lies the magnificent Wasatch Front. These craggy peaks and bucolic valleys shelter Park City and world-renowned ski resorts such as Deer Valley Resort, Park City Mountain Resort and Snowbird Ski and Summer Resort.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
