 (1766,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theaters</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Salzburger Landestheater at the Makartplatz stages performances throughout the year, from opera and ballet to classic plays. Further performances are held at the theater\''s Kammerspiele and the Elisabethbühne, both of which tend to focus on modern and contemporary plays. The Felsenreitschule theater serves as a venue for the annual Salzburg Festival.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If it rains, you could use the weather as an excuse to visit world-class museums such as the Haus der Natur, a huge natural history museum, or the Carolino Augusteum, which concentrates on local history and culture. Modern art can be found at the Museum der Moderne, and photography lovers are advised to visit the pertaining Rupertinum. Adults and children alike will enjoy the city\''s colorful and interactive Toy Museum, which is housed on the premises of the Bürgerspital. Hangar 7 features a collection of interesting vehicles, from old airplanes to Formula 1 cars.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Salzburg is a city with a close connection to the world of classical music; the Salzburg Festival, held every summer, is world-famous. There are events throughout the year in the Great Festival Hall, and in autumn, there is the Salzburger Jazzherbst, when smooth jazz accompanies the changing weather. The Great Hall of the Altes Mozarteum is another big venue. If you would like to hear Mozart\''s music in his hometown, you could visit the Mozart Audio-Visual Collection for historic recordings of the master\''s work. The Rockhouse is the place to head for rock, pop and jazz concerts on an almost daily basis. If you are interested in jazz, don\''t miss the Jazzit, a venue where you can get in on the local jazz scene. If you like pub gigs, then go to the Shamrock Irish Pub, a popular Irish pub near the Staatsbrücke. Big-name concerts are staged at the Salzburgarena.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historic Attractions</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Salzburg is dripping with history, from making its mark on classical music to the mighty Austro-Hungarian Empire, there is no shortage of historic attractions to immerse yourself in. Don\''t miss out on a visit to Mozart\''s birth house, where you can see original furnishings and even the master\''s own violin! It\''s impossible to miss the Hohensalzburg Fortress towering over the city\''s Old Town as it is one of the largest in the country. Visitors can explore the ample halls, courtyards and chambers that make up this medieval castle. The opulent Mirabell Palace is located on the east side of the river. Classic film fans may recognize the palace\''s beautifully manicured gardens from <em>The Sound of Music</em>. Kids and kids at heart will love the trick fountains in Hellbrunn Palace\''s gardens.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1767,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Altstadt (Old Town)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In 1997, Salzburg\''s Altstadt (Old Town) was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in the category of cultural monuments worth preserving for future generations. This should speak for itself, and the Altstadt should be on every visitor\''s \"to-do\" list. Because the city center is not very big, you should be able to find your way around fairly easily. Classic Salzburg is a feast for the eyes, with impressive buildings dating back to the baroque period dominating the scenery. Different epochs can easily be distinguished from one another, with Italian baroque features standing side-by-side with examples of Austrian individualism. The Salzach River acts as a natural border to the Old Town, and the traffic-ridden Rudolfskai stretches out alongside it. Another natural feature that encloses the Old Town is the Mönchsberg, a big rock face that used to protect the city\''s treasures from unwanted guests during the Middle Ages.  Salzburg\''s cathedral is without a doubt the main attraction in the Altstadt. It is flanked by two squares, the Residenzplatz and the Kapitelplatz, both used for concerts and open-air events. The nearby Residenz, the Neue Residenz, the Franciscan Church and the Kollegienkirche are only a stone\''s throw away from each other. Towering above all these attractions is the Hohensalzburg Fortress on the Mönchsberg.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Getreidegasse</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In the western part of the Old Town, you can admire the Kollegienkirche, Mozart\''s birth house, the Festspielhäuser - and the former horse pond Pferdeschwemme. The Getreidegasse, one of the most expensive streets in Salzburg, is also situated here, with St. Blasius Church at its western end. The Getreidegasse has always been the Linzergasse\''s elegant counterpart, though the latter lies on the other side of the Salzach River. It is one of the main traffic routes linking the districts on the right of the river to the city; heading west, it is also one of the main roads for those traveling to Linz and Vienna. The area around the Mirabell Palace is pure Austrian charm. The elegant palace, which is situated on the northern side of the river, has a beautiful park, which is elegantly landscaped in the style of bygone centuries. The square in front of the palace is best known for its market, the Schrannenmarkt. Farmers from all over the province meet here once a week to sell their high-quality produce. The small stalls around St. Andrew\''s Church further ensure that the area has a lively feel about it.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North Side</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The area to the north of Salzburg is mainly residential and the buildings are more modernized the nearer you get to the main train station. The station itself is central to the city\''s infrastructure as the main means of connecting Salzburg to Austria\''s provincial regions, most of which can also be reached by bus.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Taxham</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A big US-style shopping mall is situated in the Taxham district and is called Europark, the city\''s large shopping-and-leisure center for a rainy afternoon. Nearby you find Red Bull Arena, Salzburg\''s soccer stadium, home of FC Red Bull Salzburg</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Aigen</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The district of Aigen, in the southern part of town, is known as a rather a well-to-do area. Living there could cost you a small fortune, as real estate prices tend to be extremely high.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
