 (1776,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"></h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Music lovers will revel in the variety of live music available almost every night of the week in San Antonio. From jazz and symphonic music to Tejano and rock \''n roll, music exudes from bars, restaurants and concert halls across the city. The San Antonio Symphony performance season includes both traditional scores and pops performances, often with vocal accompaniment by popular artists like James Taylor and Willie Nelson. At San Antonio\''s historic Aztec Theater, you can catch plenty of touring bands live, while the Gruene Hall offers the best live country music. From its name, Sam\''s Burger Joint may not seem like it is associated with live music, but its brilliant iconic status and exciting line-up of touring acts makes you think twice. Next to the River Walk, the Tobin Center for the Performing Arts has hosted a number of large-scale concerts in the past, and has staged past performances by artists like Paul McCartney and Meghan Trainor. The H-E-B Performance Hall, a concert hall within the center is the proud home of the San Antonio Symphony, the Opera, and the San Antonio Ballet. Other prominent music venues in the city include the John T. Floore Country Store, a celebrated honky-tonk, the historic Majestic Theatre, and the Cowboys Dancehall.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There are several theatrical venues whose productions run the gamut of genres. For national acts, The Broadway Bank Theatrical Series hosts numerous touring productions in the historic Majestic Theater. Past performances include <em>Grease</em>, <em>Chicago</em>, <em>Rent</em>, <em>Phantom of the Opera</em> and <em>Cabaret</em>. Outstanding local productions grace the stages at the Josephine Street Theater with recent performances including <em>Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat</em> and <em>Steel Magnolias</em>. To enjoy great local talent and dinner, check out the Harlequin Dinner Theater at Fort Sam Houston. Guadalupe Theater typically produces more avant-garde and cultural works.  Not to be left out, children can enjoy productions designed just for them at theaters such as the Magik Children\''s Theater.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Art</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Art of all genres and media abound at the many museums and galleries in San Antonio. From cutting-edge contemporary works to more traditional pieces, you will admire the depth of this city\''s talent pool. Be sure to visit the McNay Art Museum and the San Antonio Museum of Art to marvel at their impressive collections as well as the touring exhibits they host. As far as galleries go, some of the best include Blue Star Arts Complex and ArtPace. To catch the work of budding artists, visit Say Si, which displays student work in its gallery. Many restaurants and coffeehouses also display the works of local artists; pay a visit to Rosario\''s or WD Deli to enjoy the delicacies and the view. The Texas Transportation Museum and The Alamo are also must-visits.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As with any major city, San Antonio offers more movie theaters than you could count. While there\''s at least one in every part of town, a few that stand out among the crowd. If you\''re staying downtown, the cinema in River Center Mall is a great choice for first run releases and is within walking distance of many of the hotels. The fairly new cinema at the Alamo Quarry Market offers first-run features with shows as late as midnight. If not for a movie, stop in just to see the enormous quarry-inspired movable mechanical display in the lobby. For arthouse films, your only option is the Santikos Bijou Cinema Bistro. Finally, for larger-than-life films, check out the IMAX Theater adjacent to River Center Mall downtown. A perennial favorite is <em>Alamo—Price of Freedom</em>, which tells the story of the battle of the Alamo; it\''s a great film to catch before visiting the cradle of Texas liberty.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Whether you want to get down with your bad self or simply prefer to watch, San Antonio\''s dance offerings fit the bill. If you like to dance the night away, be sure to check out The Bonham. Located downtown, this is perhaps the best dance club the city has to offer. Predominantly a gay bar during the week, the weekends and Wednesday night \"straight nights\" draw a very mixed crowd. Huge dance floors, a pounding sound system and the requisite disco lighting make for a fun, dance-\''til-you-drop evening. The place really doesn\''t start hopping until after 10p. The Davenport San Antonio, with live music plus cocktails, and the Ivory Nightclub, a popular haunt with DJs and a dance floor are two varying options for a night on the town. For those who prefer to watch the professionals, there are several dance companies that perform regularly, including the San Antonio Dance Umbrella and Urban 15. The city also hosts many touring companies during the year, quite a few performing culturally significant movements.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">San Antonio is an amazing city comprised of many different cultures. And the people here like a good party. Combine the two traits and you have more cultural festivals and events than you can imagine. San Antonio\''s biggest party, Fiesta, is a 10-day long celebration of the city\''s history and culture; it is held every year in April. Comprised of parades, debutante balls, street parties, concerts, sporting events and more, you are guaranteed to find something for everybody. So significant is this festival that the city practically shuts down on the last Friday afternoon so that everyone can attend the Battle of Flowers parade that winds through downtown. Other popular events include Jazz\''s Alive, and Juneteenth.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Considered to be one of \''america\''s 25 Best Cities for Shopping\'' by <em>Forbes.com, </em>San Antonio offers a wide palette of shopping experiences for locals and curious visitors alike. A multitude of malls like La Cantera, Shops at Rivercenter and the North Star Mall form the city\''s star retail attractions, although smaller shopping staples such as the Pearl Farmers Market and the Mexican Market at Commerce Street must not be missed either. The Alamo Quarry Market is also a good option and features a medley of eclectic brands and stores, whereas Paris Hatters offers a fabulous selection of millinery for anyone looking for quirky shopping spots. &nbsp;</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1777,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Central San Antonio</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the most ethnically diverse areas in the city, San Antonio\''s central area comprises of suburbs and neighborhoods that lie close to the downtown area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">River Walk/Downtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The heart of the city\''s tourism business beats along the River Walk and in the downtown area. A historically significant area, the area is rich with a palpable aura of Texas\'' heritage, seen in monumental landmarks like The Alamo. The Alamo Cenotaph Monument lies nearby, inscribed with the martyrs of the Battle of Alamo. Across the Alamo Plaza, an arterial street that runs through the length of this downtown complex, a number of museums like the Guinness World Record Museum and the The Buckhorn Saloon & Museum offer plenty of entertainment. The La Villita Historic Arts Village, a local gem listed on the National Register sits on a leafy stretch of South Alamo Street, and across the River Walk, the Briscoe Western Art Museum brings to life the legacy of the American West, through a multitude of art exhibits and artifacts.  Densely packed with hotels, attractions, restaurants and bars, a visitor could conceivably spend their entire trip right here. The area bustles with activity nearly every night of the week and almost all year long, with locals and tourists alike enjoying mouth-watering cuisine at Boudro\''s or Paesano\''s River Walk, singing their hearts out at Howl at the Moon. Not your average tourist trap, the River Walk entices many locals to brave the crowds and enjoy their city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">King William/Southtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If San Antonio gets funky, this is where it happens. Once primarily residential and neglected, the area has seen a resurgence of interest and an infusion of capital. Urban professionals are snatching up historical homes and refurbishing them, entrepreneurs are launching hip new businesses, and the locals are taking notice. Wander just a few blocks from downtown and discover Rosario\''s. If you can, check out the area during a First Friday celebration. This community-wide celebration held the first Friday of each month draws crowds from all over the city for art openings, theater productions, dining and shopping. King William\''s quirky sprawl also features the Blue Star Contemporary Museum that overlooks the San Antonio River, and hosts brilliant art exhibitions in its bright space. Lavaca, a former market district that once housed several stores, artisan shops and small businesses, stands vibrant transformed, and accommodates a wonderful miscellany of bars, cafes, brew pubs, art galleries and even festivals in its colorful sprawl. SoFlo, a colloquial acronym for the South Flores market that commences every second Saturday at 10a, is also located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Alamo Heights</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the original suburbs of San Antonio, Alamo Heights harbors some of the city\''s finest dining establishments and upscale shopping opportunities. And with good reason, as a huge portion of the city\''s wealth resides in this neighborhood. For dinner, locals flock to Paloma Blanca or Cappy\''s. Beer and pool preside at the Broadway 50/50. For a gift for that special someone, you can\''t go wrong at Sloan-Hall. Bounded by the neighborhoods of Lincoln Heights and Olmos Park, this historic neighborhood is dominated by the presence of the University of the Incarnate Word. The McNay Art Museum, Texas\'' oldest modern art museum is located here, as are a melange of shopping centers like the Alamo Quarry Market, the North Star Mall and the H-E-B Central Market on Broadway Street.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Monte Vista/Olmos Park</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Neighboring Alamo Heights, this area is home to some of the most exquisite mansions in the city. At the very least it is worth driving through just to gawk. It is also a popular school and college district. You will find some wonderful neighborhood dining secrets, along McCullough Avenue.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North East/North Central</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping centers, housing developments and highways are popping up all over North East and North Central San Antonio as many new residents move in, both from out of town and from within the city\''s more central neighborhoods. This kind of rapid growth seems to require predictability, as is evidenced in the plethora of restaurant and shopping chains. The Uptown Central neighborhood is home to the rich and the famous, home to residences of celebs like Tommy Lee Jones and TV actor Thomas Gibson. The Witte Museum is located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northwest/Medical Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The medical industry is big business in San Antonio, so this area continues to grow at a steady pace. Sort of a hodgepodge of strip shopping centers, restaurants, residences and office complexes, the atmosphere of the neighborhood seems a bit disjointed. Still, you can find great dining at Jacala Mexican Restaurant. Shopping is somewhat limited to chain stores.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West Side</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Locals that feel the need to escape the city head out this way to dine at Rudy\''s BBQ and observe colorful marine life at San Antonio Aquarium. The next day, shop at all the antique stores in Boerne or spend the day at Six Flags Fiesta Texas or Sea World.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
