 (1844,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums, Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">and Workshops</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of New Mexico\''s most loved artists is remembered inside the walls of the Georgia O\''keeffe Museum. Her art helped shape the style of New Mexico\''s artists and some of her best works are on display. Other galleries, like Lewallen Contemporary Art, keep the independent spirit alive and well with shows from contemporary local artists.A great way to unleash your own creative potential is to sign up for a class at the Prairie Dog Glass Studio where you\''ll learn the art of glassblowing. If you want to purchase some unique glass art pieces for yourself, the Liquid Light Glass Gallery, run by award-winning artists, is an excellent choice.Folk art is given its due at the Museum of International Folk Art while the Meow Wolf installation allows you to truly enjoy an art experience like no other within its fantastical walls.If you enjoy learning about history, then the New Mexico History Museum is the place for you, while the Museum of Indian Arts & Culture shines the spotlight on Native American art from around the region.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Some called it folly and others called it vision when a youthful John Crosby founded the Santa Fe Opera in 1957. History now recognizes it as genius. The original 420-seat, open-air theater perched on a piñon-carpeted hill north of town has been replaced. The opera has premiered dozens of now-popular shows. Each season offers old favorites and new, original productions. Designed by the renowned American architect who shares the amphitheater\''s name, the Paolo Soleri Amphitheatre is a masterpiece in a city that subsists on the arts. The theater provides a one-of-a-kind setting for entertainers like Carlos Santana, Dan Fogelberg, Bruce Hornsby and Paco de Lucia. The most historic venue in the city is the restored Lensic Performing Arts Center. Designed to resemble a Moorish Palace of the Iberian Peninsula, the theater was built in 1931. The Lensic was soon recognized as one of the finest palaces of stage and screen in the state. Desert Chorale, an internationally known singing troupe, is one of the only professional chorus groups in the country. They give a moving performance inside the hallowed sanctuary of St. Francis Cathedral every other week during the summer.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Each summer for a weekend in late July, more than 300 Hispanic artists, both traditional and contemporary, converge on Santa Fe to display their work at the traditional Spanish Market. Spanish Dancers, Bandoleros and modern musicians perform on stage in the Santa Fe Plaza during the event. Held on the weekend after Labor Day, Santa Fe Fiesta is the celebration of the Spanish reconquest of Santa Fe in 1692. One of the oldest civic celebrations in the nation, the event has run every year since 1712. In 1926, a new character, named Zozobra, was introduced to the crowds. Zozobra is a 50-foot (15-meter) animated puppet of paper, wood and pyrotechnics, which is set ablaze at the opening of the Fiesta. In a fury of fire, amplified moans, screams of agony and flailing arms, the beast is brought down, taking with it the troubles and strife of all who attend the moving ritual.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoor Activities</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Santa Fe on the edge of the great outdoors is a destination made to explore the wild. Surrounded by the Sangre de Cristo Mountains, the city is a leaping off point for all manner of adventure. From hiking, biking, horseback riding, river rafting and skiing, there\''s almost no limit to what you can do. Whether you\''re seeking adrenaline-pumping action or a leisurely nature ramble, you\''ll find your niche here. Rush down the Rio Grande in a raft or hit the slopes in winter, Santa Fe caters to all.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1845,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Guadalupe Historic District and Plaza</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Nowhere is this charm more evident than on Santa Fe Plaza. Shaded by 150-year-old cottonwood trees, this grassy square is surrounded by historic buildings. The ancient adobe structures, with their gentle corners and irregular earth-tone walls, bake in the strong light of the New Mexico sun. The hustle of the modern city teems to the south, but on the Plaza, life slows and the locals affectionately call their home \"the Land of Mañana.\" On the north side of the Plaza is the Palace of the Governors, the oldest public building in the country. Across from this grand structure, Native American artisans sell the fruits of their labors on colorful blankets at the yearly Santa Fe Indian Market. The remaining three sides of the Plaza are lined with boutiques, galleries, restaurants and jewelry stores that cater to tourists. East of the Plaza is the beautiful Cathedral Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi, built in the Roman Revival style, that replaced the original adobe church that once stood here.If you walk south, crossing the Old Santa Fe Trail, you\''ll reach the Oldest House. Converted into a museum, this structure is considered one of the oldest in the United States, though its exact age is undetermined. It offers a fascinating look at the city\''s past. Also nearby is the Loretto Chapel with its unusual spiral staircase.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Railyard</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A lively arts district in Downtown Santa Fe, The Railyard is a hub for shopping, dining, and the arts in the city. Once a historic rail yard, this area has been redeveloped into an exciting space that brings together the city\''s cultural and historic roots alongside contemporary movements and events. Stroll down the promenade and browse local boutiques and artisan galleries or bike on the Rail Trail. Quench your thirst at a local brewpub or enjoy a cup of coffee after a busy day. From shopping to outdoor fun, there\''s plenty to do in this area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Capitol and South of Capitol</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The New Mexico State Capitol, locally known as \''the Roundhouse\'' is the seat of the state government. It is open to visitors and you can tour the building while enjoying the 600 fine works of art that adorn its walls. The area to the south of the Capital is a quiet area known for its bungalow style housing.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Canyon Road</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Carrying down melted snow from the 12,000-foot (3,657-meter) peaks of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains, the Rio Santa Fe splashes and dances over granite boulders on its way south and west to the Rio Grande. Walled compounds hide historic haciendas along this narrow winding road. Many of the old properties have been converted into galleries, bed and breakfasts, and restaurants like Geronimo and El Farol.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Greater Santa Fe</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Like spokes of a wheel, three major arteries spear their way northward from Interstate 25 toward the Plaza. On the western fringe of the city, Cerrillos Road is Santa Fe\''s busiest boulevard and boasts the largest concentration of modern hotels and retail outlets in the city. Further down, El Rancho de las Golondrinas is a historic ranch turned open-air museum that has a fun array of activities and people dressed up in period costumes.To the east is Old Pecos Trail. This two-lane route to downtown is void of the high-density commercial zones that line Cerrillos Road, but a sharp eye will spot a number of appealing lodging options, like La Quinta Inn Santa Fe, and shops, like Jackalope, peeking out from behind the piñon trees.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">North</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Rolling hills carpeted with piñon and juniper bracket the city to the north and create a setting for the world-famous Santa Fe Opera. This outdoor theater is famous for its acoustics and offers the very finest in operatic entertainment. Nearby you\''ll also find Camel Rock Casino and the Ten Thousand Waves spa.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
