 (1874,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you\''re a museum lover, don\''t miss the \"MIS\" or Museu da Imagem e do Som (Sound and Image Museum), truly an extraordinary sensory experience. For those interested in the city\''s history and colonization, go to the Pátio do Colégio and thereby visit the Museu Anchieta to witness the esoteric iconography of the Jesuit order. The Museu Ipiranga is an important museum that houses works of art from Brazil\''s independence and the Museu do Folclore is another historical place of interest. Parque do Ibirapuera is a work of art from Brazil\''s most famous architect/city planner, Oscar Niemayer, who has engineered whole cities, such as the capital, Brasilia. Another intriguing museum is the Instituto Butantã; this place focuses on venom and it\''s deadliness as well as its benefits. There are also plenty of snakes in open-air pits. The São Paulo Art Gallery, the Museum of Modern Art and the Museum of Contemporary Art are other wonderful institutions worthy of note.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife & Clubbing</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The districts of Jardins, Bela Vista, Moema, Itaim-Bibi, Vila Madalena and Pinheiros are Sao Paulo\''s nightlife hubs. To taste a bit of <em>cachaça</em>, (Brazil\''s national liquor) go to Bar do Arnesto, Empório Sagarana or Terra Nova Cachaçaria, while the Wine Library is an oenologist\''s dream in the district of Morumbi. Listen to bossa-nova until the break of dawn at Baretto and mingle with some beautiful paulistas. Café Piu Piu hosts rock concerts most days of the week, while Bar Você Vai se Quiser is an authentic samba bar. Hot Hot is Flávia Cecatto\''s trendy lounge, Skye Bar is a sky-high alternative and D-Edge is a dazzling destination for electronic music. There\''s also the Lions Nightclub with its upscale, retro vibe and Bourbon Street, Sao Paulo\''s traditional jazz, blues and soul club. These are just a few options to explore, however; the city is brimming with superb nighttime distractions.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In November, which is a summer month in São Paulo, the Mix Brasil of Cinema and Video for Sexual Diversity showcases more than 200 films from around the world. The Mostra Internacional de Cinema de São Paulo (Film Festival) also presents eclectic cinema gems across theaters in the greater São Paulo area. Alongside the number of traditional movie theaters and multiplexes, there is also the Cinemateca and some art-house cinemas, offering presentations of non-commercial and cult films.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For the theater crowd, more than forty theaters are open all year round, with a variety of performances for both adults and children. You can check what\''s playing in the local newspapers and weekly magazines, with the most complete entertainment guide appearing in the \"A Folha de São Paulo\" broadsheet (with its magazine supplement every Friday). Tickets for the theater should be booked well in advance. Top venues include the historic Municipal Theatre and the surreal Ibirapuera Auditorium.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Live Music and Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">From intimate live music venues to grand arenas, Sao Paulo hosts a plethora of options for concertgoers of every stripe. The city has long been known as an important milestone for a musicians career and often features on the route of international tours featuring some of the world\''s top artists. The Arena Anhembi, in particular, has hosted the likes of Maroon 5 and the Red Hot Chili Peppers; a mammoth venue that caters to crowds of up to 35,000. The Interlagos Arena, Espaço das Américas and Allianz Parque are other major venues, while Cine Joia and the Audio Club appeal to more niche audiences.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Contemporary art and photographic exhibitions are organized throughout the year, not only in the most famous galleries, but also in dozens of other art galleries spread throughout the city. You can find information on these exhibitions in newspaper guides or in guides found in hotel receptions, or at tourist information centers. Brazilian and international cultural activities, organized by SESC (Serviço Social do Comércio) and funded by local big businesses in and around São Paulo are also recommended.The Museu de Arte de Sao Paulo is by far the city\''s most well-known exhibition space. The museum showcases an impressive collection of post-WWII and contemporary Brazilian artwork alongside the Southern Hemisphere\''s largest collection of artwork by European masters. Choque Cultural, on the other hand, proclaims ever-changing exhibitions of outsider art. The city also hosts revered art festivals like the Bienal Sao Paulo and the SP Arte each year, transforming the city into one massive art gallery.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping is a worthy pastime in Sao Paulo where bustling markets, mammoth shopping centers and quirky local shops all vie for attention. Paulistas are known for the penchant for style, so the city\''s wealth of shopping destinations should come as no surprise. The Shopping JK Iguatemi is not only Sao Paulo\''s haven for luxury goods, but is also one of South America\''s most upscale malls. Here, you\''ll find top international designer brands galore. The Rua Oscar Freire in the Jardins district is another popular haunt for designer boutique, and is best known for its collection of Brazilian brands, most notably Melissa, a local shoe emporium known for its fanciful window displays. For crafts, fresh produce and traditional street food, head to one of the city\''s many weekly markets of <em>fieras</em>, such as the Feira Benedito Calixto and Feira da República. The Galeria do Rock is a gathering place for the city\''s underground music fans, stocked with clothing, accessories and every imaginable thing related to the musical genre of rock. Other interesting shopping destinations include the Livraria Cultura for books, Salinas Off for swimwear, and Espaço Havaianas for colorful flipflops.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Others</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">São Paulo also has plenty to offer younger visitors to the city. From the local zoo to the Wet\''n\''wild São Paulo with its numerous water slides, the Parque da Mônica, and the Hopi Hari, Sao Paulo has much to boast. Or you could take the whole family on a trip to the Guarapiranga Reservoir, which offers boats and hydroplane rides, man-made beaches and natural forests. You may also visit nearby locations such as the Santos and Guarujá beaches, just 80 kilometers (50 miles) from the city.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1875,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pinheiros & Lapa</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The old center, the suburbs, and a huge number of districts that make up this city all help to reveal the history of the city and its population. Initially inhabited by indigenous peoples such as Guarani and Tupi, the city received a considerable population of African slaves in the 17th Century when the Indians succumbed to Portuguese colonists. Slaves provided the main source of manual labor for the coffee and sugar cane plantations, which in turn helped create the modern city. However, São Paulo\''s population grew very slowly until the middle of the 19th Century. At this time, the area we now know as Greater São Paulo was still made up of small scattered settlements, concentrated mainly around the present-day locations of the Pinheiros, Freguesia do Ó and Lapa districts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Brás</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As coffee became the biggest commodity in the 1870s, the city prospered. Railways linked São Paulo with neighboring Santos harbor, banks and export companies contributed additional wealth, enticing more and more people towards the development of new districts. From 1870 onwards, the urbanization of the city took place as swamps were transformed into gardens. Brás, one of the oldest districts and the former estate of the Portuguese trader José Brás, along with the Mooca and Lapa districts, became the new home of Italian immigrants who flocked to the city at the end of the 19th Century. The immigrants influenced the culture of São Paulo and heavily contributed to the <em>paulista</em> spoken accent, which is markedly different from any other in Brazil. At the end of the 19th Century and beginning of the 20th, many farms were subdivided, and new districts such as Santa Efigênia, Bom Retiro, Consolação and Campos Elísios, (where the well-to-do lived at that time) came into being.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Liberdade</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Thanks to the construction of the first power station in 1890, electrically-driven trams were introduced to the city. In the 20th Century, industrial development created new urban areas towards the east, west and south, following the railway lines and the Tietê, Tamanduateí and Pinheiros river valleys. Japanese immigrants, who arrived at the beginning of this century to work in agriculture, settled in what is today one of the most traditional areas of São Paulo: the Liberdade district. Today, this area exhibits many aspects of Japanese culture, including some of the best Japanese restaurants in the world.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jardins</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Smaller, older settlements around the city were incorporated into the metropolitan region over the course of time. From 1915 onwards, very elegant districts started to spring up, such as Jardim Europa, Jardim América and Jardim Paulista, which have today become sophisticated commercial zones known collectively as the \"Jardins.\" The Avenida Paulista is the Wall Street of São Paulo, boasting some of the most expensive office space available, as well as epitomizing the contrast of the different eras that so characterize São Paulo. Down one side of the street are historic neighborhoods and buildings, such as the Teatro Municipal, Viaduto do Chá and the Vale do Anhangabaú; and down the other side, one will find residential and modern office constructions with well-planned architecture and engineering, notably the Jardins district itself.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Morumbi</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Also on this side are the Jóquei Clube and the Morumbi district, where, besides the big mansions and luxurious residential buildings, you can find the Morumbi Stadium, one of the venues chosen by FIFA for the first World Club football tournament.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Vila Madelena e Bexiga</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Another district notable for both its culture and its gastronomy is Vila Madalena, which possesses a high number of bars and restaurants, and an intense nightlife that attracts professionals, university students and artists. Most of São Paulo\''s districts have acquired a unique personality as, for example, the Bela Vista (also known as Bexiga) neighborhood, where you can find most of the city\''s theaters, and patrons frequent numerous bars featuring <em>forró</em> music - traditional music from north-eastern Brazil.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
