 (1904,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Art</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The patriarch of the local art scene, the Seattle Art Museum (SAM) has been pushing steadily away from exclusively showing antiquities to showcasing more contemporary art. At SAM, look for rotating modern art shows, and be sure to check out the Native American and African galleries. The contemporary art shows at the Henry Art Gallery at the University of Washington always have an academic background and a flair for challenging conceptions. The Center on Contemporary Art (CoCA) and a host of edgy galleries like James Harris and Greg Kucera, showcase young, enthusiastic local talent. Check it all out during the monthly neighborhood Artwalks, during which galleries stay open late and serve wine and cheese.  The Frye Art Museum has a pleasant collection of 19th and 20th Century paintings, while the Museum of History and Industry covers the same time period but with its focus on Seattle\''s history. The Burke Museum and the Museum of Flight offer glimpses of natural history and Boeing science respectively, with towering artifacts (dinosaurs and airplanes, naturally) at both.  The history of Seattle\''s ethnic minorities gets a thoughtful, detailed look at the Wing Luke Asian Museum. The Seattle Children\''s Museum and the Pacific Science Center, both at the Seattle Center, are paradises of activities for kids. Further afield, the Bellevue Art Museum has a good collection of 20th Century art. The Museum of Pop Culture displays truly captivating exhibits from the pop culture realm across genres, and has several interactive displays in its Frank Gehry-designed building. The Chihuly Garden and Glass exhibit nearby is a stunning display of Dale Chihuly\''s glass installation, a visually striking modern sculpture that stretches for over 100-feet (30.48 meters) along the expanse of the glass-walled museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hollywood glitz rules the downtown scene at Pacific Place. Art-house funkiness rules Capitol Hill at the SIFF Cinema Egyptian Theatre, and over the University District at the Neptune, the Varsity Theatre, and the Grand Illusion. Those with various tastes can have fun at the various annual film festivals held in the city, where sneak previews of blockbusters play alongside world cinema. The biggest festival is the Seattle International Film Festival, which takes the town over for three weeks in May and June. Also keep a lookout for the Seattle Lesbian and Gay Film Festival.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Seattle\''s vast sprawl accommodates a wide and dynamic repertoire of fantastic performing arts that keep denizens and vacationing audiences engaged throughout the year - whether it is brilliant theater, rib-tickling comedy, dance, or classical opera or concerts, Seattle has it all.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Seattle Symphony performs in the acoustically crisp Benaroya Hall, which also provides much-needed concert space for the excellent Seattle Men\''s Chorus and other classical groups. The past few years have also seen the rise of an early-music movement, with several period ensembles garnering acclaim and audiences under the aegis of the Early Music Guild. Churches around town and the Seattle Art Museum often stage lovely chamber music concerts as well. Experimental rock groups and other combinations of world, funk and pop music play frequently at the Showbox and the Crocodile Cafe. Jazzmen and blues masters hold down regular gigs at the Tractor Tavern. For more jazz, the sleek Sea Monster Lounge deserves a mention, while Columbia City Theater is a colorful ex-vaudeville venue is known for previously hosting performances by Duke Ellington and Ella Fitzgerald. There\''s also a lively Irish scene in town, with live traditional and modern music at Conor Byrne\''s, the Owl \''n\'' Thistle and Kells Irish Pub. The KeyArena is famous for hosting contemporary music concerts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Opera</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Seattle Opera is internationally for its Wagner productions, most notably its four-day <em>Ring</em> cycle. The opera has broadened its range considerably since, and performs from August to Late May in Marion Oliver McCaw Hall at Seattle Center.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Mainstream houses include the Seattle Repertory Theater, the Intiman and the ACT Theater. These companies put on strong seasons every year, usually comprised of modern classics and premieres. Fringe theater groups, such as the Annex Theater, the Book-It Repertory Theatre and Theater Schmeater provide well-produced, eclectic alternatives. There\''s also a manic fringe festival in early spring, when dozens of groups materialize out of nowhere to put on shows. In the niche bracket, Seattle Children\''s Theatre presents extremely professional, creative productions for kids ages 4-14, while the historic 5th Avenue Theatre brings Broadway musicals to town.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Comedy</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Open-mic nights and laugh-till-your-sides-hurt comedy shows are one of the things that keep Seattle\''s denizens fresh and alive. A miscellany of various clubs in the city, such as the Laughs Comedy Club in U-District, the Jet City Improv and Downtown\''s Unexpected Productions Improv are a hit with Seattleites, while others like Theater Schmeater and Paramount Theatre are known for occasionally hosting an impressive comedic line-up of shows and artists.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dance</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Apart from the deservedly renowned Balanchine-school Pacific Northwest Ballet, and the beloved contemporary dance house On The Boards, good dance in Seattle is hard to come by on a regular basis. The best pickings include the University of Washington excellent World Music & Dance Series, which brings top-notch groups such as the Paul Taylor Dance Company into town every year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you have a preference, then Seattle has a store for it. Teeming with a bevy of retail options that span locally-owned boutiques, high-end designer stores, souvenir specialty shops and bargain spots, Seattle is every shoppers\'' dream. For generic shopping needs, explore the \''one-stop-shop\'' destinations in Downtown Seattle, where shopping centers like Pacific Place and Westlake Center await. Of course, if its local flavor and artisanal gems you\''re seeking, then stop by at longstanding retail fixtures like the Pike Place Market, or the shops lining Seattle\''s sparkling waterfront. On Ballard Avenue, there is a gaggle of unique boutiques to explore, whereas brand outlets like Centralia and North Bend offer excellent budget shopping options.  &nbsp;</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1905,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Seattle</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A moderate-sized sprawl occupies Seattle\''s vibrant center, a commercial area with several distinct neighborhoods of its own. Downtown Seattle is a versatile haven, straddling the city\''s cultural, commercial, culinary and retail facets with splendid aplomb.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Seattle Chinatown-International District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Pungent aromas and delectable dishes emit from restaurants like Bush Garden in this primarily Asian-American neighborhood. Specialty shops filled with unusual treasures line the streets. The district is home to the inner-city oasis Hing Hay Park, complete with a pagoda and the Wing Luke Asian Museum.The neighborhood, while primarily populated with Chinese immigrants, also consists of a smattering of Vietnamese and Japanese families who have made this place home. Other landmarks include the Kobe Terrace and the Danny Woo International District Community Garden. Festivals such as the Lunar New Year are celebrated here, and the district is also home to a lovely night market that comes alive in early fall.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pike Place Market/Belltown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Pike Place Market is the heart of Seattle and the number one tourist site in the area, attracting frenzied crowds of visitors and locals. The oldest continually operating farmer\''s market in the country, Pike Place features fresh fish, fruits and vegetables, and arts and crafts as far as the eye can see. Abundant restaurants include Maximilien in the Market. Shops offer goods from around the world. Bring some change as there are always street musicians and buskers singing for their supper. This is also the home of the first Starbucks coffee store, located at 1912 Pike Place. The Moore Theater, Seattle\''s oldest operating theater, and the Seattle Aquarium are also located here.  If you venture further north of Pike Place, the cool and trendy neighborhood of Belltown unfolds before you, a dynamic area filled with fashionable boutiques, art galleries, bars and sky-piercing condominiums. The area receives a large share of Downtown\''s yuppie crowd that begin trickling into the area after hours, unwinding at its hip bars and nightclubs such as the Crocodile Cafe after a long day at work. It is also known for its scenic offerings, with the waterfront Olympic Sculpture Park providing sweeping views of the Puget Sound, as well as fascinating visitors with its wonderful array of sculptures and nature trails.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pioneer Square</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is Seattle\''s oldest neighborhood and the place where the term \"Skid Row\" originated. Lumberjacks skidded logs down \"Skid Road,\" now Yesler Street, to a mill at the bottom of the hill. Saloons and brothels lined the street, and the term soon took on its derogatory connotation locally and nationwide. The Underground Tour explores the now subterranean storefronts of the original neighborhood. Today the neighborhood is filled with art galleries, small shops, bookstores, including Elliott Bay Book Co., and restaurants like the elegant Il Terrazzo Carmine. At night the square comes to life. Popular nightspots include Central Saloon, one of Seattle\''s oldest bars. Many clubs feature live music, and a group of bars and clubs in the area offers admittance to each for a single cover charge. Occidental Square, a leafy public space is sprawled in the midst of Pioneer Square, not far away from Smith Tower and other landmarks like the Sky View Observatory Columbia Center and the Seattle City Hall.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">First Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Extending beyond Downtown\''s tourist-dominated center is the neighborhood of First Hill, a predominantly cultural area characterized by a warren of modern homes, stately manors and mansions, and hospitals, intermittently speckled with art museums, cafes, and a miscellany of small restaurants. Its most notable landmarks include the Frye Art Museum, the Seattle University and its surrounding campus, and the historic town hall, and the Renaissance-themed St James Cathedral.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Capitol Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Yes, this Washington city has one too and its mix of eclectic shops, art-house theaters, wonderful restaurants and interesting people make it one of the most diverse neighborhoods in Seattle. Some of the city\''s most historic houses are located here, as is Volunteer Park. Seattle University and Cornish College of the Arts also border this hill. The park is also home to the Lake View Cemetery, the resting place of several of the city\''s founders, and of father-son duo Bruce Lee and Brandon Lee. In recent years, Capitol Hill has also become widely known for its role in the activities of the LGBT community, and also boasts a vivacious nightlife, with landmark bars like Pony and Garage located here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Alki Beach</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">About as close as Seattle gets to California, this sandy beach in West Seattle draws swarms of walkers, joggers, bikers, skaters, scuba divers and volleyball players. Cafes and restaurants such as Salty\''s on Alki line the main street, ready to nourish those who\''ve played at the beach all day. Alki Beach, directly across Elliott Bay from downtown, is the spot where the first European settlers camped in the winter of 1851 before they moved to the more sheltered area that is now downtown. The Log House Museum and a handful of boutiques are located here as well.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ballard</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Affectionately known for slow drivers and the lilting accents of its many residents of Scandinavian descent, this area was first settled by immigrant Nordic fishermen and mill workers. Visit the Hiram M. Chittenden Locks to watch boats travel from salt water to freshwater, then take a trip to Golden Gardens Park to watch the sunset. Popular restaurants in the area include Ray\''s Boathouse and Bad Albert\''s Tap & Grill. Stop by Fisherman\''s Terminal for a look at the boats that keep the fishing industry thriving.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Fremont</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hip and eclectic, Fremont is always a fun place to go. The sign that says \"Welcome to the Center of the Universe\" is the first clue that you\''ve arrived. Oddities like the Freemont Troll, a smoking rocket and a bronzed Vladimir Lenin statue will leave you laughing while the Saturday gallery walks and the Fremont Sunday Flea Market will have you browsing. Say hello to the group waiting for a bus, but don\''t expect an answer—they\''re life-sized statues, often dressed in celebration of someone\''s birthday or another grand event. The Fremont Oktoberfest is also held here each year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Madison Park</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Quaint shops, restaurants and cafes fill this upper-crust neighborhood on the shores of Lake Washington. The Washington Park Arboretum fills you with a renewed energy as you walk along its scenic pathways and flower-filled corners, while the Seattle Japanese Garden\''s cherry orchards and teahouse ceremonies brighten up even the bleakest Seattle day. Walk down the street to the Madison Park & Beach, take in the beautiful view of the Eastside, and dream about owning a waterfront villa. The Museum of History and Industry can also be found in Madison Park.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Queen Anne Hill</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A combination of a quiet hilltop neighborhood and a young trendy hot spot, Queen Anne has popular restaurants like Peso\''s Taco Lounge as well as coffee shops and nightspots. The view of the city from the west slope is incredible, especially from Kerry Park, which offers Seattle\''s most photographed view. Split into North Queen Anne and Lower Queen Anne, this scenic neighborhood is dominated by landmarks like the Seattle Center. Part amusement park, part festival grounds, the center hosts The Bite of Seattle, Bumbershoot and many other popular festivals. Permanent fixtures of this 74-acre (29-hectare) park include the Intiman Theater, Paul Allen\''s Experience Music Project Museum, the Pacific Science Center and the Space Needle.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">University District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This area is home to the University of Washington, known to locals as \"U-Dub.\" The park-like 700-acre (283-hectare) campus is perfect for a midday stroll. Boats filled with die-hard Husky fans fight for space around the waterfront stadium on game days. Low-priced restaurants and pubs like line the \"Ave\" (University Avenue), and stylish young people fill the streets. The University Bookstore anchors a thriving shopping scene. The Burke Museum of Natural History and Culture, the Henry Art Gallery, the Husky Stadium and the Center for Urban Horticulture are all part of this sprawling district.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Waterfront</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Elliott Bay, part of Puget Sound, laps against Seattle\''s Waterfront. On summer days, visitors pack the area to enjoy the fresh air, quaint shops and many seafood restaurants, which include Elliott\''s Oyster House, Anthony\''s Pier 66, and Ivar\''s. Catch a ferry to Bremerton or Bainbridge Island, or take a water tour to Blake Island\''s Tillicum Village for a salmon dinner and Native American dance show.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Redmond</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Thriving due to corporate residents like Microsoft and Nintendo, Redmond has an unlikely yet appealing combination of countryside and technology. The software industry brings money here and with it good shopping at Redmond Town Center. Cyclists appreciate the velodrome at Marymoor Park and the Lake Sammamish State Park Trail.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Kirkland</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Across Lake Washington from Seattle lies the \"Monterey of the Northwest,\" so called for its posh art galleries, boutiques, restaurants and waterfront. The Kirkland Performance Center can be found here. While close to the city, Kirkland manages to maintain its small-town atmosphere, which adds to its appeal.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
