 (1933,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art and Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Sienna is a cultural powerhouse, and each district or <em>contrada</em> has its own museum. Among the top choices, the historic hospital-turned-museum, Complesso Museale Santa Maria della Scala displays an excellent array of artworks across genres from fine painting to sculpture and medieval artifacts. Another important museum where visitors can explore the city\''s intriguing artistic development is the  Palazzo Pubblico and Museo Civico, whose frescoes are some of the most beautiful and well preserved in the country. Salvaged architectural sections of the gorgeous Duomo and its artworks are displayed at the Museo dell\''opera Metropolitana while the Museo della Tortura is perfect for visitors with a morbid streak.  <div class=\"listing_callout\"></div></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Siena\''s pubs and bars are largely focused in the center of town. The <em>osterie</em>, or inns, offer a chance for guests to sample some of the area\''s great wines. Here you can recapture some of the old flavors of the city, and has become an activity that is being rediscovered by young people. This is not an incentive for heavy drinking, but a way to enjoy a good wine as it should be served—accompanied by a snack. One of the most popular <em>osterie</em> in the city is the Antica Osteria da Divo that\''s worth a visit for a traditional meal amidst ancient caves. There is also the opportunity to learn about winemaking techniques, and how different wines are made using these traditional methods. For anyone who feels like a beer, there are a number of English and Irish-style pubs like La Diana that are open until late at night—though this is in comparison to other places in Siena, not to bars in other towns such as Rimini, where a closing time of 3a is more likely to be the norm.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music & Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Of course, drinking and dancing aren\''t the only ways to spend an evening in Siena. There is also a large choice of cultural activities to keep you from idleness. The university organizes an annual \"Parole e Musica\" (Words and Music) program, which covers dramatic arts and offers good, inexpensive shows. There are also all the traditional entertainments, with cinemas and theaters that have excellent seasons throughout the winter, such as the Teatro dei Rinnovati and the Teatro dei Rozzi. There are also classical music concerts in winter, organized by the Accademia Chigiana, which take place in the halls of the Palazzo Chigi Saracini. Students on a budget need not fear, as there are a variety of discounts to be found. Siena has also become known as a jazz center, as it holds a variety of concerts between the end of July and the first week in August and which feature a host of famous names. In addition, Siena has become renowned for the study of jazz theory that takes place here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Wine Tasting and Wineries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Siena, in the heart of the Tuscan wine region, is a perfect place for oenophiles. The undulating hills around the historic city are home to lush vineyards that produce excellent Chianti and there are numerous wine tours and wine tasting organized by local companies and wine bars around the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Palio</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Palio is the summer\''s biggest event for residents of the city, and is also of great interest to visitors seeking a thrill. The people of the various districts of Siena follow their ritual of strategies, hopes, prayers, dramas, and more - all to win a horse race. No visit to Siena is complete without an encounter with this exciting race to cap off the fun.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1934,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Aquila (Eagle)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Southwest of the stunning Piazza del Campo, Aquila is a neighborhood steeped in history, home to the magnificent Siena Cathedral. It is represented by an eagle and yellow, black and blue are its historic colors. It\''s one of the four noble districts.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bruco (Caterpillar)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">North of the Pizza del Campo, Bruno is the second of the four noble districts, This neighborhood is represented by a caterpillar and yellow and green striped with blue are its colors.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nicchio (Seashell)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In the city\''s far eastern corner, Nicchio is represented by a scalloped seashell. Its identifying colors are blue with a red and yellow border.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Oca (Goose)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">On Pizza del Campo\''s western border, lies the <em>contrade</em> of Oca. Its colors are white and green with a red border and its symbol is a goose with a ribbon around its neck.All of the city\''s major monuments are concentrated in the city\''s historic center around the Piazza del Compo and are easily explored via foot.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1935,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">Singapore\''s vibrant character merits a leisurely stay that would allow one to see its famed attractions and landmarks, and immerse in its storied culture. A tour planned around the major districts allows you to appreciate its history, people and rich cultural diversity in an optimal period of time. Here is the best of Singapore not to be missed.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
