 (1942,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Singapore bubbles with party frenzy almost every night of the week. With a dynamic nocturnal scene that spells excitement, this island boasts close to 700 clubs, bars, pubs and nightclubs. The vibrant nightlife here pampers pub-crawlers and party-goers with a cornucopia of choices, differing in music, range of drinks, the kind of crowd or simply the ambiance they create as they seek an individual identity.  <br><br>\r\nAlong the Singapore River lies Harry\''s Bar at Boat Quay. Each week live bands lure a handsome crowd, mostly expatriates with their soulful jazz. Perfect for a hip night out! A household name for soul and blues is Crazy Elephant. Blues fans pack this pub every weekend to soak in the roaring music of popular bands. Other popular venues that see rocking crowds are Timbre @ The Substation, the Wala Wala Cafe Bar, and the Blu Jaz Cafe. Lulu\''s Lounge, a suave cocktail bar on Raffles Boulevard has all the trappings to keep revelers pleasantly occupied, while others like the CÉ LA VI, tucked within the posh Marina Bay Sands, gives rooftop dining a whole new meaning.  <br><br>\r\nFor those who love to dine, wine and party all night long at one location, there are restaurants that are swiftly transformed into dance grounds right after dinner, the Hard Rock Cafe being a prime example. <br><br>\r\nWhen it comes to dance clubs, one of the most popular ones is the highly-acclaimed Zouk, with its huge dance floor and captivating live screens. In the past, Zouk has been termed by the Singapore Tourism Board as the city\''s \''best Nightspot Experience\'', and is a global favorite. Another big name in town is Altimate, perched atop One Raffles Place\''s 61st floor, while the waterfront Attica has developed a loyal following and excellent reputation over the years. Kilo Lounge, a hidden gem on Tanjong Pagar Road also offers an exceptional atmosphere with its underground party scene and music.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3> \r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Over the years, the Singapore arts scene has leapt onto the international platform, uplifting its cultural image. There are always numerous performances from touring international troupes, in particular during the Singapore International Festival of Arts held over the months of April and May. Another cool festival is the Singapore Festival of Fun, held in March, where a host of family-fun events and comedy fiestas are lined up, including the Magners International Comedy Festival.  <br><br>\r\nCultural festivals abound and often provide a riot of color. Many of these offer visitors much to see, such as the processions during Thaipusam and the Birthday of the Monkey God. Singapore celebrates the Chinese New Year in grandeur, with a lively Chingay procession that produces a grand parade. The city comes blissfully alive with dazzling lights and communal celebrations during festivals like Hari Raya and Deepavali.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Concert Halls & Theatres</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">The best venue for contemporary or classical music has to be the Victoria Theatre and Concert Hall, home to the Singapore Symphony Orchestra. For an orchestra with a difference, experience an evening with the Singapore Chinese Orchestra with its splendid repertoire of traditional and symphonic Chinese music.  <br><br>\r\nFor those interested in dance and renowned troupes with accolades, check out the Singapore Dance Theatre with their enchanting dance movements and exuberant costumes. For more cultural dances, try the Kala Mandhir Temple of Fine Arts and Nrityalaya Aesthetics Society, both known to stage impressive performances.  <br><br>\r\nTheater lovers will appreciate some of Singapore\''s highly acclaimed drama groups. The Necessary Stage tries out experimental works, the Theatre Practice boasts productions like King Lear, and the Singapore Repertory Theatre has a string of accomplishments, including the Golden Child by David Hwang.  <br><br>\r\nAn ambitious project is the Esplanade Theatre on the Bay, which has gained much acclaim. This tremendous center offers just about everything: theater, music, performance space of all kinds, and it\''s all close to the waterfront. Included is the 2000-seat theater and 1800-seat Concert Hall with a 39-foot-high pipe organ and the necessary acoustics to match. This is indeed welcomed by arts fans, who have been going to venues such as The Substation, Jubilee Hall and the Kallang Theatre.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">A \''shop till you drop\'' destination, Singapore offers a multitude of options for those seeking retail therapy. The iconic Orchard Road, a brilliant stretch for shoppers, offers a vibrant atmosphere, and is lined with boutiques and malls from end to end. Some of its most popular tenants include malls like ION Orchard, Paragon, Orchard Central, and Centrepoint. There are luxurious shopping options galore at Raffles City and The Shoppes at Marina Bay Sands. VivoCity, Singapore\''s largest shopping mall, merits a visit for its sheer colossal grandeur and variety.  <br><br>\r\nTo escape mall culture, visit some of Singapore\''s independent designer stores, where there is always something interesting and original to be found. For lovely, one-of-a-kind jewelry, raid Keepers, or visit the stylish nana & bird for a bevy of global and independent labels catering to women. Indulge in locally-made brilliance and carry home gifts and souvenirs from THE FARM STORE on Waterloo Street. Bibliophiles must consider visiting BooksActually, a beautiful enclave of literature that promotes local writers and is also known for their stationery, which is crafted in-house.   <br><br>\r\nBudget musings begin at famous shopping centers such as Mustafa Centre, known for selling everything under the sun, and the Bugis Street Market, known for its dirt-cheap offerings and outstanding variety.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Family Fun</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Singapore is a great family destination. Home to the famed \''sentosa Island,\'' Singapore has several entertainment and leisure opportunities for all ages. Top picks include Universal Studios Singapore, Adventure Cove Waterpark, Madame Tussauds Singapore, and Trick Eye Museum Singapore. With its world-class museums, adventure activities, theme parks and more, whether you\''re looking for a fun day indoors or outdoors, there are plenty of exciting options for the entire family. Night Safari, Singapore, offers an enchanting experience to the entire family. The world\''s first nighttime zoo, this award-winning attraction in Mandai houses more than 2500 animals. At Bayfront Avenue, exciting scientific experiences await curious kids. The ArtScience Museum located here is streamlined into three galleries - Curiosity, Inspiration, Expression - each of them offering discrete experiences through various exhibits.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1943,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Civic District</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is Singapore\''s architectural goldmine. Let yourself be whisked back in time to 1819, when Sir Stamford Raffles first stepped ashore. Still exuding a strong air of a bygone era are well restored government buildings, cathedrals and churches, notably Singapore Cricket Club, once a heritage sports center. Esplanade Park makes for a pleasant stroll while learning about the martyrs and heroes, in honor of whom the various memorials in the park have been built. Impressive government buildings like The Arts House, Singapore\''s former Parliament Building stand as sentinels of a historic time.  <br><br>\r\nThe city\''s finest museums also lie nestled in and around the district including the Singapore Art Museum, Asian Civilisations Museum, Singapore Philatelic Museum and Singapore History Museum. Just at the eastern outskirts of the colonial core stands the renowned Raffles Hotel. A modest museum on the third floor retells its legend.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Singapore River</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Singapore River is marked by the iconic presence of the Merlion that stands guard here. Quaint bridges span the river, ranging from the elegant Anderson Bridge to the simple Ord Bridge. Boat Quay, featuring an array of Peranakan shophouses and godowns, is a pleasant place to dine alfresco, with its long slew of chic cafes, restaurants and pubs. Further upstream is Clarke Quay, yet another series of restored shophouses, where a carnival atmosphere prevails at the fall of dusk. Come Sunday, a flea market thrives here, displaying an appealing range of old treasures, curios and collectibles. Other dining and entertainment attractions along the river include the Riverside Point, Riverside Village and Robertson Quay at the uppermost end.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Financial District</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is home to the towering skyscrapers that lend Singapore its distinctive skyline. Over the years, building after building has battled to be the tallest, among which are included the UOB Building, One Raffles Place, Republic Plaza and the Guoco Tower. At one end near the Singapore River is The Fullerton Hotel, a hotel built in neoclassical architecture that once dominated the district. Further south is Clifford Pier, built in 1931 and is today the embarkation point for cruises to neighboring islands. Another part of old Singapore is the Lau Pa Sat, a complete reconstruction of the first municipal market of 1894 that has been transformed into a thriving food center—the perfect venue for relishing Asian cuisines at budget-friendly prices.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Orchard Road</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Shop till you drop! Join the jostling crowds and do what Singaporeans do best—shop, catwalk and flaunt their chic style. Swanky malls and charming boutiques dot Singapore\''s prime shopping belt from end to end, while trendy alfresco eateries make great spots for watching the fashion parade go by. Top stops include local department stores Robinsons and TANGS (which is a landmark in itself with the distinctive pagoda-roofed tower of the Singapore Marriott Tang Plaza Hotel just above it), and mammoth shopping arcade Ngee Ann City for its posh boutiques and the anchor tenant, Takashimaya. During Christmas, Orchard Road is always a colorful spectacle of bright lights and exuberant decorations.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Chinatown</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Despite having been redeveloped in the past, this ethnic enclave still holds pockets of time-worn buildings where Singaporeans continue to practice age-old trades. Others have been restored to their former state, like the series of shophouses at the Tanjong Pagar Conservation Area. For an authentic taste of Chinese culture, try visiting a teahouse, then take a peek into a typical middle-class Chinese home in the 1920s at the Chinaman Scholar\''s Gallery. Crowded streets throb with people, especially just before Chinese New Year, when Chinese opera and lion dances add to the festivity. Do not forget to visit the eclectic mix of mosques and temples while you are here—the serene Nagore Dargha Shrine, the elaborate Sri Mariamman Temple and the grand Thian Hock Keng Temple are just a few. You will be delighted to find that this is perhaps the only neighborhood in the city where places of worship of several religions stand harmoniously next to each other along the same street.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Kampong Glam</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">With its top draw being the Sultan Mosque, this is the repository of culture for Singapore\''s Malay community. Visitors can stop by the Malay Heritage Centre at the Istana Kampong Glam and take a stroll around Singapore\''s oldest Malay cemetery. Shopping here is a refreshing change from the glitzy malls of Orchard Road, with stores selling everything from Malay, Indonesian and Middle Eastern merchandise to trendy one-of-a-kind boutiques. Stroll down Haji Lane, Bussorah Street, and Arab Lane and you\''re sure to take home some unique finds. During the holy month of Ramadan this district is at its charming best; a feast for the senses await as streets are lined with stalls offering a variety of specialties and night markets set up shop, offering a plethora of wares.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Little India</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">A riot of color, particularly on Sundays and during major Hindu festivals, like Thaipusam and Deepavali. Awash with scents and sights that transport you to India, this is where everything needed by an Indian household is found. Traces of Hinduism are seen everywhere, from the embellished Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple to pictures of Hindu deities. Mustafa Centre sells just about anything you need under one roof and is a haven for bargain hunters.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sentosa</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Sentosa promises an enjoyable time for all ages. This island dubbed \''the State of Fun,\'' is a short 15-minute ride from the city center and is accessible via public transport. From living the cinematic experience at Universal Studios to discovering the wonders of the ocean at S.E.A. Aquarium, and thrilling at the rides at Adventure Cove Waterpark, there\''s plenty to do here. After a busy day, you can head to  Quayside Isle for some well-deserved R&R. With its theme parks, historic sites, pristine beaches, spas and adventure sports, there\''s sure to be something on Sentosa to pique your interest.</div>\r\n\r\n<br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
