 (1981,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theaters</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Stockholm\''s theatrical community is characterized by three main sections: state-subsidised theaters, privately operated theaters, and independent theater companies. The state-subsidised theaters typically have a large and varied selection of classics, dramas, comedies, and children\''s theatre on offer. The Stockholm City Theater, housed in the enormous Cultural Center at Sergels Torg, is a prime example of this with its seven stages. There are performances here from early morning until late at night, catering to all tastes and ages. The best place to catch celebrities is probably the Royal Dramatic Theater at Nybroplan, however. Ingmar Bergman left an indelible mark on this theatrical institution, and while The Stockholm City Theatre is more modern and populist, The Royal Dramatic Theatre offers an exclusive atmosphere and royal boxes.Privately operated theatres have higher ticket prices, lots of chartered buses coming in from all over Sweden, and a repertoire of musicals and farces. The beautiful Oscarsteatern with its long theatrical history, has been at the centre of much controversy lately because of acrimonious disputes over changes of ownership, but the theater and the productions are generally magnificent and lavish, with strong casts and award-winning productions. The latter is equally true of Chinateatern at Berzelii Park and Cirkus on Djurgården. Intiman and Maxim are sure bets if you are in the mood for a farce, and Göta Lejon has also staged productions worth seeing over the years.Independent theatre companies typically offer rather reasonable ticket prices and are often home to a more experimental staging by young, hot directors and actors. Among the better known companies are Teater Galeasen and Teater Plaza, where names like Thorsten Flinck, Mikael Persbrandt, Simon Norrthon, and Stefan Larsson often appear on the programs.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Operas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Stockholm opera scene is dominated by two stages: the Royal Opera and the Folkopera. The same comparison applies here as between The Royal Dramatic Theatre and The Stockholm City Theatre. The Royal Opera is fancy and fairly traditional whereas The Folkopera is younger, fresher, and more modern. The great divas appear at The Royal Opera, and the upcoming opera stars of tomorrow at The Folkopera. Both are well worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinemas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you prefer cinematic Hollywood entertainment, downtown Stockholm has a lot to offer. Along the route from Hötorget to Stureplan, you will find Filmstaden Sergel, Saga, and Rigoletto practically next door to one another. On Sveavägen, there is the Grand, and in Söder, you\''ll find the offerings of Filmstaden Söder, Biopalatset, and Victoria. The suburbs also have their fair share of Hollywood blockbuster cinemas, of course. For those who prefer a more original cinematic repertoire, one place to go is Zita on Birger Jarlsgatan. Sture also has a great deal to offer to those who have had enough of American box office hits. The non-Swedish-speaking visitor will be pleased to hear that foreign films in Sweden are shown in the original language with Swedish subtitles. The one exception to this is in children\''s movies, which are usually dubbed into Swedish. Even with children\''s movies, however, you may find that there are two versions available, subtitled or dubbed. This is especially likely with the major Disney movies, and it could be well worth your while to check with the box office.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Stockholm has a lot to offer to those in the mood for more cultural exposure. Djurgården is an excellent first stop. The dramatic reconstruction of the war ship Vasa, which sank in the Stockholm harbour on its maiden voyage, is a truly impressive sight at Vasamuséet, a highly recommended attraction for visitors of all ages. Close by is the magnificent Nordiska Muséet, which has been mistaken by many a visitor for a royal palace with all its towers and spires. Waldemarsudde is a must for art lovers, and the Museum of Maritime History is a boat lover\''s dream. Skansen is not just a zoological park but also a reserve for historic architecture and crafts. Visitors to Stockholm should definitely put several hours aside for all the wonderful sights here. Next to Skansen is the Biological Museum, which specializes in displays taxidermy animals in their natural habitats.If you are the least bit interested in history, a visit to the Museum of Medieval History is an experience you will not soon forget. There, you can learn all about the history of Stockholm through the centuries of the Middle Ages, and the displays are usually of very high quality. The Swedish Museum of Natural History is a bit off the beaten track out by The University of Stockholm, but it is well worth the effort of taking a bus or the metro to see all the fantastic exhibits and installations. While here, don\''t miss out on the omniplex films where you can learn more about the cosmos or the Egypt of Pharaohs. Fans of sculpture should definitely make a point of visiting the amazing Millesgården. Färgfabriken by Liljeholmen also has a lot to offer, in both sculpture and modern art. In the latter category, a visit to the Museum of Modern Art is another obvious choice.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Concert Hall at Hötorget offers a sterling repertoire of classical music. Berwaldhallen, home to The Swedish Radio Symphony, is also highly recommended with its unique acoustic design of beautiful natural wood. For jazz and blues lovers, Fasching and Stampen are the top choices, but many of Stockholm\''s bars and pubs offer musical entertainment of their own in this genre, especially on weekends. The major pop and rock concerts are usually held at the Ericsson Globe Arena, Cirkus, the stadium, or the concert hall.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Stockholm\''s undisputed nightlife hub is the area between Kungsträdgården and Stureplan. This is where you\''ll find the hottest clubs and bars. In Kungsträdgården, Café Opera is the ultimate nightlife attraction, but Victoria is also very popular. If you prefer local pub life, Söder is the place to go. Söders Hjärta is a safe bet. Vasastan also has a number of good pubs and bars, such as Cliff Barnes and Storstad. Or why not explore the huge selection of whiskeys and genuine British pub atmosphere of the little known but very congenial Bishop\''s Arms on St. Eriksgatan. Stockholm is a fun loving city with more than enough nightlife to keep any visitor entertained.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1982,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Norrmalm (City)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Stockholm wears many beautiful faces, and each area of the city is delightfully distinctive. Centralen, for example, is a typical downtown area with traffic jams and bustling crowds. Take the subway a couple stations and spot modern, daring architecture, such as the City Library a few blocks north of the Rådmansgatan subway station and the Cultural Centre at T-Centralen. Go through Kungsträdgården, The King\''s Garden, and walk over the bridge to cozy little Skeppsholmen, popping into Moderna Museet or Skeppsholmen\''s church. You can even take a ferry out to the magical archipelago and you will still be, geographically at least, within the borders of Stockholm.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Östermalm & Djurgården</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Östermalm is the most elegant part of town and where some of the city\''s most impressive buildings are found. Notably, Östermalms Saluhall should not be missed! You can also head alongside the water and over the bridge to Djurgården, a lovely island ideal for walks and picnics, and visit Skansen or the famous Gröna Lund amusement park.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Södermalm</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The south side of town, Södermalm, is also worth seeing. In the late 1800s, this area was home to Stockholm\''s working class. Returning home from long, hard days by the ships, workers used to stop for drinks at the area\''s local taverns. This image of Södermalm as the home of the bohemian workers, of genuine pub culture and socializing has been preserved. In fact, more cafés, galleries and pubs are found here than in any other part of town. A lot of small, funky stores featuring local artists\'' and designers\'' works are also to be found in this area, as well as at the summer Mynttorget street-festivals. At Vita Bergen, you canenjoy performances both in theater and song. Overall, it is here in Södermalm that you will experience a creative, urban Stockholm.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Gamla Stan (The Old Town)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If Södermalm is cultural Stockholm, then Gamla Stan is genuine Stockholm. It is still the city\''s pride and joy. Cobbled streets and narrow, 17th-century alleys—the smallest one being just over 26 inches wide— create a unique atmosphere here. Don\''t forget to look up at the impressive old church, Storkyrkan, while exploring. The area\''s old houses all feature ambitious decor and ornaments. If you turned back the clock by about 700 years this is what all of Stockholm would look like. A lot has happened since, one example being the construction of the Royal Castle. Unfortunately, members of the royal family no longer live here, and Drottningholm now serves as their home. Stroll through the lovely gardens, admire the water, and appreciate the history of the diverse Swedish capital from its unmissable Old Town.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
