 (1991,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater, Opera & Ballet</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">What could be better than a show after dinner? If opera or ballet is your thing, spend a night under the gorgeous ceiling fresco in the majestic Opera House. If you prefer live theater, there are numerous small independent companies, or try the Altes Schauspielhaus, opened in 1909, Drei Groschentheater, a small theater showing mostly 20th-century plays, or Thtr Rmpe, which focuses exclusively on plays by young German playwrights.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you\''re interested in cinema, look to the Delphi and Atelier for top European productions. English speaking guests may be happy to learn that Corso shows Hollywood films in English.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cabaret & Musicals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For lively cabaret, you can\''t beat the Renitenz, with its political satire or the humorous Theater der Altstadt. The list goes on, of course, with most everything people do on stages to be found somewhere in the city, even first rate puppetry at FITS - Figurentheater. Another venue that promises excellent entertainment is the SI-Centrum, hosting acclaimed musicals.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Clubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you like the nightlife, after dark in Stuttgart can be loud and long. The clubs have a good mix of modern music and are a great way to mingle with locals. A mainstay in Stuttgart discos is House and Hip Hop music; if that\''s your thing, check out ClimaX Institutes, Perkins Park, or ProTon for a lively night out. Stuttgart clubs run from small to huge, and several offer two, three, or even four separate dance floors to accommodate a range of musical tastes. Kings Club is popular on the LGBTQ scene. To round it out, check out Toy for techno beats.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (1992,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">City Center</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The city is situated in a valley which is open on one side. From the center of town, one is surrounded by picturesque vineyards and slopes in almost every direction. Due to its unique topographical site, the city has a distinctly southern flair. Green parks spread from Neues Schloss to Höhenpark Killesberg. You will seldom find gardens of this size in other large cities, although there are also a great deal of pedestrian walkways for visitors to explore. Königstraße is the main shopping street, but Calwer Straße, with houses dating from between the 17th and 20th Centuries, is an elegant and historically interesting location. The beautiful Altes Schloss and Neus Schloss are situated side by side in the city center, and the Schlossplatz, Schillerplatz and Markthalle are only some of the attractions you will pass whilst just strolling around the center. Cafeterias, restaurants and snack bars are on almost every corner. Those on the search for drink and history will appreciate Calwer-Eck-Brau (Stuttgart\''s first local brewery), located on Calwer Straße. Here, the beer on tap is always brewed on-site.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bohnenviertel</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This district gets its name from the bean gardens that once grew in the area. At one time, beans formed the staple diet of the lower classes, so there are many stories and tales about these beans and their uses. Around the end of the 19th Century, these gardens were developed into real estate, but the area retained the same name. It is the most distinctive district, with plenty of wine taverns and pubs. Bohnenviertel\''s residents know and love Stuttgart, and the district is packed full of insiders who are experts on the city. The shops in this area also fit the town\''s character; they are original and really quite extraordinary.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bad Cannstatt</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Bad Cannstatt is Stuttgart\''s biggest and oldest suburb. Thanks to its rich supply of mineral water, it used to be a world-famous spa where kings and emperors met. Even today, it is a very attractive district with a long and interesting history, good shops, spas of course, and a great deal to offer those seeking ways to spend their leisure time. It is the home of the Wilhelma, a zoo and botanical garden, as well as the boarding point for boat rides down the Neckar. By the way, if you ask the locals where they come from, the answer will always be \"Bad Cannstatt\" and never \"Stuttgart.\"</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Degerloch</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A favorite residential area, the name of this district comes from <em>teger</em> and <em>lohe</em>, which means \"thick forest.\" There are many beautiful paths for walks, and more than a handful of sports facilities, especially in the woods around the Fernsehturm. If you are keen on trying an alternative way of reaching Degerloch, you should take a ride on the rack railway, the Zahnradbahn. It leaves from the center of trendy Marienplatz and ends up at Degerloch Station.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Möhringen</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Just like Degerloch, this is a heavily residential area that is located south of the city. First documented in 1100 CE, Möhringen has a small town center, but became very famous due to the SI-Erlebnis-Centrum, which stages world famous musicals. Besides the many high-quality restaurants and bars, SI-Erlebnis-Centrum also hosts the Schwaben-Quellen, a spa complex, and Spielbank Stuttgart, a casino.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Killesberg</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Stuttgart\''s most noble and elegant district, it is here that one can find villas with a truly stunning view of the city. From the viewing tower in Höhenpark Killesberg, visitors can gaze upon the vineyards, which wind down to the city center and then connect to the parks in the downtown area. A very exclusive and quiet residential district, many prominent citizens of the past and present have flocked to live here. In fact, Theodor Heuss, the first president of the Federal Republic of Germany, and the Porsche family have called Killesberg home. It goes without saying that the prices for renting or buying property in the area are sky high. The Theodor-Heuss-Haus and Weissenhof Estate are attractions that should be on every visitor\''s list.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Rotenberg</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the oldest wine-producing communities in the Neckar area, Rotenberg still has its own authentic, charming character. From here, you have a glorious view of the surrounding vineyards and the neighboring village of Uhlbach. Those who love nature and have a strong interest in wine will be thrilled by the information boards posted along the walking paths, which offer details about the wines of the region. Further area highlights are Grabkapelle and Weinbaumuseum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Untertürkheim</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This area is located in the eastern part of the city and was first documented in 1100 CE as Durinkheim. Originally wine-making country, Daimler Motor Company started to build the first motorcars here in 1904, making Untertürkheim famous. The Mercedes Benz Museum is absolutely worth a trip, even if you are not a \"car person.\"</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Stuttgart-West</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The western part of town is the biggest one due to the fact that it accommodates the inner city. It was only in the period after 1870 that development on a massive scale began. Characteristic in this district are long, straight roads and lots of churches. Here you will find some wonderful, old buildings, lots of alternative pubs, and a young, urban scene.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
