 (2092,'<div class=\"OverviewText\">A city where canals are streets and taxis are boats, Venice is truly unique. From the three-kilometer (two-mile) stretch of the Grand Canal to the remote outlying islands, Venice is choc-a-block full of attractions to explore on foot or by water. The city\''s main artery, the Grand Canal lined with aristocratic houses and beautiful historic churches stretches in an \''s\'' shape; often exploring on foot is a lot faster (and cheaper) than taking a gondola or water taxi.  A crisscrossing network of canals connected by bridges intersect through the city, and many of the noble villas open directly out onto the water, complete with a landing dock for boats.Venice\''s <em>Centro Storico </em>or<em> </em>Historic Quarter is divided into six districts or <em>sestieri </em>connected by a labyrinthine maze of canals, palaces, and bridges. These districts include the following:</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
