 (2098,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art and Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Venice is a cultural powerhouse and many of its major landmarks double up as museums where you can get a glimpse of the city\''s fascinating past as well as its artistic lineage. Among the top choices, the Gallerie dell\''accademia is a treasure trove of Venetian art while the grand Palazzo Ducale takes you back to another era, and the Peggy Guggenheim Collection showcases some of the best modern art in the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals, Concerts and Events</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">One of the largest and most famous festivals in the world, Carnival is when Venice leaps to life. This glorious masked ball sees events organized through the city and a festive air that\''s hard to beat. Fun, games, concerts and other events draw visitors from around the world, looking to experience the magic of this festival rooted in centuries of tradition. The Biennale d\''arte Contemporanea and Architettura is a contemporary festival established in 1895 that celebrates innovations in these fields and invites artists from around the globe to participate and spotlight their work among their peers. Every year, the city welcomes the creme-de-la-creme of the cinema world during the Venice International Film Festival. This 11-day event sees screens set up at venues around the city and season passes are available to watch titles vying for the coveted Golden Lion. Jazz enthusiasts will love the Veneto Jazz festival that brings together international talent from big-name artists to up-and-coming performers on one stage. The festival is held at venues across the city.For a glimpse of traditional Venice, the Regata Storica, a colorful boat racing event along the Grand Canal is a truly thrilling sight.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater and Opera</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The stunning Teatro La Fenice, one of the landmarks of Italian Theater, is a glorious ode to the city\''s love affair with the arts. Here, renowned artists take to the stage and enchant theatergoers with their soaring sopranos, flair for drama and captivating stories. The Scuola Grande dei Carmini and Scuola Grande di San Rocco  also host a variety of classical music and ballet performances through the year. Venice\''s historic churches and public squares also host a number of performances through the year from chamber orchestra\''s to opera and jazz. Listening to beautiful arias under the gilded domes of a historic church is one of the most atmospheric experiences one can have in the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With a centuries-old crafts traditions, Venice\''s alleyways and islands are host to some of the most beautiful works available for purchase. Along the city center, you\''ll find more than your fair share of name-brand and designer shops for the fashion conscious, but those looking to purchase something more unique may have to dig a little deeper. Local boutiques and antique stores abound, and are filled with glass art from Murano, the iconic papier-mache Venetian masks, hand carved artifacts, linens and lace, and handmade jewelry. Of course, all of this comes at a price, and if you\''re on a tight budget, then you\''ll find the usual souvenir shops a dime a dozen for a quick, cheerful buy.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Venice\''s nightlife is of the more restrained variety, choosing cozy wine bars and jazz lounges over thumping electro music. For a post dinner coffee on Piazza San Marco, Caffè Florian with its neo-baroque interiors and 18th-century charm is a top choice. For some of the best wine in the city, in a convivial space catered to locals, head to Enoteca Mascareta. For jazz lovers, few things beat a night at Venice Jazz Club, where drinks and jazz standards go hand in hand.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2099,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">San Marco</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Characterized by the stunning piazza, or public square, and the monumental basilica of the same name, San Marco is home to some of Venice\''s most iconic attractions like the St Mark\''s Clocktower, Doge\''s Palace, and Teatro La Fenice. The winding streets fanning outwards from the piazza towards the Rialto Bridge are full of upscale boutiques and designer fashion, nestled alongside gorgeous churches and chic cafes serving glasses of the best Italian wines.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cannaregio</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Cannaregio is the largely residential neighborhood to the north of Venice that extends from the Grand Canal to San Marco. This neighborhood, home to the city\''s historic Jewish Quarter, is characterized by tranquil bylanes, traditional homes, and a vibrant nightlife area frequented by a local crowd around the Cannaregio Canal. You can visit the The Church of Madonna dell\''orto or the charming Ponte delle Guglie. For a taste of old-fashioned Venetian cooking, Osteria Al Bacco is an excellent choice.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Castello</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A neighborhood with many facets, Castello stretches from the crowded tourist area to the Giardini Gardens in the east. Strolls along Via Garibaldi, visits to Museo Storico Navale, and sunny afternoon visits to Giardini are just a few things to do in this beautiful neighborhood.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Dorsoduro</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">To Venice\''s west, lies the youthful neighborhood of Dorsoduro. Known for its student population, the area is packed full of fun bars and cafes that spill onto busy piazzas till late into the night. On weekends the area around the Santa Margherita is especially lively. The younger population also means there are other alternative things to do here, like visit modern galleries highlighting up-and-coming young artists and designers. Art enthusiasts shouldn\''t miss the Peggy Guggenheim Collection found here.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">San Polo and Santa Croce</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">At the base of the Rialto bridge, lie the bustling markets offer a plethora of sights and sounds for the curious visitor to explore. From picking up fresh produce to enjoying an espresso in one of the many cafes around the bridge, and plenty of people-watching, San Polo is a glimpse of Venice from a local perspective. The glorious Basilica Santa Maria Gloriosa dei Frari is a must-visit for those exploring the neighborhood.Apart from the six historic districts, Venice\''s charm extends past the main island.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Lido</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">An island bordered by a long strip of resort-covered sandy beaches, the Lido is great for those who want a break from the crowded, historic center and simply unwind by the beach. Located between the Venice Lagoon and the Adriatic, the Lido offers, sun, sand and campari to visitors. Cycle along the Lungomare or enjoy a feast at one of the many family-run restaurants on the island, Lido promises an authentic Italian experience.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outlying Islands</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Venice\''s outlying islands offer promise. From buying traditional ceramics and marveling at mosaics on Torcello to watching master craftsman create art works from red-hot glass on Murano and watching centuries-old fishing traditions on colorful Burano, there is plenty to keep you occupied if you have the time for a day trip from the city center. Don\''t miss out on purchasing the fabulous handmade lace on Burano or a glass souvenir from Murano.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
