 (2137,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">According to the Austrian writer Karl Kraus, the streets of Vienna are \"paved with culture.\" Its multitude of museums bears testament to Vienna\''s penchant for all things cultural while the outstanding historic architecture of the Naturhistorische Museum and the Kunsthistorische Museum reinforce the city\''s proud artistic legacy. Both are worthy of note and their prominent location at the Ringstraße makes them easily accessible as well. The KunstHausWien is the antithesis of classical museums, designed by the famous Austrian painter and sculptor Friedensreich Hundertwasser. The building itself is quite inspiring, as are the exhibitions held here, featuring mostly 20th-century modern art. The Museumsquartier also boasts a couple of small galleries that feature photographic exhibitions. A classic is the Belvedere gallery showcasing some of Austria\''s most valuable paintings, such as Klimt\''s <em>The Kiss</em>.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Burgtheater is not only Austria\''s national theater but is also one of the world\''s most prominent German theaters and Vienna\''s prime venue for the performing arts.  In contrast, the 19th-century Volkstheater hosts traditional performances alongside new interpretations of classic and modern literature for a wider audience than that catered to by the classical Burgtheater. The Theater in der Josefstadt is another popular venue, and the city\''s oldest, still running theater, originally established in 1788. For theatrical performances in English, head to Vienna\''s acclaimed English Theatre for vibrant renditions of American classics, comedy, thrillers and contemporary works. The English Theater is not only one of the city\''s most favored destinations for the performing arts but is also the oldest English-language theater in continental Europe. The satirical cabaret shows staged across the city are also quite enjoyable; the Ronacher is a great place to catch one of these.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Classical Music & Opera</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Classical music is still the soundtrack for Viennese culture; a legacy that is so deeply embedded in the fabric of the city that strains of melodious symphonies seem to pervade every corner. The Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra and the Vienna Mozart Orchestra regularly perform at the Musikverein - a legendary venue that is said to have the best acoustics of any concert hall in Austria, if not in the world. Just a stone\''s throw away is the Konzerthaus, which boasts the capacity to stage up to three performances simultaneously, while the Schönbrunn Palace hosts outdoor classical concerts each summer. Visitors to Vienna should not miss a night at the world famous Staatsoper (State Opera), oft ranked among the world\''s top five opera houses. Another popular venue for opera is the Volksoper (People\''s Opera), whose repertoire includes operettas and musicals.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">In Concert</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">While the city\''s taste for classical music is one that is world renown, Vienna also hosts live music performances featuring more contemporary genres. Within walking distance of each other, the Chelsea and the Rhiz are top choices for rock and alternative performances by both international artists and local bands. On the other hand, Jazzland is one of Vienna\''s few real jazz clubs. The Radiokulturhaus also hosts international jazz musicians while large-scale concerts by pop ensembles are often featured at the Stadthalle.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Some say Vienna is the old-fashioned capital of a small country. Its nightlife, however, suggests otherwise. Everything from cozy bars for an intimate tête-à-tête to a huge clubs for a night of dancing can be found here. The most popular nightlife district is the so-called Bermuda Triangle—the area around Ruprechtsplatz, Seitenstettengasse, Rabensteig and Salzgries. There you will find bars such as First Floor, pubs like the Krah-Krah and live-music venues such as Der Neue Engel. The club scene is spread out in Vienna; at places like Volksgarten or U4, you will find a young crowd dancing to commercial house and mainstream music. Lastly, at Flex, the accent is on independent music, hip-hop, drum and bass, trip-hop and all sorts of electronic tunes, Viennese style.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Film</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinemas in Vienna screen mainly Hollywood productions, including the latest U.S. releases, sometimes with a short delay. Films are generally dubbed, but exceptions do exist. There is an annual film festival, the Viennale, which features a wide range of international films as well as local productions. Cinemas screening more niche genres can also be found - the Votiv or the Filmcasino screen mainly independent films.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Vienna Extraordinaire</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Prater, the extraordinary amusement park with its gigantic Ferris wheel, also featured in the film <em>Before Sunrise</em>, is a place that appeals to the young at heart. Enjoy traditional food from the many stalls, or give one of the dizzying rides a whirl if you\''re up for a thrill.The Spanish Riding School (<em>Spanische Hofreitschule</em>) is another uniquely Viennese attraction that hosts performances by the famous snow-white Lipizzaner stallions.With origins that date back to 1498, the Vienna Boys\'' Choir (Wiener Sängerknaben), sings every Sunday at the Burgkapelle (Royal Chapel) in Hofburg. Over 500 years hence, their concerts are still considered by many to be a quintessentially Viennese experience.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2138,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">1st District: Innere Stadt</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This is the central, most elegant and one of the most expensive of Vienna\''s districts. Splendid boutiques, luxury hotels, popular cafés such as the Demel, the Burgtheater, the State Opera and a vast majority of the historic monuments are all located in the Innere Stadt (inner city). This area is also the home of many important politicians and the Austrian President. Here you will find medieval Vienna: old houses, narrow cobbled streets and romantic squares where Mozart\''s symphonies seem to resound. Right through the 1st District runs Kärntner Straße, a pedestrian zone and shopping boulevard that is anchored by the State Opera at one end and Stephansdom at the other.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">2nd District: Leopoldstadt</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"><p dir=\"ltr\">Leopoldstadt, the city\''s 2nd District, is separated from the center of Vienna by the Danube Canal and, along with the 20th District, Brigittenau, forms a misshapen island bordered to the east by the main arm of the canal. For the most part, this area is a residential suburb only redeemed by the Prater, the vast city park with its funfair, the Augarten, and the Wiener Kriminalmuseum. Between 1600 and 1939, Leopoldstadt was the center of Vienna\''s Jewish community. In the mid-19th Century, thousands of Jews took the opportunity to leave Bohemia, Moravia, Hungary, and Galicia and migrate to the capital of the Habsburg Empire. The Strauss family, Sigmund Freud, Gustav Mahler, Arthur Schnitzler and Theodor Herzl all lived here at some point, before upgrading to the city\''s wealthier suburbs.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">3rd District: Landstraße</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Vienna\''s 3rd District lies to the east and southeast of the Innere Stadt, framed to the east by the Danube Canal (<em>Donaukanal</em>), and to the west by Prinz-Eugen-Straße and Arsenalstrasse. It is a predominantly working-class neighborhood. The one exception is the diplomatic quarter close to Schwarzenbergplatz and around the extraordinary rococo palace Belvedere. Here you will also find the Hundertwasserhaus, a colorful, architectural masterpiece, and the St. Marx Cemetery, Mozart\''s final resting place.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">4th District: Wieden</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">In Wieden, situated between Karlsplatz, Wienzeile and Gürtel, the atmosphere is more splendid than in the neighboring 3rd District. The 4th is one of the more well-presented residential suburbs close to the city center. Here, you will find Radiokulturhaus, the Vienna Museum of History, and the Naschmarkt, Vienna\''s biggest and most exciting market.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">5th District: Margareten</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Margareten lies next to Wieden between Gürtel and Wienzeile and is mostly a working-class suburb. There aren\''t very many attractions in this district, besides the Filmcasino.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">6th & 7th Districts: Mariahilf & Neubau</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Between Wienzeile and Lerchenfelderstrasse, Ringstrasse and Gürtel you will find the districts of Mariahilf and Neubau, divided by Vienna\''s biggest shopping boulevard, the Mariahilferstrasse. Once home to several warehouses and beautiful patrician mansions, the neighborhood fell into a state of despair when housing conditions deteriorated in the 1950s and property values fell. Today, the 6th and the 7th Districts offer the busiest nightlife in town; the old warehouses have been transformed into fashionable studios and apartments, chic bars, and dazzling nightclubs.  The 6th district is also home to the Vienna State Opera and the flea market on Wienzeile that takes place every Saturday.<p dir=\"ltr\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">8th & 9th Districts: Josefstadt & Alsergrund</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Between Ringstraße and Gürtel, lie the districts of Josefstadt and Alsergrund, two very nice residential areas with large patrician houses. Many wealthy Viennese, who prefer to live in the city center and not in a villa outside of town, have flats here. The main attractions are the Theater in der Josefstadt, the Volksoper, and the Sigmund Freud Museum.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">10th, 11th & 12th Districts: Favoriten, Simmering & Meidling</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The only significant sight in these districts south of the Gürtel is the Zentralfriedhof in the outskirts of Simmering. Generally speaking, these are working-class suburbs dominated by flat buildings, ranging from 1920s tenement housing to the huge project-type blocks of the 1980s and 1990s.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">13th District: Hietzing</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This area of town is a pleasant suburb west of the 5th district with splendid villas and gardens, ranging from the Biedermeier summer residences (enjoyed by the 19th-century nobility) to the Art Nouveau Jugendstil and modernist villas favored by the successful artists and businessmen of the late-imperial era. Here, you will find the famous Cafe Dommayer, Schloss Schönbrunn and the Lainzer Tiergarten - the former imperial hunting ground that is nowadays Vienna\''s second largest park.<p dir=\"ltr\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">14th, 15th & 16th Districts: Rudolfsheim & Ottakring</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The patrician houses of the 15th and 16th Districts, situated between the Gürtel and the Wienerwald, west of the city center, were all built at the same time as the Ringstraße; but today, housing conditions are very poor. Nevertheless, amid the hills of Ottakring, you will find some beautiful old villas, including Schloss Wilhelminenberg.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">17th, 18th & 19th Districts: Hernals, Währing & Döbling</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Beyond the Gürtel and towards the Vienna Woods north of the center, the villas get bigger, the surroundings greener and the streets more splendid the further you go. In these districts, you will have ample opportunities for relaxing walks in the woods, and also find beautiful <em>Heurigen</em> (traditional Austrian wine taverns), especially in Grinzing and Neustift am Walde. Vienna\''s greatest and most beautiful public swimming pool, the Krapfenwaldlbad, is situated in Döbling and offers a wonderful view over the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">20th District: Brigittenau</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Named after the 17th-century Brigittakapelle, much of the land on which this district sits was claimed from the Donau River after its containment in 1870. Around 1900, the 20th District was divided off of the larger 2nd District to become Vienna\''s last. Brigittenau lacks the historical attractions of many of the other districts, but is home to the high-rise spectacle that is the Millennium Tower, and Hannover Market.<p dir=\"ltr\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">21st, 22nd & 23rd District: Floridsdorf, Donaustadt & Liesing</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Viennese call the districts Floridsdorf and Donaustadt Transdanubien (beyond the Danube) because they are situated on the other side of the riverbank, east of the city center. Here, you will find Vienna\''s most popular recreational area, the Donauinsel. This is a very narrow, very long, artificial island in the river Danube—a paradise for rollerblading, cycling, jogging and walking. Liesing, which sits to the south of the city center, is huge with its small detached houses, council block buildings and some fine wine bars. Villages such as Mauer and Atzgersdorf are part of the 23rd district. They are so rural that it is sometimes hard to believe you are still in Vienna.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
