 (2427,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Most of Heidelberg\''s museums are centrally located, close to the Hauptstraße, within easy walking distance of each other. Among the many cultural offerings, the Heidelberg University, Germany\''s oldest university, is home to several unique venues like the Antikenmuseum, the University-Museum, the Studentenkarzer (a historic prison especially for students), and the Universitätsbibliothek (university library).  Heidelberg\''s iconic castle is also home to the one-of-a-kind Deutsches Apotheker Museum which showcases the history of pharmacy, while the castle itself has historic rooms and exhibitions complete with period furniture. Further on the Schlossberg you will find the Carl-Bosch-Museum, located in the former house of the eponymous Nobel Prize winner. For those who are interested in art, the Heidelberger Kunstverein and the Museum Haus Cajeth offer contemporary art, whereas the Museum der sakralen specializes in religious art. A wide thematic range from archaeology to the history of the town, paintings and sculptures to arts and crafts is presented in the Kurpfälzische Museum. Heidelberg also boasts an ethnological museum, the Völkerkundemuseum.   Specialty museums abound in the city. These include the Deutsches Verpackungsmuseum, where you can see classical German packing. The University\''s Botanischen Garten (botanical garden) in the Neuenheimer Feld and a little outside the town, the Bonsai-Museum and Textilmuseum Max Berk. The HeidelbergCard offers you free entry in a bulk of the museums and free use of Public transport within Heidelberg.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A cultural powerhouse, Heidelberg has a number of theaters for every taste, largely attributed to the university and its students. The Theater der Stadt Heidelberg, the municipal theater, offers a standard program of dramas, operas, and dance performances. In addition, it hosts the <em>Heidelberger Stückemarkt</em> and in summer the theater festival in the Castle, the <em>Schlossfestspiele</em>. The theater has a section for children and young adults, the Zwinger 3, that offers a special program for this age group.  Beside the municipal theater, Heidelberg has several private venues including a dance theater, a theater in the university and a variety of cultural theaters. The annual <em>Dance international </em>- an international dance festival - is hosted by the Unterwegs-Theater, a dance company. The Zimmertheater, the second oldest private theater in Germany, has an excellent lineup of performances. They play modern dramas; largely European or German plays. For more than 10 years, an amateur theater in an old factory, the Taeter Theater has produced modern and unconventional dramas. In the Old Town, the Volksbühne hosts community productions and an orchestra. The faculty for languages at the University has its own \"basement\" theater, the Romanischer Keller, that performs for an audience of students and other patrons. For an alternative theater experience, the Tikk-Theater in the Karlstorbahnhof is an unconventional pick.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Besides theater, art and museums, Heidelberg also has a variety of nightlife options on offer. Like everything else in Heidelberg, bars are largely concentrated in the Old Town, on the Untere Straße (Lower Street) to be precise, below the Holy Ghost Church. Bars cater to the student population, as well as an eclectic clientele of businessmen, tourists, and other patrons. Bars like Sonder Bar are among the popular options. If you prefer gigs of the independent variety, Karlstorbahnhof hosts a series of monthly disco events like the alternative Chop Suey Club and Brit-pop oriented Rollercoaster. Halle 02, which is located on the other side of the rail tracks at Heidelberg Hauptbahnhof, is most popular for student parties, art exhibitions and concerts. If jazz is your thing, then Cave 54 is definitely the place to be, also known as the oldest student bar in Heidelberg. If you feel your left-of-center spirit emerging, check out Villa Nachttanz, which is conveniently located near the tracks of the S-Bahn in Pfaffengrund/Wieblingen; punk parties, goth gigs in an abandoned house, a garden with regular bonfires and the cheapest beer around — what more do you need?</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinemas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Most of the cinemas are located in Heidelberg\''s city center or nearby. Those who are interested in the latest movies and the standard program can opt for one of the big multiplexes while in smaller theaters like the Gloria & Gloriette; they screen independent and alternative films. The award-winning cinema, especially noted for its children\''s program, lays its emphasis on European cinema. In October and November the International Movie Festival Mannheim-Heidelberg is organized each year, drawing cinephiles to the city, while in summer (June-August) the Gloria cinema organizes the popular Open-Air-Cinema event in the Neuenheimer Feld. The Karlstorbahnhof offers cultural movies from all over the world—mostly in their original language with subtitles.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Heidelberg has an eclectic array of festivals through the year, starting with the Heidelberg Spring, a lively music festival and the Heidelberger Stückemarkt, a drama festival in the start of the year. Later on, the Heidelberg Castle Festival takes place in summer, followed by the Heidelberg Fall Festival, and the Heidelberg Christmas Market. These festivals represent the city\''s vibrant character and invite visitors to experience firsthand the city\''s multifaceted and lively nature.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2428,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Altstadt (Old Town)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With its magnificent backdrop and narrow, picturesque roads, the Old Town is perhaps the most frequented destination in Heidelberg. This area extends to about two kilometers (one and a quarter miles) on both sides of the lively Hauptstraße from Bismarckplatz in the west along the south bank of the river Neckar and to the foot of the famous Schloss (Castle). The castle sits majestically enthroned on a small plateau above the river and town. Other important locations include the Universitätsplatz (University place), the Marktplatz (Market place) and the Alte Brücke (Old bridge). Most of Heidelberg\''s museums are to be found in the Old Town, along with theaters, cinemas, and countless restaurants and pubs. Heidelberg University, the oldest in Germany and one of the oldest in the world, offers various short-term and long-term courses in different fields.  The whole of Old Town can be discovered easily and pleasantly on foot. However, if you are driving down, the city center offers ample parking space. Walking is particularly recommended during the months of November and December when the famous Heidelberg Christmas Market or when the Heidelberg Castle Festival takes place to avoid traffic jams.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Schlierbach, Ziegelhausen & Bergheim</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Neckar valley leads upstream to the east. Schlierbach lies here on the southern side. It was first documented in 1245 as having hardly more than 3,000 inhabitants and even today, it is arguably the smallest district in Heidelberg. Located in northern Heidelberg, Ziegelhausen was founded in 850 CE. It is beautifully situated between the Neckar meadows and the Odenwald Forest, and is a fantastic starting point for hiking-tours. The Textile Museum Max Berk and the Benedictine cloister Stift Neuburg are both popular visitors\'' choices.  West of the Old town and castle, between the Kurfürsten-Anlage and the Neckar, the district Bergheim reaches from the Bismarckplatz in the center to the motorway. In 769, Bergheim had already been mentioned as an independent settlement, but in 1392, the inhabitants were resettled within Heidelberg\''s town walls. The area was only built up again in the 19th Century, characterized by institutes and the university hospital, small businesses, and residential premises.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Weststadt, Rohrbach, Boxberg & Emmertsgrund</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">South of Bergheim lies the Weststadt, with its beautiful old facades. It is a district much in demand amongst potential house buyers today. To the west of it, you will find the main railway station. It is only recently, since 1935, that the Südstadt has developed and expanded. It now joins the Weststadt to the Mark-Twain-Village and the NATO Headquarters, with the former village Rohrbach to its south. Rohrbach had already been documented as early as 766 CE. and, like Heidelberg itself, suffered damage in the Thirty Years War and the French-Palatinate War of Succession. The districts of Boxberg and Emmertsgrund are situated on a rise above Rohrbach, and have only really grown in the last 50 years.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Kirchheim</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The western Kirchheim is also an old settlement. Tombs of Merowinger from the early Stone Age (3500-1800 BCE) were found here. Kirchheim itself was first mentioned in 767 CE. It, too, suffered from the wars in the 17th Century and afterwards seemed to develop at breakneck speed. From a population of just 350 inhabitants in 1766, it had expanded to 2,000 by 1861. In 1920, it was incorporated into Heidelberg and is now home to some 15,000 inhabitants. Like Rohrbach, Kirchheim\''s new infrastructure presents a wide range of gastronomic and shopping possibilities.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Pfaffengrund & Wieblingen</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Pfaffengrund lies in northwestern Heidelberg and was part of the \"The Garden City Movement\" at the beginning of the 20th Century. This group\''s objective was to bring about low-priced housing options for working-class families and other socially disadvantaged citizens. With this background, the Pfaffengrund developed slowly but steadily in phases: 1920, 1934, and 1948 to 1953. The district now has a population of about 8,000.  Wieblingen lies between the highway and a bend of the Neckar River. Not only was a mammoth tooth found here, but also traces of human settlements dating back to the Stone Age. Wieblingen itself was first mentioned in a deed of donation in 767 CE. In the following centuries, the Wieblinger inhabitants made their living from agriculture and fishing, but this hamlet was plundered on several occasions and burnt down in the wars of the 17th Century. In the 19th Century, crafts workshops and industrial companies flourished in this area. The residential character changed from village-like structures to working-class dwellings, and like Pfaffengrund, a garden city with small houses was set up. Nowadays Wieblingen even has a specialty museum, the Bonsai-Museum, which is certainly worth a visit.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Neuenheim & Handschuhsheim</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Neuenheim is situated just north of Heidelberg\''s city center. Its origins date back to a Roman Castellum. Neuenheim was first mentioned in 765 CE and developed, like the hamlets around, into a settlement for peasants and fishermen. In the Thirty Years War and again in the French-Palatinate War of Succession, this region was completely destroyed. Later, in the 19th Century it became the favorite residential area of university professors and today one can still admire the beautiful art nouveau villas. With the beginning of the 20th Century, the university institutes for natural sciences were relocated from the town center to the close-by Neuenheimer Feld. Apart from two Max-Planck-Institutes, the German Cancer Research Center (DKFZ), the country\''s largest biomedical research institute is also based here. Furthermore, you will find a cluster of sports grounds, public swimming-pools, the Youth Hostel and last but not least, the Heidelberg Zoo and the Botanical Garden in this district.  Heidelberg\''s northernmost district is Handschuhsheim, first documented in 765 CE. Over many centuries, until 1600, it belonged to the aristocratic dynasty of Handschuhsheim, whose last heir lost his life in a tragic duel. The impressive Tiefburg, surrounded by a deep moat, once belonged to this dynasty. In the St. Vitus Church, the oldest church on Heidelberg grounds, several members of the family are buried in old and fascinating sepulchers. The Handschuhsheimer Schlößchen, and the many restaurants and pubs are definitely worth a visit. Heidelberg maintains a fair balance between cultural charm and industrial adaptation, and cherishes its well-deserved dynamic flair. As the popular local phrase goes, \"<em>Ich hab\'' mein Herz in Heidelberg verloren</em>\" (I lost my heart in Heidelberg) - visit this enchanting city of unlimited grace and fall in love with its enviable charisma.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
