 (2511,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Missoula\''s fabled past can be re-lived by journeying through its many historical museums. Stop by at the Montana Natural History Center to learn about the state\''s exemplary wildlife and ecosystem. The Fort Missoula Museum traces the journey of the historical city when it was first discovered, to the trying times of World War II. At the Philip L.Wright Zoological Museum in the University District, explore collections and specimens of various species of animals and birds.The Missoula Art Museum teases the city\''s artistic side with its avant-garde collection. The Monte Dolack Gallery with its nature-oriented paintings will hold you captivated, while the Dana Gallery is a stellar arthouse for fine art works.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals & Markets</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Missoula\''s small city corners erupt with cheer and festivity during the summer, when most festivals commence. The city is known for its soul-stirring music festivals, whether it is the unique International Choral Festival or the River City Roots Festival. Bibliophiles flock to the city during the city\''s biggest literary fiesta, the Montana Book Festival. The city is also famous for the Celtic Festival held at Caras Park, which celebrates the Celtic way of life and all its splendors, from music and food, to dance. Summers also herald market season in the city, with hordes of vendors taking their local bounty and wares to city streets. Some of the most popular markets in the city are the The Prairie Sisters - a range of spring vintage markets, the Missoula Farmers\'' Market, and the Clark Fork Market.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Concerts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Missoula hosts both large-scale musical bonanzas and home-grown bands with equal aplomb. If you fancy a listen, the historic Wilma Theater opens to a number of top-billed shows each month. The Adams Center at the University of Montana features a similar setting, with the added backdrop of Mount Sentinel. Forego the music biggies for some of the city\''s local bands at the Top Hat Lounge, which hosts live music in laidback digs. At the Dennison Theater, tune in to the dulcet notes of the Missoula Symphony Orchestra every season.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Outdoors</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Missoula is known above all, for its exquisite outdoor setting. One can see its beauty in amber-painted skies that refuse to dim, long-winded nature trails that end in breathtaking scenery, and alpine beauties that stand guard to the city. Its location in the Northern Rockies means that winters are not too harsh, opening up possibilities for outdoor recreation round the year. First off, warm up with a lesson in stand-up paddle boarding on Clark Fork River, or try surfing at the artificial Brennan\''s Wave in Downtown Missoula. Then, huff and puff your way up any of the mountain trails that lead to the summits of Mount Sentinel and Blue Mountain. These trails also offer opportunities for bike-riding. The Pattee Canyon Recreation area is great for horseback riding, while disc golf courses like the Linda Vista Golf Course are a short drive away. Explore the trout-swarmed waters of the river and try your hand at fly fishing.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2512,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown Missoula Historic District / Heart of Missoula</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Missoula inherits an endearing old-world charm from the state it is located in, and this percolates to the very heart of the city. Downtown Missoula is a riveting mix of the old and the new, with long-standing architectural fixtures mingling with the city\''s modern, booming face. The river forms a fitting backdrop to the slew of shops, restaurants, museums and galleries that dot Pine, Spruce and Alder streets. Downtown Missoula is bounded by railroad tracks to the north, May Street to the east, and extends all the way along the river to the end of Easy Street to its west. Some of the landmarks that you will see as you enter downtown include the Missoula Art Museum, the Wilma Building, the Millennium Building and the Florence Hotel. Its famous green space, Caras Park, is another beautiful landmark that comes alive in the fading light of the setting sun.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">University District (U-District)</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Located amid the foothills of Mount Sentinel and south of the Clark Fork river, the University of Montana is an iconic structure in the city. The university and its surrounding areas is a bit of a yuppie oasis, and is deemed as one of the most interesting neighborhoods to visit. The campus itself is home to several landmarks, including the Montana Museum of Art & Culture, the Adams Event Center, the Washington-Grizzly Stadium, and the Dennison Theater. Outside of campus, the University Golf Course and the scenic \''m\'' trail that leads to Mount Sentinel are a couple of the best spots for outdoor recreation.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">East Pine Historic District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This small, yet tony neighborhood to the north of the river is among the most picturesque neighborhoods in town. The East Pine Historic District is characterized by paved pathways, tree-lined streets and stately manors that can be traced back to the 19th and 20th Centuries. The district clearly housed several moneyed residents at one time, back when it was part of the City Beautiful movement. Featuring one sprawling estate after another, this district is reminiscent of an upper-middle class suburban neighborhood.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lewis and Clark / Southgate Triangle</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This homey neighborhood named after two of America\''s greatest explorers is bounded by the small Southgate Triangle. Lewis and Clark is recognized as the town\''s \''school neighborhood\'', and is home to Sentinel High School, Lewis & Clark School and Missoula College. The Playfair Park and Spartan Park are two local playgrounds for kids, while the neighboring Splash Montana water park offers fun days out for families. The Southgate Triangle is known to have an active shopping scene, with the Southgate Mall located centrally.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Lower Rattlesnake</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This oddly named neighborhood lies between Van Buren Street and Rattlesnake Drive. Characterized by a rustic atmosphere and absolutely no rattlesnakes, this is the place to come out to for some solitude. Greenough Park\''s dense coniferous trees make perfect homes for more than 100 bird species, while the Rattlesnake Creek is surrounded by an aura of serenity. But the real attraction here is the gigantic Mount Jumbo, replete with its elk-filled expanses and unending trails that snake their way to the top.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northside / Westside</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Both of these communities are well-known for their easy descent into Downtown Missoula rather than any distinct cultural flavor of their own. The neighborhoods are largely occupied by residential communities, although you may also see the occasional historic building around the corner. Northside is home to two cemeteries, the Missoula City Cemetery and St. Mary\''s Cemetery.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
