 (2530,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Theater maintains a firm place in Newport\''s nightlife. The Firehouse Theater breathes life into the former fire station and hosts rollicking evenings of improv and comedy. Thanks to its intimate size, there isn\''t a bad seat in the house! If you like your meals with a side of drama, then the Newport Playhouse & Cabaret Restaurant serves up heaps of fun. The over three-decade-old venue offers fantastic buffet dinners followed by a play and cabaret performance. For opera shows, one of the oldest opera houses in the county, the Newport Opera House hosts opera evenings in a grand historic space.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Newport also provides venues for moviegoers of all types. While Newport and surrounding towns have chain movie theaters, the Jane Pickens Theater is the best secret in Newport. Catch an independent or foreign film in old-fashioned theater surroundings complete with warm, buttery popcorn and retro-style seats.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\"></div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">and Outdoor Recreation</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">There is plenty of fun for sports fans of all kinds. Tennis fans may watch an evening match at the International Tennis Hall of Fame, which hosts exhibition tournaments. A great addition to Newport\''s sporting scene is the minor league baseball team, the Newport Gulls. The stadium is near the Visitors Center and within walking distance from downtown. You can also try your luck at the renovated Newport Grand Casino nearby.For outdoor enthusiasts, the Cliff Walk is an absolute must and the well-marked trail takes you past some of the town\''s most beautiful mansions while the ocean-lashed beach and rugged coastline form the perfect backdrop. Fort Adams State Park, with its harbor views and hiking trails, is another local favorite.You\''re never far from the ocean in Newport, and the area has a number of beautiful beaches for coastal activities. From lounging on First Beach and Second Beach to yachting on the harbor, you\''ll find plenty to do.Portsmouth\''s Green Animals Topiary Garden is sure to be a fun day for the whole family!</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals and Live Music</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Newport takes its music culture seriously. From early spring to late fall, the city hosts annual musical events including the Newport Folk Festival and Newport Jazz Week. For live music enthusiasts, Newport Blues Café offers nightly jazz or blues shows. During warmer months, several bars along the waterfront open their outdoor space to live bands that fill Thames Street with everything from folk to rock \''n\'' roll. Fort Adams State Park is host to several contemporary musical artists throughout the summer months. Less than an hour away in nearby Massachusetts, Gillette Stadium in Foxboro attracts popular big-name artists to the Newport scene.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Historical Landmarks</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Newport\''s Gilded Age mansions, many turned into house museums open to the public, offer a look at a bygone era and are well worth a visit. Visit the International Tennis Hall of Fame for a glimpse of America\''s love affair with this world sport. Art enthusiasts shouldn\''t miss the Newport Art Museum, a historic institution that has a great roster of changing exhibitions through the year. Those with an interest in visual arts and illustration will love a look at the collection of the National Museum of American Illustration that spotlights the \"Golden Age of American Illustration\".</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Find the best of New England shopping in Newport. From the lively waterfront district to the cobblestone streets bordered by quaint shops and independent boutiques and galleries, shopping here is a unique experience. Shop for antiques and interesting finds along Thames Street and Spring Street or browse the locally-owned shops along Bowen\''s Wharf and Bannister\''s Wharf.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2531,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Downtown and Historic District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The downtown area of Newport is considered the historic district with its surrounding residential areas and The Gilded Age mansions of Bellevue Avenue in the Cliff Walk section. Newport is composed of rows of colonial homes, shops and eateries, and beaches skirting the city. Historic sites and architectural wonders draw many visitors to Newport. One of the lesser known yet interesting architectural designs is the Old Stone Mill in the middle of Touro Park on Historic Hill. The Old Stone Mill is said to be one of the oldest structures in the United States. Many people believe the Mill dates back to the Norsemen, 900 years ago. It is also rumored to be a colonial windmill or the ruins of a building built over a previous structure. The Old Stone Mill lends mystery to history and is the subject of debate and controversy in Newport and elsewhere today.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Portsmouth</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The historic structures of Newport are valued not only for their architectural aspects, but also for the grace and beauty of landscape design surrounding the buildings, homes, museums and mansions. Green Animals Topiary Garden, a self-supporting estate of the Gilded Age with more than 800 topiary sculptures, is a perfect example of Victorian design.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cliff Walk</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Another estate, the most famous on the map in Newport, is The Breakers, located in the Cliff Walk area on Ochre Point Avenue. The Vanderbilt family fortune, attained through the advent of steamships and the New York Central Railroad, is displayed in all its grandeur at The Breakers, located in the Newport mansion district. The 16th-century, European palaces of Genoa and Turin inspired this 70-room villa, designed by architect Richard Morris Hunt. Today, along with other Newport homes in the mansion district, The Breakers is a National Historic Landmark. Many Newport music festivals are held on the lawns or inside the ballrooms or music rooms of these great estates. First Beach, also known as Easton\''s Beach provides a spectacular view of Newport\''s famous historical mansions. The luxurious The Chanler at Cliff Walk hotel is here and is ideal for romantic vacations and breathtaking views of the coast from its elegant rooms. At the end of the trail, you\''ll come to Bailey\''s Beach. This exclusive beach club caters to the town\''s upscale clientele and has been a posh locale since the town\''s Gilded Age.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ocean Drive</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">If you squirm in your seat during a violin concerto and would rather skip out to sea, head back to the yachting district. This district of Newport is known in yachting circles all over the world and is home to many private yacht clubs and their avid yachtsmen. You may even stumble upon a regatta or a sailing race as Newport sponsors several sail related events throughout the year. Sail aboard an America\''s Cup Yacht docked at the Newport Harbor Hotel & Marina at 49 America\''s Cup Avenue. On a sailing cruise you can view Newport\''s Point District, which is close to the harbor and the area of the Jamestown Bridge. See the smaller Colonial homes along the shore that Newport residents have restored. Sail past Newport parks, including Brenton Point State Park, and catch a glimpse of local fisherman trapping fresh seafood that might be your dinner. Learn why locals refer to their home as \"the island\" as you circle the coastline dotted with rocky beaches. Newport beaches, with their glistening sand naturally sculpted by nature, are some of the most beautiful in the world. Second Beach is located west of Third Beach, which runs to the mouth of the Sakonnet River. Third Beach, which faces the Narragansett Bay, is a favorite spot for locals to enjoy the passing sails and watch the sunset by the sea.Your explorations will help you develop an eye for the paths and promenades of Newport, its great structures and landscaped walks, pulled together by the natural shoreline of the city of Newport.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
