 (2614,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Most hotels provide some sort of rather sophisticated entertainment at their bars and restaurants, particularly during the busier winter season. The offerings run toward local artists, some quite good, playing piano, steel pans or guitar. Hotels occasionally offer West Indian-style events popular with tourists. Bolongo Bay Beach Resort & Villas holds a Wednesday Carnival Night with a steel band, fire eater, limbo show and dinner.  Many restaurants set up entertainment after dinner with offerings that run from sophisticated jazz to very loud rock and roll. Duffy\''s Love Shack sets the pace for a party hearty atmosphere with its outrageously named drinks and loud music.  The Greenhouse also attracts a young crowd for nightly music that runs from rock & roll to local music.  Molly Malone\''s in American Yacht Harbor at Red Hook always has Irish music playing. The Iggies Beach Bar & Grill in Bolongo is a great spot for theme nights and live music nights along the waterfront, while the Hull Bay Hideaway is a clandestine gem accessible via Route 37. The Caribbean Saloon Steakhouse & Bar in Red Hook is one of the most popular fixtures on Vessup Bay.  Frenchtown is the place to stroll from bar to bar for eclectic late night entertainment. The hot spots seem to come and go, but there is always something happening.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performances</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Reichhold Center for the Arts on the University of the Virgin Islands is the island\''s only place for major performances. Imported symphonies, ballet, and repertory companies join homegrown theater and dance groups in staging performances. The Pistarkle Theater, in the Tillett Gardens art complex, holds performances throughout the year.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Carnival, held every year, is the island\''s premier event. Thousands of islanders living abroad return home for this event, so make sure to reserve your hotel early if you plan to attend. The event culminates with a parade by troupes and floats of people wearing fanciful costumes.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art & Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">With little to entertain them in the way of formal events, residents gather at local galleries and shops whenever an artist unveils a new collection. Spots like the Camille Pissarro Gallery are known for these events. Wine, cheese, conversation and a chance to meet the locals are the reasons to attend. While St Thomas is not largely known for its museums, there are a handful spread across the island that appeal to curious visitors. The Virgin Islands Children\''s Museum in Charlotte Amalie\''s historic heart is a good place to take family, and is full of interactive exhibits and scientific displays. <font color=\"#0000ff\">T</font><font color=\"#0000ff\">h</font>e St Thomas Historical Trust Museum waxes eloquent about the island\''s rich heritage and culture, and the Pirates Treasure Museum in Havensight is a priceless repository consisting of shipwrecked treasures and artifacts that were once lost to the sea. Other small museums include the Weibel Museum and the Haagensen House in Charlotte Amalie, a restored historic house that once belonged to a Danish banker.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A duty-free shopping haven that has held its status since 1724, the island is teeming with a multitude of shops that cater to avid shoppers and cruise passengers who scour the port for relatively less expensive jewelry and other luxury items. Downtown Charlotte Amalie and the Main Street near Fort Christian is where the most dazzling shopping boutiques lie. Peppered with a mix of jewelry shops, perfume stores, branded luxury accessories and specialty stores, this area is a shoppers\'' paradise. Not far away is Havensight Mall, another retail landmark near the cruise ship port that is brimming with duty-free stores. Yacht Haven Grande, a stunning avenue for luxury shops sits amid Charlotte Amalie and Havensight, and is home to more than 40 designer stores and boutiques.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Horse racing at Clinton Phipps Racetrack provides gathers a crowd every other Sunday. While the crowd is mostly local, a smattering of tourists also place bets.  School fields and Emile Griffith Park, located along Route 30 in Charlotte Amalie, often see local teams play baseball. Avid fans are always welcome to sit in the stands.  The St Thomas International Regatta is the island\''s premier sailboat race event with competitors coming in from all over the Caribbean. All are welcome to view the festivities that ensue at the St. Thomas Yacht Club.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2615,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Charlotte Amalie</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The island\''s main town, Charlotte Amalie, bustles like any small city with vacationers shopping and residents heading off to work. Traffic can pile up along the waterfront Route 30, called Veterans Drive, and the city\''s main parking lot adjacent to Fort Christian is often filled. Despite the surface buzz, it is easy to find quiet pockets away from Charlotte Amalie and other busy areas. At the heart of Charlotte Amalie is Fort Christian, a settlement that is also home to the eponymous 17th-century red-brick fort built by Danish settlers. The oldest structure in the U.S. Virgin Islands, the fort is surrounded by a bevy of historical landmarks that bring alive the splendid past of the settlement. From the legendary 99 steps that lead to the top of Blackbeard\''s Castle, a watchtower from the same period, to the Government House and the Emancipation Gardens and memorial that stand as a symbolic testament to the abolition of slavery, Charlotte Amalie\''s Fort Christian area is a sightseeing complex in itself.  The Main Street, a vibrant thoroughfare stretching through Downtown Charlotte Amalie is a paradise for shopping, packed with a multitude of duty-free shops and specialty boutiques. The accommodations options nearby are many. Luxury hotels and condominium complexes line the beaches on the island\''s eastern end. Historic hotels and inns are tucked into Charlotte Amalie\''s back streets. Cozy guest houses dot the hills above Charlotte Amalie Harbor and vacation villas pepper many exclusive residential neighborhoods.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Frenchtown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This settlement, located to the west of the island\''s capital can be reached by driving via Veterans Drive, along the waterfront. Once here, don\''t be thrown by the colloquial Norman-French dialect that is still used here by locals. Relatively less safer than the island\''s capital, there isn\''t much to do here, other than visit the miscellany of unique bars and restaurants that line its waterfront streets. The Hassel Island Historic District, located in the Caribbean Sea, offers a handful of hiking and kayaking tours.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West End</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Hotel visitors and guests heading for a sailboat charter usually arrive at the modern Cyril E. King Airport, located at the western end of the island. Facing Lindbergh and Brewers Bay, the West End of St Thomas is lined with a dazzling array of villas, resorts and hotels. The Brewers Bay Beach is a favorite sand-lined attraction here, while the Reichhold Center for the Arts and the University of the Virgin Islands are located nearby.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Havensight</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Boasting one of the busiest cruise ship ports in the world, Havensight offers a wide range of water-sports in its sun-dappled location along Long Bay. A variety of marine excursions, scuba diving, snorkeling and jet-skiing adventures can be availed here.  While Charlotte Amalie is the main shopping area, several shopping areas with tourist-oriented shops are now spread out all across the island. Havensight Mall, the community\''s main retail landmark, is home to over 60 shops and boutiques. For more kicks, the SkyRide to Paradise Point offers spectacular gondola rides that soar 700 feet (213 meters) above ground to offer sweeping views of the entire island.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Water Island</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This island offers a vast variety of activities. Spend the day snorkeling, sunning or snoozing at a crystal clear cove ringed with a white sandy beach and palm trees, head down to the briny deep on a Scuba excursion, set sail to an offshore island, play a round at Mahogany Run Golf Course, or visit any of the historic sites in the main town of Charlotte Amalie and around the island. Numerous tour and water-oriented excursions are popular with hotel guests as well as cruise ship passengers.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Northside</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A trip around the island with a taxi driver or in your rental car should include stops at the palm-fringed Magens Bay Beach, the island\''s most popular. You will find changing rooms, water sports rentals, and restaurants in addition to clear blue water and lovely white sand. As you travel around the island, you will see gorgeous views at nearly every turn in the road. Drake\''s Seat, where Sir Francis Drake reportedly checked on his fleet, and the busy Mountain Top are especially popular viewpoints.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
