 (2644,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums and Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Apart from its inextricable association with history, Williamsburg is also surprisingly strewn with a range of art museums and galleries. From gems like the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum that enthralls visitors with a rich collection of American folk art, to the DeWitt Wallace Decorative Arts Museum that balances both British and American decorative artwork collections from the 17th through the 19th centuries, Williamsburg has much to offer. Modern art lovers will adore the exhibitions at the Muscarelle Museum of Art. On Richmond Road, the Virginia Musical Museum is a unique repository containing musical instruments and related objects from over 40 years ago. Williamsburg is also known for its historic mansions and erstwhile stately homes that now function as museums, including the famous Governor\''s Palace, Bassett Hall and the Peyton Randolph House. A number of galleries can also be found in Williamsburg. The award-winning Williamsburg Art Gallery, an award-winning institution is located in Colonial Williamsburg\''s Merchants Square. The Williamsburg Contemporary Art Center and the Linda Matney Fine Art Gallery are other important purveyors of art in the city.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Historical Attractions</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">As you might suspect, the Williamsburg area is jam-packed with sites of historical interest. Both Williamsburg and Jamestown have built recreations of colonial settlements. Colonial Williamsburg offers several walking tours to get you acquainted with its stories, as well as period homes, artisans, and even a trial reenactment at the courthouse. Historic Jamestown is the actual archaeological dig of the original settlement, with the found artifacts on display. Park rangers are happy to explain the history of the site. Adjacent to the excavation is Jamestown Settlement, which is a recreation of the settlement that is being excavated. The settlement includes actors who show everyday life in Jamestown, a Powhatan village, and replicas of the ships used to sail from England.  The Yorktown Victory Center is another recreation of colonial times, this time focusing on the battle of Yorktown, which won the Revolutionary War. Actors here demonstration colonial wartime life, and in separate areas, children can make woodblock prints while parents learn to spin flax into thread. If the battle scenes at Yorktown Victory Center pique your interest, you might also want to visit the U.S. Army Transportation Museum in Fort Eustis. Admission is free, and the museum teaches the public about the evolution of Army vehicles from colonial times to the present.  Plantation life was a big part of Colonial America and this is reflected in the many restored plantations that are open to visitors. Two of these are the Sherwood Forest Plantation, which was home to former president John Tyler, and Shirley Plantation, which was built in 1613 and is the oldest plantation in Virginia.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Bars & Pubs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Fun in Williamsburg doesn\''t end after dark. There are plenty of pubs that cater to students and music lovers, some of which are historically themed. Josiah Chowning\''s Tavern, for example, invites visitors to participate in its Gambols, games and songs that were typical of 18th century taverns. The Cogan\''s Deli & Sports Pub, another local gem, combines live music, cocktails, and an atmospheric ambiance that makes it one of the most popular pubs in the city. Corner Pocket is a bar, restaurant, and music venue and a great place to shoot pool. It\''s also a great way to end a day touring Colonial Williamsburg as it is nearby. Pitcher\''s Sports Bar is just what it sounds like and can be a very relaxing environment if you like sports and beer. Yorktown Pub in, you guessed it, Yorktown is popular with the locals and it has great food and a great location, overlooking the water.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts & Cinemas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Williamsburg offers both contemporary films and live theater. For new films, check out Regal New Town Cinemas 12, a large movie theater, considering the size of the town it\''s in. For more upscale charm, visit the Kimball Theater, a 1933 playhouse available for private parties and screenings. The Kimball Theater is also the proud home of the Williamsburg Youth Orchestra, the Williamsburg Symphony Orchestra, and the Williamsburg Classic Swing Orchestra. Kaplan Arena, an indoor arena at the William and Mary Hall is favored for both athletic events and large-scale concerts. In the past, it has seen performers like Nirvana, Kendrick Lamar, Bruce Springsteen and the Beach Boys perform on stage. Williamsburg\''s top-notch Comedy Club also presents a riveting line-up of seasoned comedians who perform at various venues across the city. The Williamsburg Dinner Theatre on Richmond Road also performs to a full crowd.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Seasonal festivals almost outnumber stationary places of business in the Williamsburg area. Again because of its historical significance, dates of historical import are celebrated here more than any other location. For example, Independence Day at Colonial Williamsburg is not like any other Independence Day celebration. The day includes a fife and drum march, a read of the Declaration of Independence, and at night, an extraordinary fireworks display. Jamestown Landing Day in the nearby settlement is similar in that it celebrates another day in history: May 13, 1607, when the first English settlers arrived at what they would call Jamestown. The day includes sailing demonstrations and historical re-enactments of contact between English and Native. Another re-enactment that will interest history lovers is Military Through the Ages, an event performed at the Jamestown Settlement in which actors wear period uniforms and re-enact battles from the Revolutionary War and more modern wars. Bacon\''s Rebellion Night Walking Tour may be the most exciting of the seasonal events as it includes a mock burning commemorating the 1676 burning of Jamestown Francis Bacon orchestrated to protest England\''s rule. Brothers in Arms, which includes a parade and various presentations, celebrates African American soldiers and their role in wars from the Revolutionary War to World War II.  Non military festivals include the Virginia Shakespeare Festival, a month-long festival that celebrates Shakespeare\''s work and takes place at the College of William and Mary. The West Point Crab Festival includes three separate parades, river cruises, music, and a fireworks show over the river after sunset.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (2645,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Colonial Williamsburg/Williamsburg Historic District</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Williamsburg is best known for its colonial charm. Colonial Williamsburg is one of the city\''s main points of interest and features an 18th-century town complete with actors to create one of the largest living history museums in the world. Visitors can interact with the townspeople to become a part of history. Numerous Colonial Revival mansions and structures that span the 17th and 19th centuries also dot its historic streets, while there are a few reconstructed buildings as well. Among the most notable buildings are landmarks like the the Capitol, the original building which housed the House of Burgesses of the Colony of Virginia, the stately Governor\''s Palace dating back to the 18th Century, and the Raleigh Tavern, a place of congregation that now functions as a museum. Other places of interest are the Randolph House, the Courthouse, and the Bruton Parish Church.  Besides the institutional Raleigh Tavern, Colonial Williamsburg also has several other restaurants and taverns serving up olden day fare, adding to the complete experience.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">New Town</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">This charming New Town is less touristy than the rest of the city. Filled with conveniences, New Town is a great place for shopping, dining, or catching a movie. A slew of nearly 170 shops, plenty of restaurants and cafes line New Town Avenue and Courthouse Street. Some of the more refined dining options here include the Opus 9 Steakhouse and Bonefish Grill. Many services for residents, such as banks, fitness centers, and real estate agencies are also located in New Town.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">William & Mary</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A large part of Williamsburg belongs to the College of William and Mary located just south of New Town and to the west of downtown Williamsburg. This historic college which forms the centerpiece of this iconic district was founded in 1693, and is regarded the second-oldest university in the United States. Keeping the town young, the university is a first rate institute full of cultural offerings. The campus and surrounding areas that are spread out around the university are mostly teeming with institutional complexes, arenas, halls and college venues, intermittently speckled with dining and shopping options. The idyllic Crim Dell bridge, a wooden bridge laid out near the college campus, spans the eponymous pond, and is also surrounded by several myths and urban legends. Other prominent landmarks on and around the campus include the Muscarelle Museum of Art and the Williamsburg Library.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Surrounding Areas</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Beyond colonial happenings and suburban offerings, Williamsburg also has a plethora of unique attractions drawing both locals and tourists just outside the city center. Amusement park Busch Gardens and Water Country USA, a water park, are located in Williamsburg and are incredible attractions for wholesome family fun. To its north are also shopping outlet centers such as Williamsburg Prime Outlets, as well as Williamsburg Pottery which manufactures and sells handmade salt glaze pottery.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Jamestown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Site of the first permanent English settlement in North America, Jamestown today is a historical site that provides numerous ways to learn about the past. There are no permanent residents in Jamestown, although during the day it is bustling with colorful colonial characters and tourists from all over the world. The two main Jamestown attractions are both centered around the town\''s rich history. Jamestown Settlement is a recreation of an English fort, a Native American village, and the ships that used to sail to the New World. Also at Jamestown is Historic Jamestown, the actual site of the original colony featuring archaeological digs and glass blowing.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Yorktown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A tiny town with less than 300 inhabitants, Yorktown is primarily known for the part it played in the Revolutionary and Civil Wars. Historic Yorktown contains buildings dating back to the colonial era, as well as quaint shops, cafes and restaurants. See Yorktown Battlefield where General Cornwallis surrendered to General Washington and the Yorktown National Cemetery where hundreds of Civil War soldiers are buried.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
