 (3023,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Beaches</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">A good day on Martha\''s Vineyard often means a good day at the Island beaches—a day of sunbathing, beachcombing, maybe some surfing. The Vineyard is blessed with beaches of every variety. Those suited for families with small children tend to lie on the Nantucket Sound where the waves are minimal and the water is warm. More adventurous swimmers should make their way to the ocean beaches on the south side of the island. Hikers, on the other hand, will find that some of the most magnificent views of the Island can be had from Gay Head, now officially referred to as Aquinnah.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">The Outdoors</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">After a few days of relaxing on the beach, once you\''re refreshed and recharged, don\''t be surprised if you\''re taken over by an unspoken desire to hike, watch birds, perhaps even canoe or ride out into the sunset, inspired by the spectacular scenery of this quaint, colonial isle. The good folks at the Trustees of the Reservation understand this urge and arrange tame yet beautiful excursions into the rough country of the Vineyard. Cape Poge Wildlife Refuge and Wasque Reservation (East Shore), which is run by the Trustees, is one such piece of wilderness to explore. Think pristine barrier beaches, salt marshes and more. Embark on one of the daily, guided 3-hour \"safaris,\" venture out on foot, set out on a guided canoe trip. The Trustees also arrange twice daily fishing trips that are quite popular. If bird watching is more to your liking, head to Felix Neck Wildlife Sanctuary, which is operated by the Mass Audobon Society. For a destination point that is more beach-centric head to Long Point Wildlife Refuge Beach on the island\''s south shore. Pristine beaches that go on for miles in either direction make for a rewarding hike and close encounters with native wildlife. Once the Vineyard\''s land-based wilderness areas have been sufficiently explored, head to the ocean for water sports of every stripe. One of the most popular pursuits on the Vineyard for visitors and residents alike is sailing.  Edgartown is home to the Edgartown Yacht Club, which each year hosts the Edgartown Regatta. Those who thrill at the high drama of a race on the seas should be sure to be on Island for this annual event. Other smaller races are held here throughout the season. For sailing lessons, call or visit the Island Sailing Schools of Martha\''s Vineyard, Inc. to schedule a class or to sign up to participate in sailing activities. The school offers instruction for all levels and age groups. For those who\''d rather take to the seas than watch the action from the shore, but do not wish to commandeer their own sailboat, sailing and yacht charters are the best alternative. Catamaran Arabella is one such charter known to provide romantic sailing experiences around the Vineyard.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">During the height of the summer season, a lively vibe prevails over certain sectors of the Island, most notably in and around Oak Bluffs and Edgartown. After all, even the most devoted beachcomber or sailor likes to top off their day of outdoorsy pursuits with a lovely nightcap overlooking the harbor. At the end of the day, the Martha\''s Vineyard restaurant and bar scene is often what passes for nightlife. Head to the harbor and grab a seat outside with friends at watering holes such as the Newes from America Pub in Edgartown. Or, if you\''re yearning for a bit of culture, check out the offerings at the Vineyard Playhouse. Oak Bluffs is one of the only two towns on the Island that has a significant after-dark scene. Although you can\''t go as far as to call it a \"club scene,\" there are a few places where singles can mix it up on the dance floor or at the bar. Lola\''s is a favorite among locals and visitors alike for live music and dancing. Offshore Ale Co is another hotspot, serving delicious microbrews, while the Loft is a great place to hang out with friends and battle it out over shuffleboard, pool and darts or dance the night away to DJs spinning the latest tunes.Edgartown boasts a fairly diverse nightlife as well that\''s centered mainly around the city\''s bars. Drop by Alchemy for some of the best cocktails to be had on the island, or head to the Port Hunter for live music. Other popular nighttime hangouts include the Newes From America Pub, Seafood Shanty and The Wharf.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Museums & Art Galleries</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Martha\''s Vineyard may not have a particularly large cache of museums to explore, but those that do call this island home offer a mesmerizing glimpse into the depths of its history, art and culture, At the top of the list is the Martha\''s Vineyard Museum in Edgartown, a haven for history buffs looking to get to know the island better. Built in 1672, the Vincent House Museum, also in Edgartown, is the island\''s oldest residence and is now open to visitors for a glimpse into life on the island over four centuries. The Cottage Museum in Oak Bluffs is another historic home that now serves as a museum, complete with period furniture and antiques.Those who enjoy the fine arts will find plenty to keep them busy. The island is home to over 50 fine galleries that showcase regional crafts, contemporary pieces and fine art. The Old Sculpin Gallery is the abode of the Martha\''s Vineyard Art Association and is over 240 years old, while the Eisenhauer Gallery showcases artwork from across the world. Other fine choices include the North Water Street Gallery, the Granary and the Gallery Josephine.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Martha\''s Vineyard Performing Arts Center, in Vineyard Haven, is the island\''s premier venue for the performing arts. The center offers a diverse program of dance, music and drama, alongside educational activities for the community. Also in Vineyard Haven, the Vineyard Playhouse is a historic, 19th Century black box theater that hosts professional theatrical productions.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Shopping</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Although devoid of shopping malls and plazas, Martha\''s Vineyard is replete with antique stores specializing in maritime treasures, galleries stocked with artwork by regional and nationally recognized artists, boutiques selling one-of-a-kind wares, and shops brimming with island-made goodies. At Aquinnah Cliffs, shops owned by the Wampanoag Tribe offer authentic Native American crafts.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
 (3024,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Edgartown</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Edgartown was once a large whaling community that boomed in the late 18th Century and early 19th Century. Today it is a popular destination for its many historic homes, many of which once belonged to famous sea captains. The Old Whaling Church is the oldest in Edgartown. There are also many charming bed and breakfasts and restaurants such as the Seafood Shanty in this area.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Oak Bluffs</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Oak Bluffs was once called \"Cottage City,\" and it\''s easy to see why, with its many quaint, homes and lodging options, like the Dockside Inn. Events for the whole family include fireworks at Ocean Park and The Annual Harbor Festival held in mid-June.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Vineyard Haven</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Vineyard Haven is Martha\''s Vineyard main harbor for both imports and exports. This is a popular destination for those looking to spend the summer away from home. You\''ll find Vineyard Playhouse and the Felix Neck Wildlife Sanctuary here. The list of accommodation options is long, with Hanover House and Crocker House Inn standing out among some of the best.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Aquinnah</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The little town of Aquinnah rests upon the westernmost tip of the island, a modest community of only about 400 year-round residents and the home of the island\''s only federally recognized Native American Tribe - the Wampanoag. The town is best known as the site of the vividly-hued, Gay Head Cliffs and the historic Gay Head Lighthouse.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">West Tisbury</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Split from the town of Tisbury in 1892, the old New England folk of West Tisbury boast a fiercely independent character. The town has retained much of its rural charm, its streets adorned with historic homes and other noteworthy attractions. The most famed of these are Alley\''s General Store, the Field Gallery and Sculpture Garden, and the Grange Hall. The town also hosts the annual fair of the Martha\''s Vineyard Agricultural Society.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Chilmark and Menemsha</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Chilmark and Menemsha are located at the southern tip of Martha\''s Vineyard, along the coast. Like many towns on the island, Chilmark was once a fishing village. Visitors come here to enjoy the quiet countryside and rough beaches. Menemsha remains a fishing community today. Its sleepy atmosphere is perfect for those looking to get away from the hustle and bustle of city life. Here you\''ll find lighthouses, tiny shops, cafes and secluded cottages, all there for your exploration.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
