 (3063,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Winter Sports</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">During the winter months, there is no comparison to the awe-inspiring beauty of the snow-clad mountains of Vail and the promise of a day on the slopes afforded by the pristine power. By the end of November, lines begin to grow by the ski lifts of Vail, as the mountains come alive with skiers and snowboarders carving a path down the slopes. The numerous ski resorts that surround the mountain town, such as the Vail Marriott Mountain Resort, begin to fill up, and for good reason. There are competitions and contests to compete in and numerous trails to explore.The American Ski Classic takes place every March and turns the Vail mountains into celebrity slopes. Don\''t be surprised if you happen to spot legends like Billy Kid and Franz Klamer, or stars like Kelsey Grammer and Gloria Estefan. If you\''re a snowboarder who isn\''t really excited by \"two-planking\" festivities, then check out The Session, - a snowboard competition and party on the slopes of Vail. Today\''s top riders bust out high-flying tricks while live music and delicious food are accompaniments that make this one of Vail\''s must-see events.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Festivals</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Vail kicks off ski-season with the Snow Daze, an annual event that brings headlining musicians, street parties, on-snow events, great food and good times to the mountain. Although Vail is best known for its wealth of outdoor pursuits and related events, the town also hosts a variety of festivals that celebrate music, dance and film. The Jazz Festival impresses with its smooth musical stylings while classical music fans greatly anticipate the Bravo! Music Festival for six weeks of open-air concerts. Every year the Vail International Dance Festival twirls its way into the area for several weeks of classic and contemporary performances by well-known dance ensembles, such as the Paris Opera Ballet and Dance Cuba! The Vail Film Festival is another acclaimed event -a four-day cinematic extravaganza that incorporates feature films, shorts, documentaries, and student films. In October, Vail hosts its own Oktoberfest with live music, festivities and endless pints of beer.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Cinema</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">For cinema buffs, Vail offers two fabulous theaters. While the historic Riverwalk Theater in Edward screens first-run films in an old-world setting, the Cine Bistro at Solaris promises a luxury cinematic experience with gourmet, in-theater dining, delicious cocktails and fine wine served at your seat.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Art Galleries & Museums</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Vail Village has some great little galleries and museums to entertain its visitors when they are not on the ski slopes. You\''ll find nature inspired hand-made jewelry at the J. Cotter Gallery, while Raitman displays contemporary fine art.A world-renown destination for skiers, there could be no better location for the Colorado Ski Museum than the town of Vail. Take a walk through the hallways of this museum for a deeper understanding of how the Vail Valley transformed from its humble beginnings as a sheep farm to the ski Mecca it is today.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Other Outdoor Activities</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Even when the snow melts in Vail, the smiles don\''t, and the warm sunny days bring out some of the best, with activities ranging from river-rafting to golf. There are plenty of things to see and do around Vail, as it is truly an all-season town. There are a number of skilled tour guides in Vail that can show you the true meaning of the great outdoors. No matter what your skill level or experience, Lakota River Guides will take you on a river rafting trip that is sure to be rewarding. If you\''re looking for more than just a rafting adventure, consider a tour with Nova Guides. These tours will take you on unforgettable excursions that can include everything from dog sledding, snowmobiling and river fishing, to off-road adventures aboard jeeps and ATVs.In the spring, the rivers around Vail begin to rise and fly-fishing is at its best. Pack your waders and head out to the many local streams and rivers to catch some of those elusive trout.Vail is also home to world-class golf courses that include the Cotton Ranch Golf Club, and the Eagle Ranch Golf Club.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Nightlife</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Long after the lifts have closed for the day and the stragglers have called it a day, the night is just beginning for Vail\''s bars and nightclubs. Apres-ski spots range from the congenial Bart & Yeti\''s and the lively Red Lion to the more cultured Pepi\''s, while connoisseurs of fine spirits should definitely check out 10th Mountain. There\''s the Root & Flower for fine wine and inventive cocktails, and the Vail Brewing Company for craft beer. For a more upscale evening, head to Remedy at the Four Seasons and enjoy uninterrupted mountain views as you sip on your drink. Meanwhile, the Shakedown Bar is the place to be for live music.</div><h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Performing Arts</h3><div class=\"WorldGuide\">Vail\''s performing arts scene is an impressive one for a town that\''s obsessed with the outdoors, with plenty to keep you entertained after a day on the slopes. The Vail Performing Arts Academy hosts a variety of shows across venues in Vail throughout the year, with a leaning towards more youth-oriented programs, while the Vilar Performing Arts Center offers a more diverse line-up of dance recitals, concerts and theatrical plays. The Gerald R Ford Amphitheater is another premier venue for the performing arts - an outdoor arena for live music and summertime spectacles.</div><br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
