 (3161,'<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Centro Storico &amp; Brera</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">The Historical Center incorporates the fashion district (called the<em> Quadrilatero d\''oro</em>), Castello Sforzesco, the glorious Piazza della Scala, the inviting neighborhood of Brera, and other areas of historical and commercial interest. There is always plenty to do; there are many excellent restaurants and bars within walking distance of each other, and an evening stroll through this area in summer is absolute bliss. This is where some of the city\''s most revered historical landmarks and attractions are found, including the iconic Duomo, the Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II - the world\''s oldest shopping mall - and Teatro alla Scala.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\"><br><br>Corso Buenos Aires</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Northeast of the center, Corso Venezia and its intersecting roads are lined with noble families\'' palaces; in some cases, these are still used as residences, in others, they have been converted into luxury offices. The gardens of Porta Venezia make up a small, enclosed park, which is one of the most beautiful in Milan. Further north, is Corso Buenos Aires; one of the largest commercial main roads, it is easy to reach and is well-served by the metro. The neighborhood has a cosmopolitan vibe, and is home to several ethnic restaurants that exemplify its multicultural flavor.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Magenta</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Corso Magenta begins at Porta Magenta and leads into the heart of this locale. This <em>corso</em> is \"healthy and wealthy\"; one half has hardly any shops, but many gorgeous <em>palazzi</em> with exquisite, hidden gardens, while the other half has a multitude of shops, some of which are very prestigious. There are also several interesting churches and museums in this area. The <em>corso </em>is well served by public transport, and is often chock-a-bloc with traffic with few parking spaces during the day, but becomes a great deal more peaceful at night.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Ticinese-Navigli</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Southwest of the city center stands the Ticinese-Navigli area, which is a mixture of old and new. Many of the original residents still live in Ticinese and there are many <em>case di ringhiera</em> - apartments with wrought-iron balconies that face inwards. Once the 20th-century abode of blue-collar employees, these renovated apartments now house architects, artists, fashion designers <em>et al</em>. This area is full of bars and shops selling new and vintage clothes, antiques, furniture, as well as basic necessities.  <br><br>The <em>Navigli</em>, the city\''s canal system, includes the Naviglio Grande and the Naviglio Pavese. A short way down the Naviglio Pavese is Via Chiesa Rossa, shaped by the wave of immigrants who settled here in the 1950s and 1960s. The area by the Navigli teems with nightclubs, bars, and pubs, forever bustling with an exuberant energy, especially during the summertime. The Naviglio leads to the <em>autostrada</em>, or highway, to Genova. The Assago complex, where the Datchforum is situated, can be seen on the A7 highway.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Amendola-Fiera &amp; San Siro</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Amendola-Fiera is a district that is famous for its exhibitions and trade fairs. This is a residential area as well, with many tree-lined streets and tall <em>palazzi</em>, or large residential buildings. Most of these were constructed post 1930, and are still in good condition. San Siro is famous for its Stadio San Siro football ground, an important spot for fans of the AC Milan team.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Porta Vittoria &amp; Porta Romana</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Vittoria is a popular residential area that has a working/middle-class feel. Viale Lazio is predominantly made up of residential, leafy avenues; Corso Lodi reverberates with the hum of commercial activity; Viale Umbria is residential and Corso XXII Marzo is filled with shops. Some fashion houses have their headquarters in Vittoria, around Viale Umbria and Corso Lodi. There is still some industrial activity to the east, on Viale Mugello and towards Viale Molise (the large complex of Macello Comunale) and further out, while nearby is the famous wholesale market, Mercato Ortofrutticolo. Further east, between Forlanini\''s verdant park and Taliedo (heading towards Linate Airport), is the <em>Idroscalo</em>, a large dock filled with water where you can swim, sunbathe, and sail.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Città Studi</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">Città Studi is located in the east of Milan and as the name suggests, is the University district, home to the Polytechnic, and several chemistry, biology and pharmaceutical departments. Many of the buildings here were constructed in the 1920s, 1930s and 1940s and the overall feel is that of a charming residential area with trees on every street.</div>\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"WorldGuide\">Isola</h3>\r\n<div class=\"WorldGuide\">To the north of the city lies Isola, located just behind the Stazione Centrale, other zones in the vicinity are home to large hospital complexes, such as Ospedale Maggiore di Milano Policlinico and CTO.</div>\r\n\r\n<br><div class=\"FodorsCopyright\">&copy; Cityseeker</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
